<SLUG> BC-SKATE-USTITLE-KWAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN COMES THROUGH FOR ANOTHER CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ This time, she had her game face on. This time,
Michelle Kwan was fighting for her competitive life against the
orthodontic generation, and she knew it. So she shrugged off
another fall, pulled herself back together, and won the US women's
figure skating title for the fourth time in five years Saturday
night before 15,435 inside Gund Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all business today, concentrated and centered,'' said
the 19-year-old Kwan after climbing out of third place to outpoint
15-year-old Sasha Cohen and 14-year-old Sarah Hughes. ``I came into
the ring determined. I said, `Michelle, you've got something to do;
do it. Don't fool around on the ice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan had been in serious trouble after falling on a simple
triple toe loop toward the end of Friday's short program. Hughes,
with her two triple-triple jump combinations, had a tougher long
program. And Cohen, the leader going into the evening, had an
impressive blend of skill and artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Had one of them skated cleanly, she might have knocked off the
two-time world champion, who hasn't skated without error for an
entire major event since the 1998 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But Hughes, a ninth-grader from Great Neck, N.Y., singled the
back end of her triple toe-triple loop combo, fell on a triple
salchow 10 seconds from the end, and finished third. ``I had a
little trouble at the end; that was obvious,'' said Hughes, who
still made the team for next month's world championships in France.
``I fought through the program and tried to make every moment
count. If I didn't, I would regret it later.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen seemed headed to a flawless outing after landing a pair of
triple-double combinations early on. With 20 seconds left in her
four-minute program, Cohen's only bobble had been a double-footed
triple lutz. Then, out of nowhere, she splattered her triple toe
and ended up second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the way I skated, but disappointed with the
last jump,'' said Cohen, who is technically too young to compete in
the world championships but can earn a ticket if she wins a medal
at next month's world junior event. ``But I really don't think I
would have won even if I had landed it. Michelle is a world and
Olympic skater, and she has a reputation that I don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's fall left her with only five triples, one fewer than
Kwan. That, plus Kwan's more nuanced artistry and the extra triple
toe she tossed in, was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   It was a slender, shaky difference, though, and Kwan knew it.
The juniors who once gazed at her in awe have drawn even, and there
are more on the way. Jennifer Kirk, the 15-year-old rookie from
Newton, Mass., and the Skating Club of Boston, finished sixth in
the long program and seventh overall. And Deanna Stellato, jumping
up from novices, was ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan survived because her immature rivals slipped. Next year,
they might stand tall. ``I really feel I have to up the ante,'' she
said. ``There's a lot of skaters doing triple-triples, and I feel
I've got to do one of them. Or maybe two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two will probably be the opening bid at the FleetCenter. And
more people will be drawing cards at the table. ``We know that
Michelle is a wonderful champion, the premiere skater, but she's
being challenged by the youth of America,'' said John Nicks, who
coaches Cohen. ``It's been the tradition of American ladies'
skating that the champion never rests easy on her throne.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
