<HEADLINE>
US SHUTS DOWN HAITI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The US national team had only a handful of supporters at
the Orange Bowl to witness its 3-0 victory over Haiti Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, much of Little Haiti, plus busloads of immigrants
from Boston, Montreal, New York _ and Rene Preval, the president of
the Republic of Haiti _ created a festive atmosphere in the kickoff
game of the Gold Cup. The Haiti team has skill and style, but lacks
the experience to duplicate the exploits of its coach, Emmanuel
Sanon, who helped Haiti qualify for its only World Cup final in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to it because we've played a lot of games in LA
and on the East Coast where the crowd is like that,'' said US
striker Eric Wynalda, who scored his 34th international goal on a
second-half penalty. ``It's not like it hurts our feelings or
anything. This is the only time Haitian-Americans have a chance to
see their team play in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   US supporters will likely again be in the minority in
Wednesday's game against Peru.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States finally seems capable of winning over
critics and hyphenated American soccer fans. The team performed
with poise, thanks to the midfield composure of Claudio Reyna. It
was able to set the tempo, retain possession, vary the speed of the
game. The efficiency of the US midfield and the tenacity of the
defending prevented Haiti from establishing a rhythm and enabled
Eddie Lewis to find space on the left flank, and Wynalda, Cobi
Jones, and Jovan Kirovski to maneuver through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Kirovski scored in the 18th minute, heading off the underside of
the crossbar after Wynalda centered a Reyna cross.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna was taken down in the penalty area in the 55th minute, and
Wynalda blasted the penalty past goalkeeper Didier Menard.
</P>
<P>
   Jones scored a last-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honor to play against the US, which is one of the
most improved and best teams in the world now, especially with
thousands of Haitians here,'' forward Sebastien Vorbe said. ``It is
going to take a while for us to get to the level we want to be at.
We need a lot of big games but it is hard to find big games because
teams are booked and they don't want to play Haiti.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bruce Arena altered the US lineup after an irregular
heartbeat was detected in Brian McBride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brad Friedel and Jones played for the US team the last time it
met Haiti, taking ictory in a Barcelona '92 Olympic
qualifier in Port-au-Prince . . . ``We have a lot of natural
talents, soccer technicians,'' said Patrice Dumont, who coached the
Olympic team. ``But since 1977, we haven't had a lot of activity
with the national team, so we are not here to win this tournament.
This is a chance to work on preparing for international
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Cup continues with Canada-Costa Rica and
Mexico-Trinidad and Tobago games in San Diego Sunday. Former
Revolution players include defender Mark Watson (Canada) and
midfielders David Nakhid and Evans Wise (Trinidad and Tobago) . . .
The tournament winner qualifies for the Confederations Cup, but
Mexico coach Manuel Lapuente is using a young team since the
Mexicans automatically qualify as defending champions. Lapuente
will be missing players because America and Atlas players will be
participating in the Copa Libertadores. ``But Lapuente believes
this is the best team Mexico has, regardless of age,'' said
Rigoberto Cervantes of Los Angeles' La Opinion. Mexico has won
every Gold Cup title since 1991, when the US upset the Mexicans in
the semifinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
