<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COP BURNS KNOWS ENOUGH TO WATCH HIS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cops and coaches have a lot in common. They both have jobs where
instincts matter more than anything else on their resumes. They
understand that skepticism is good and paranoia is necessary;
you've always got to know when someone is trying to pull some
chicanery behind your back.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns was a cop and is a coach. That's why I am convinced
that he knows what is happening to him now. He has to know he is
being set up by his employers. They have all but framed his
likeness, raised it above their heads, and screamed to the world
that this is the suspect who has brought down the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be skilled in police work to know what an
insult that is.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the case for Burns is not a very good one. His
team lost to the Panthers Saturday night at the FleetCenter, 5-1.
There were boos for Byron Dafoe, who was pulled. There were boos
for the team that seemed to master the art of shooting and missing.
There were boos for failed power plays. There were boos for the
absentee defensemen who allowed Pavel Bure to shoot, miss, secure
his own rebound, and score as he guided the puck past a sprawled
Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Games like these and times like these are dangerous, in any
sport. Rough times make people do strange things. Like revise
history. Obviously Burns is not blameless in the collapse of the
Bruins. But if you look at some of the other things that have
happened to the Bruins since last summer, are you surprised that
they are currently playoff outsiders?
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, you can bring anybody in here and they're not
going to do a better job than Pat's done,'' Ray Bourque said after
the loss. He also said it would be silly to fire the coach at this
point in the season. What he didn't say is that the evidence
against owner Jeremy Jacobs, president/general manager Harry
Sinden, and assistant general manager Mike O'Connell is just as
damning as the stuff against Burns.
</P>
<P>
   You can't bring in a Sprewellian guy (Joe Murphy) who cusses out
the coach and expect it not to affect your team. You can't have the
owner _ sitting in Buffalo watching DirecTV _ questioning the
coaches in the newspaper and expect it not to affect the team. I
certainly wouldn't have re-signed Dmitri Khristich, either, but you
still have to expect that losing your leading goal scorer will hurt
you. The same is true with Tim Taylor, a terrific penalty killer.
And don't forget the injury to Jason Allison, the center who seems
to calm everyone when he is on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Dafoe Saturday night, it is apparent that he is
not the same as he was during his 10-shutout 1998-99 season. There
are two ways to analyze his skittish play so far. A cynic would say
he has relaxed because he has a new contract. I would argue his
lack of training camp _ due to his contract showdown with Sinden _
still is limiting his performance. Burns had said that he would
rely heavily on his goaltender, but Saturday night the coach said
he is considering a Dafoe-Rob Tallas swap.
</P>
<P>
   We have found out in the last few days that pro sports are not
always about loyalty or fairness. So in a sense, it doesn't matter
that Burns came to town in 1997 and took hockey's worst team to the
playoffs. And it probably doesn't matter that he has had to try to
get the best out of many players who are _ or have been _ clearly
annoyed with the words and/or negotiating tactics of management.
</P>
<P>
   I remember talking with Burns last month in his office. He said
that most good coaches know when they are about to be fired. There
are no surprises. ``They may say they are surprised,'' he said at
the time, ``but if they were paying attention, they knew it was
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, as Burns spoke, I couldn't help thinking that he
was defending himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the puck is there and the goalie is not there and we don't
put the puck in the net, is that coaching?'' he said. Eventually,
he was asked about the speculation surrounding him. There always
seems to be a Burns report from someone. Recently, Channel 4
reported that this weekend was critical to Burns's future. Burns's
team was outscored, 10-3, over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sinden said there would be no in-season firing of
Burns. But he said nothing of 2000-01. He implied the media have
been irresponsible in their speculation, even though the owner of
the team publicly criticized the coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Burns is fired, it would only be fair if Jacobs comes to
Boston and does it face to face. And after that, it would be
refreshing if he attended the press conference and agreed to take
questions. So far, Jacobs has been like the ``Charlie's Angels''
voice in the squawk box.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he doesn't pay attention to the newspapers. He said
he doesn't watch the television shows. ``If I did, it would drive
me crazy,'' he said. But he doesn't have to read the paper or watch
TV to know what is happening around him. It's a job of instincts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
