<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX     02-13 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In proper text, there is a place for Bible in schools
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critical teaching and study of the Bible neither reduces it to a
handbook for morals nor to a talisman for personal salvation.
</P>
<P>
   - James Fowler, director of the Center for Ethics, Emory
University
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The annual debate about teaching the Bible in public
schools rages on in state legislatures across the nation. It is
part of the larger issue about which religious texts can be
included in public schools without crossing the First Amendment,
which prohibits the state from favoring or disfavoring any
particular religion.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a new political strategy: Rather than bills that
call for reinstating prayer and Bible reading in school, both of
which the U.S. Supreme Court has barred, there's a call for
teaching the New and Old Testaments as history and literature.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, some parents associated with neither the left
nor the right say, ``Why not?'' Students are being cheated out of a
key dimension of human history because schools have become so
fearful of stirring up religious extremists that they avoid all
reference to religious and moral thinking _ themes that undergird
much of the development of western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong, then, with legislation that simply requires
schools to offer elective courses on the Bible as history and
literature? The problem is that while the legislation calls for a
``non-devotional'' approach, it is written in a way that assumes a
literal interpretation, outlining what is to be taught.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler says no legislation is even needed to include such
electives in high school. Georgia state and local school boards
already have that power, and some have figured out how to use it in
a manner that provides for critical thinking, not indoctrination.
Fowler, who in the 1970s helped found Harvard's master's program on
teaching religion in public schools, says models for high school
courses that emphasize critical thinking already exist in Fort
Myers, Fla., Oklahoma City and several other school districts.
</P>
<P>
   If legislators, parents and educators truly want to fashion a
course that helps students understand the uniqueness and
similarities of many religions (which will inevitably help them
figure out their own personal beliefs in life), they should take
the time to form a task force to do it right and to provide the
in-depth training teachers need. Fowler suggests starting with
materials from the Freedom Forum, located at the First Amendment
Center in Arlington, Va. Charles Haynes, the center's senior
scholar, has coordinated an excellent guide, ``The Bible and Public
Schools'' (www.freedomforum.org). The guide is endorsed by 18
organizations, ranging from the national Association of
Evangelicals to the Anti-Defamation League and the Council on
Islamic Education. Haynes describes it as a ``third way,'' leaning
neither left nor right.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler's guidelines for critical study of the Bible are also
excellent starting points for parents and politicians. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledge that the Bible is a document that took form over
several centuries in several languages, with contributions from
many sources.
</P>
<P>
   _ Differentiate between the forms and types of writing the Bible
encompasses, from myth to legend, from hymnic poetry to proverbs,
from laws and commandments to gospels, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compare it with texts from other religious traditions _ not to
show its superiority, but to recognize both its uniqueness and
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be honest about the way it has functioned in different eras
and for different peoples. For example, it has been used both to
justify racial prejudice and as a reference point in drafting this
nation's founding documents.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is easier to simply omit the Bible or to insist on
one interpretation of it than it is to facilitate students'
critical thinking about it, but we ought not give up on the
challenge. Sunday school is the place for teaching the Bible;
school is the place for teaching about it _ and about other
religious texts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
