A5523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN14-COX     02-13 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet freedoms endangered by Reno's vow to patrol
superhighway
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Attorney General Janet Reno has fire in her eyes
when she talks about tracking down Internet hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's zeal to throw all the powers of government into the
search for the people responsible for the cybervandalism of Yahoo,
Amazon.com, eBay and a few other Web sites contrasts sharply with
her reluctance to pursue evidence of pervasive criminal
fund-raising conducted in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The cyberpunks, or punk, who jammed up the Web sites deserve
punishment, perhaps with a manual-labor job to repay the damage.
But Web site jamming does not threaten cherished national
treasures, undermine democratic principles or suggest double
standards of justice.
</P>
<P>
   There is something unsettling about the enthusiasm of the
Justice Department to issue cyberbadges to the FBI, and presumably,
every other government agency, so Big Brother can lurk behind
cyberbillboards ready to pounce upon digital vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Damage caused by anti-social hackers can be considerable and
should not be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the wide-open architecture of the Internet is an open
invitation to cyberhackers just as it opens the door to
advancements in communication, research, education, entertainment
and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The downside to the Internet is that it is open to everyone
worldwide with access to a computer, which also is its strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can be compared to a democracy where all people are
equal and have the power to control their own destinies.
</P>
<P>
   That egalitarian principle has threatened tyrants and elite
ruling classes throughout human history. The United States, one of
the world's youngest nations, happens to be the oldest democracy, a
condition Americans should jealously guard.
</P>
<P>
   Insecure and despotic governments fear giving too much freedom
to the people. Throughout history, monarchs and ruling classes have
passed all manner of restrictions to keep control and power out of
the hands of common people.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is not a government, a person or even an
institution. It's something brand new, or relatively new. It
doesn't even have an address. It is everywhere, presumably in every
nation and province.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is a new form of communication that embodies
several of the fundamental rights protected in the U.S.
Constitution's Bill of Rights, especially freedom of speech and of
the press.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the Internet offers the opportunity for every
person worldwide to publish his or her own newspaper as a personal
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet surely gives citizens everywhere a soapbox to stand
on to expound their thoughts, no matter how goofy or profound.
</P>
<P>
   The American press, unique among private institutions, is
independent of all branches of government. It has been a feisty
watchdog guarding the public against abuses from governmental or
private sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
   It is axiomatic, at least to guardians of the press, that free
speech and free press go hand in hand with a free society. The
freer the speech and the press, the freer the society.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I feel uneasy when the government's highest ranking
law officer promises to unleash the full weight of federal law
enforcement to make the Internet secure from cybervandals.
</P>
<P>
   What will be gained and what will be lost when the Internet
superhighway is patrolled by FBI, ATF, IRS, INS and other
government cybercops?
</P>
<P>
   The feds have no idea if the site jamming was done by an
American citizen. It could have been the act of a savvy but bored
goat-herder in Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the Internet might mean that it can never be
totally secure. We must be careful that we do not throttle the
freedom and the opportunities of the Internet while trying to make
it secure.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1427EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
