<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SCORSESE-Q&AMP;A0214-COX     02-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCORSESE-Q&AMP;A0214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scorsese makes
 &HT;    `Personal Journey'
 &HT;    through the movies
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's Valentines Day. And Martin Scorsese's heart
belongs to the cinema. ``I love movies so much,'' the director says
with a passion as profound as a slow-mo punch to Robert De Niro's
mug in Scorsese's visual poem to pugilism, ``Raging Bull.''
</P>
<P>
   He loves movies you've seen a thousand times. Like 1972's ``The
Godfather.'' Ones you've probably never heard of. Like 1949's ``Gun
Crazy.'' And bigger-than-life movies he saw as a kid, partly with
his eyes closed. Like 1946's ``Duel in the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Personal Journey With Martin Scorsese Through American
Movies,'' airing in three 90-minute parts at 8 tonight through
Wednesday on Turner Classic Movies, is an often stunning,
fact-filled look at the role directors have played through most of
American cinema.
</P>
<P>
   With revealing clarity, Scorsese discusses the art elements
reflected in myriad directors' works: art vs. commerce; distinct
genres (the western, gangster movies and the musical); the
influence of technology; film language; and more. And he includes
clips. Lots of clips crossing several decades. ``The Bad and the
Beautiful,'' ``High Sierra,'' ``Point Blank'' and ``Meet Me in St.
Louis.'' ``The Birth of a Nation,'' ``East of Eden,'' ``Shock
Corridor'' and ``Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   From his New York office, Scorsese recently talked about making
``Personal Journey,'' the Directors Guild of America's recent
snubbing of silent era legend D.W. Griffith and other opinions
about movies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tell me about your goals with this documentary. You show
clips from a lot of movies many people have never seen.
</P>
<P>
   A: I try to emphasize that I'm not a film critic. I love movies
too much to be a critic. I look at a film that may have one or two
scenes that are good and then the rest of it is not good. ... I
think it's important to look at the documentary not as a history
but a personal look and walk through as what affected me.
Therefore, it's not historical. I was interested in how these minor
films affected me and my filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there one or two directors in ``Personal Journey'' whom
you really want to champion?
</P>
<P>
   A: I really like Jacques Tourneur. Watching his films are like
spending time with family members you love. ``I Walked With a
Zombie.'' ``Cat People.'' It's like spending time with a piece of
music or a painting that moves. I can never tell what the plot is.
Like with ``Vertigo.'' There is no such thing as having seen it too
many times. ``North by Northwest.'' After seeing it 20 or 30 times,
you know the plot and the narrative seems to be most important.
Once you know the narrative, it's not as important anymore.
``Vertigo'' is more emotional and psychological. I see ``Cat
People'' as that way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think ``Personal Journey'' will inspire young
moviegoers to go beyond what's at
</P>
<P>
   theaters today?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, absolutely. I was surprised there was still more to find
in American cinema. In the past 10 years I've discovered silent
cinema. Up to about 12 years ago, silent films were shown very
poorly in America. You couldn't get emotionally involved with them.
With the restorations _ like ``The Four Horsemen of the
Apocalypse'' _ a whole other world has opened up to me. Even
``Nosferatu'' had a restoration. And it's a revelation. Back in
1962, I saw it in black and white. I always wondered why (the
vampire) was walking around in the daytime. Five years ago I saw
the restoration, and it's tinted blue. That means it's nighttime.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What kind of personal film library do you have?
</P>
<P>
   A:There are several thousand 16mm prints and 1,500 prints in
35mm.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What do you think about the Directors Guild of America's
decision to take D.W. Griffith's name off its special award?
</P>
<P>
   A:I understand it. ``Birth of a Nation'' is an extraordinary
movie. But the racial aspects are very disturbing. That's why I
like ``Intolerance.'' My personal view is that he was the one who
created everything we know about film. He inspired the Russian
montage of the '20s. We owe everything in the silent period to
Griffith. ... You can't deny that everything comes from him.
</P>
<P>
   Q:It's been awhile since your ``Last Temptation of Christ''
created a stir. Were you surprised by the reaction to it?
</P>
<P>
   A:I had no idea it would cause such a reaction. We knew it would
generate talk and discussion. I like throwing back out to the
public: ``What is the message of Christianity? Are we capable of
living out and behaving in such a way as that? Is it part of our
makeup or are we more in tune with the animal side of our nature?''
But it got bogged down in fundamentalism. In terms of
fundamentalism in America, they can't tell us what to believe.
There were some people who had some wonderful discussions out of
this.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
