<SLUG> BC-JOHN-LEWIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis steps up majority whip campaign, faces tough rivals
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) is ratcheting up his
campaign to be House majority whip if the Democrats win control of
the House next fall, raising money and campaigning for candidates
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis sees it, the third-highest ranking post in the House
would give him a platform to bring the Democratic Party, ``under
one roof of one House _ the American House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a builder of bridges,'' said Lewis, Georgia's senior
congressional lawmaker. ``I bring people together and I will use
that experience in the Democratic leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis faces formidable opposition in Reps. Steny Hoyer
(D-Md.), chairman of the Democratic Steering Committee, and Nancy
Pelosi (D-Calif.), a fund-raising machine from the nation's most
populous state.
</P>
<P>
   All three lawmakers are running highly competitive campaigns for
the job, which requires shrewd vote counting skills. The campaigns
are in full force despite an important fact: The Democrats don't
control the House now, and they won't have a chance to win it back
until November's congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats succeed in their mission next fall, Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) would likely become speaker and Minority
Whip David Bonior (D-Mich.) would move up to the majority leader
slot, leaving open the whip job.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates have raised a tidy sum of money to dole out
to lawmakers and new recruits. The idea, perfected by the current
Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas), is to raise money for candidates
and then call in those chits to win the whip election.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis defeats Hoyer and Pelosi, he would become the second
African-American elected to a leadership position in Congress,
behind former Democratic Rep. Bill Gray of Pennsylvania, who served
as majority whip from 1989 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of such a distinction is not lost on Lewis, a
former civil rights leader and close confidant of Martin Luther
King Jr. Bringing diversity to the upper reaches of Congress is a
key aspect of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a history of fighting, of not giving up,'' Lewis said.
``But I also have a history of caring.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Lewis ran a low-key campaign out of concern that it
would distract the 211-member caucus from the party's larger goal
of winning back the majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, it became apparent to him that Pelosi was gaining
momentum with her campaign by starting early. Lewis decided that he
``could not afford to stand on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several months, Lewis has relentlessly gone on the
road to campaign for Democratic candidates, visiting some two dozen
districts over the last three months alone. He meets weekly with
his steering committee of 20 supporters and plans to host dinners
and fund-raisers to whip up support.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Lewis has raised $700,000 in his campaign fund. In
addition, he has given $270,000 to the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have more than money to offer,'' Lewis said. ``I
have gone to districts and met with members one on one. I have
shown how accessible I will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who would be the first woman elected to a House
leadership position, has raised $1.3 million for the DCCC.
</P>
<P>
   She has raised $700,000 for her political action committee and
contributed $550,000 to individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can bring a fresher perspective,'' said Pelosi,
noting that California is the land of entrepreneurial spirit.
Issues that play big in the West such as urban sprawl,
transportation and the development of high-tech companies, are
starting to move East. The party needs her expertise, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with each issue in a much more comprehensive
way than in the old, stale way,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Democratic Party leaders purposely avoided the fray
over the race, it has not stopped other key Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi has support from the ranking Democrats of three
committees. She also has the support of Rep. Cynthia McKinney
(D-Ga.) _ much to the dismay of Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's other Democratic representative, Sanford Bishop, is
solidly behind Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer has raised $240,000 for his political action committee
over the last year. He has raised $50,000 for the DCCC and plans to
give an additional $50,000 next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer is betting that his years of experience in the Democratic
leadership will win him votes. Before the Republicans took over
Congress in 1994, Hoyer was chairman of the Democratic Caucus. He
narrowly lost the whip job to Bonior in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think members are going to make a judgment on who can best
bring us together,'' Hoyer said. ``Who can reach across regions of
our country from the Northeast to the South to the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
