<SLUG> BC-NEWLYWEDS-AGAIN0214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The marrying kind: Once is not enough
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dearly Beloved, we are gathered together as
readers this Valentine's Day to celebrate the whimsical love story
of an Austin couple who can't stop getting married.
</P>
<P>
   To each other.
</P>
<P>
   The once and future bride is Karen Richards, 48, owner of Accent
copy and graphics shop. Always at her side is the incurably
romantic repeat groom, Mike Hudkins, 58, owner of TOPS, an office
supply warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   How do they love each other? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 7, 1987, Washington, D.C. _ Mike accompanies Karen on her
business trip to the nation's capital and ends up in the hotel bar
confiding to a stranger that he wants to get married. The newfound
friend choreographs an immediate wedding at a stained-glass church,
complete with an encore Rolls-Royce limo ride past all the
breathtaking monuments of American history.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31, 1988, Las Vegas _ Karen and Mike join Karen's parents
in the gambling dreamland for a 2 1/2-minute assembly-line chapel
wedding presided over by a minister who talks about 100 mph and
wears a white suit with huge pockets that only Captain Kangaroo
could love. Mike wipes away tears as they pledge to love and honor
each other til-- death parts them.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31, 1991, Austin _ A man and woman dressed as flower
children pull rose petals out of plastic pumpkins on Halloween
night as Mike and Karen march down a hotel lobby staircase to stand
before a minister outfitted as a 13th century friar. So many guests
wear costumes that the bride and groom can't tell who's a
party-crasher and who's not.
</P>
<P>
   June 6, 1993, Phoenix _ Karen and Mike wear shorts as they climb
1.2 miles up to Squaw Peak to stand before a minister. The heat is
so debilitating that when they realize the camera was left in the
car, no one wants to hike down and retrieve it for the magical
nuptial moment.
</P>
<P>
   And the wedding bells are still ringing.
</P>
<P>
   Beckoning as must-do wedding locations are Catalina Island off
the California coast, the Giant Sequoias in Northern California and
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may skip a year or two if we don't feel like we want to get
married that year,'' Karen said. ``But every year we feel like it,
we're going to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last one is going to be in Paris, France,'' Mike said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a moment of hesitation, an almost imperceptible quiver
of panic, as Karen absorbs that last thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it won't be the last,'' Karen said. ``We're flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, too. Though their paths intersected many times throughout
their lives, they didn't meet until each had experienced first love
and marriage. Each had lived in Indiana, California and Phoenix _
but never knew the other. The closest they came was when Mike's
mother mailed him an Army care package that contained Playboy
magazine photos of Karen, who represented Phoenix in an issue
devoted to beautiful secretaries. Mike and his family didn't know
Karen, but his mother figured her son would enjoy seeing someone
from his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   They met in Austin, where both had real estate jobs. Karen found
a romantic and sentimental man who dreams up unconventional
entrepreneurial schemes and treats her as an equal. Mike said he
found a beautiful, self-made businesswoman with more savvy than an
MBA who happens to share his interest in camping, sailing, travel
and gem shows.
</P>
<P>
   Mike had been married to another woman before choosing to be a
bachelor, and Karen had been married and divorced three times. The
idea of multiple marriages to each other blossomed after Karen
decided she wanted to be married to Mike more times than she had
been married before.
</P>
<P>
   ``That nullifies all those other marriages,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen: ``You're my fourth one, my fifth one, my sixth one and my
seventh one.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike: ``And eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen: ``Soon to be ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Let's double-check that matrimonial math.
</P>
<P>
   Karen: ``I'm losing count here.''
</P>
<P>
   They have to put the conversation on hold and run through the
nuptial numbers until they have things straight.
</P>
<P>
   Karen: ``So we're going to do the eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   That eighth marriage may happen soon. They plan to be in San
Diego this weekend to shop for a 35-foot sailboat so they can have
a wedding on deck in the harbor of Catalina Island.
</P>
<P>
   The number of weddings they've had is not the only thing Karen
and Mike can't keep straight. Forget trying to ask them the dates
of their weddings. It can take more than 30 minutes to
conversationally chew those numbers over. And they still can't
recite them correctly.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. This couple doesn't do anniversaries. When it's time
to celebrate, they just get married again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is an anniversary,'' said Mike.
</P>
<P>
   And they truly live that philosophy, says their close friend
Lana Weill, who owns the Austin company that makes Lana's Eggrolls.
She was invited to the couple's third wedding, the Halloween
costume knot-tying gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual, but at the same time very encouraging to
me,'' she said. ``It reminds other people that when you marry for a
long time, you tend to take things for granted. This way, you can
remind yourself that you just got married yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike and Karen don't just renew their vows. They always go to
the courthouse and file the proper paperwork for another legal
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   That's perfectly legal in Texas. The law prohibits court
officials from withholding a marriage license just because the
bride and groom already are husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legal,'' said Travis County Court at Law Judge David
Phillips. ``The family code even anticipates this. I don't know
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Legislature has written a law that says this is OK,
and the county clerk may not refuse to issue a license on the
ground that the applicants are already married to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that a U.S. law could ever stop this love story. And if it
did?
</P>
<P>
   They'll always have Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
