<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RADIO-LOVE0214-COX     02-13 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-LOVE0214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latino love connection
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jesus Zamoracq has a hard time meeting women. He
leaves home by 7:30 a.m. each day to work construction and does not
return until 8 p.m. He works Monday through Saturday and sometimes
on Sunday, a grueling schedule that leaves little time for dating.
All of his co-workers are men, and it's fun to hang out with them,
but he gets lonesome when he thinks about his ex-girlfriend in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, 28, has had very few dates since he moved to Georgia six
months ago. So he wasted little time when an opportunity presented
itself as he listened to the radio in his home on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of woman are you looking for?'' the announcer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora had stumbled on a radio show wildly popular among
lovesick Latinos in metro Atlanta. People call the program, talk
about themselves and describe their ideal mate. They give their
phone numbers on the air, hang up and wait for the phone to ring.
</P>
<P>
   The calls have poured in to WWWA-AM (1100) recently from
Hispanics in search of a date for Valentine's Day. Most callers are
Mexican men in their 20s who work long hours painting or building
houses. They are away from home for the first time. Many spend
Saturday night at home because they do not have a car. A few of
them admit on the air that they've never kissed a girl.
</P>
<P>
   For them, broadcasting a request for companionship on AM radio
is the easiest way to get a date.
</P>
<P>
   Their matchmaker and guide on this amorous adventure is Mexico
native Alberto Alvearcq, an announcer whose voice rings with an
enthusiasm that encourages the shy, reassures the forlorn and
extends the promise that true love is only a phone call away. He
often reminds callers that ``there are lots of women listening at
this very minute to this program!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is your name?'' he asked a caller recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armando.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arrrrrrr-mando!'' Alvear repeated in a tone that suggested he
had just won the lottery. ``Where are you from?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guanajuato.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guaaaa-nnnaaaaa-juato!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How long have you been in Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of woman are you looking for?''
</P>
<P>
   Armando said he'd like to meet a woman who shares his interests
and is about his age. He's 22 and said he likes to dance and listen
to music _ not a thorough biographical sketch, perhaps, but enough
to elicit a call the next day from a Guatemalan woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise,'' said Armando, a construction worker
fromthe central Mexicoan state of Guanajuato whose full name is
Armando Jimenezcq.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had a pleasant conversation with the woman who
called, but his hopes ebbed when she said she lived far from his
house near Hartsfield International Airport. He said he wasn't sure
if they would talk again.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I get lonely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The love lines are open from 11 a.m. to noon on weekdays on
WWWE-AM (1100), a Spanish-language station in Atlanta. Alvear calls
his show ``La Media Naranja''cq _ ``The Half Orange'' _ because of
a Latin American saying that compares the unattached person to an
incomplete orange made whole when he finds his other half.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with a financial stake in romance sponsor the show.
One big advertiser is a nightclub called La Pantera Rosa _ The Pink
Panther _ that urges listeners to come to a place ``where the party
never ends!'' so they can ``dance to the best groups and with the
prettiest girls!'' Dating services also advertise on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``The Half Orange'' came to metro Atlanta seven years ago,
about 70 couples have married after meeting through the airwaves,
including Joel and Veronica Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Hernandez, 25, said he came to the United States from
Mexico in 1993 and worked as a janitor, cab driver, truck driver,
construction worker and deliveryman. He said it was hard to find
dates during his first few months here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people here just work, work, work. I was lucky to
hear that program,'' he said. ``I called for fun, just for fun,
just to meet girls. I didn't realize I was going to meet someone _
my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Hernandez, now 22, said it was hard to mino men
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that, number one, the men work a lot. Number two is
that they don't have a car,'' she said. ``They don't have the
opportunity to leave work. They don't go to the discotheque. They
don't go to the cafes.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the difficulties, she said, was that the men she met
soon after her arrival in 1996 never had anything of interest to
say. It was this frustration that turned her to the radio, where
she heard her future husband describe himself one morning a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much liked his manner of expression,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She called him, and they talked on the phone over the next three
weeks. Then they met at a restaurant and chatted over hamburgers.
They were soon married and now have two sons, 2-year-old Alexis and
3-year-old Allan. A third is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates to join the ranks of the betrothed-by-radio include
Cristobal Santos, a 42-year-old immigrant from Chiapas, a
mountainous state in southern Mexico. He came to this country two
years ago and worked in North Carolina tobacco fields and New York
apple orchards before coming to Atlanta six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   After he called Alvear's show, a 44-year-old Columbian woman
called him from her house in a Grayson, a town of about 575 people
Gwinnett County. Now they're seriously dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could be my wife one day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most callers are men seeking women, but Alvear said he also airs
calls from women seeking men. Less frequent are on-the-air calls
from men seeking men, and rarer still are calls from women looking
for women. Once in a while, a native-born American will call to ask
for a Hispanic mate. Alvear said occasionally reads letters from
single men in jails and prisons on the premise that the
incarcerated need love, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Jackson, producer of the program, said he didn't realize how
hungry people were for a date until the show first aired on WWWE-AM
in August 1998. Even though the program airs for only an hour a
day, Jackson said, phones in the studio ring all day with people
asking about someone they heard on a previous show _ usually they
heard someone interesting but they failed to write down a phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   The show's impact isn't just shown by the matches made, but by
mistakes as well. During one show, Alvear was one digit off in
reading a phone number. He accidentally broadcast the phone number
of a local law firm. Suddenly, workers in the law office were
getting calls for a Hispanic man they had never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Even when there is interest _ and the right phone number _ it
doesn't always lead to a match.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Zamora heard from three women after he called the show.
They apparently were impressed with the way he answered Alvear's
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What type of woman are you looking for?'' the announcer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to meet a woman that _ well, I like to read, to
listen to good music, take walks and chat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you also like to dance?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very little, but I would like to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of music do you like?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I like rock, modern music, bolero, tango and
instrumental music.''
</P>
<P>
   Zamora talked with all three women, but said he worried that
they did not share his interests in things such as mathematics and
the environment. He eventually ruled out two but had a date with
the third that confirmed his hunch: no sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a hesitant venture into the dating world, Zamora has
rejoined the ranks of lonely Latinos without a date for Valentine's
Day. Together they form a fraternity of the luckless whose sole
membership requirement is a yearning for companionship. Members who
want to get out have their last best shot at a Valentine's date
today. They'll tune in by the thousands at 11 a.m. and listen for
that person who might make them whole.
</P>
<P>
   And if that person doesn't call? Not to worry. Another show airs
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
