<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-GADGETS0214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guidance system for RVs is gaining popularity
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Dayton Camper and RV Show that ended Sunday
put some of the latest gizmos for the recreational vehicle market
on display.
</P>
<P>
   And John Baldwin, parts manager for Tom Raper RVs of Richmond,
Ind., said the industry is expecting a boom in demand for gadgetry
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large group of people who are retiring in the next few
years are used to using high-tech equipment,'' Baldwin said.
``They're going to want systems that tell them where they're going
and where they're going to stay when they get there.
</P>
<P>
   One futuristic guidance system suitable for the RV crowd already
is available, according to Carl Marotzke, owner of Stereo on
Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The Eclipse Commander from Fujitsu TEN is able to understand
verbal requests for directions and guide motorists from place to
place using spoken directions.
</P>
<P>
   The Eclipse Commander, Marotzke said, is linked to the vehicle's
stereo. When the driver wants the system to plan a route, he simply
says ``navigator'' to turn on the system's map functions. He then
says ``route'' and spells out an address such as ``B-R-O-W-N 250''
for 250 Brown St.
</P>
<P>
   Before using the Commander, the driver has to program the
system's memory with a compact disc containing maps of the area
he'll be traveling. The Commander has a built in global positioning
system that uses information from orbiting satellites to determine
the vehicle's current position.
</P>
<P>
   The system looks up the requested address in its memory and
tells the driver the best way to get there. It gives directions
such as ``turn left at the corner 100 feet ahead'' and constantly
updates the driver as he approaches the destination.
</P>
<P>
   Marotzke said the Eclipse Commander also accepts voice commands
to tune its radio or turn on its CD player.
</P>
<P>
   Stereo on Wheels sells the system for $1,069, Marotzke said. For
additional information, visit the Eclipse Web site at
www.eclipse-web.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1428EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
