<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran) _ Conservatives whip up their supporters
ahead of a crucial test in national elections this week. By Kevin
Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ The deadline for a ``framework''
agreement between the Palestinians and the Israelis passes,
unceremoniously, without an accord. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ A standoff is continuing between
the president and his top general over who should control the
government. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-WAR (Huambo) _ After a series of back-to-back government
victories late last year, the rebels have seized the offensive in
this country's seemingly endless war. But despite the see-saw
fighting, hopes for peace have not died. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-VOTE (Dateline TK) _ Zimbabwe ends voting in a
referendum on a new constitution, which would allow land to be
taken away without compensation from white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   These two items are tentative:
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-CHOPPERS (Sao Paulo) _ Helicopters have become the
vehicle of choice for the privileged of Sao Paulo, not only to
hopscotch over hopelessly clogged streets but also to avoid
carjackings, kidnappings and roadside robberies that have become a
part of the risks of daily life. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-TRAVEL (Havana) _ Hundreds of Cuban families are stuck in a
limbo of politics and bureaucracy, holding valid documents for
travel to the United States that remain useless until they can get
exit visas from their government. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-VALENTINE (Philadelphia) _ For Valentine's Day in
Philadelphia, who needs expensive, candelit restaurants? One of the
most romantic places in the city turns out to be a 47-year-old
science exhibit intended to teach schoolchildren about the
circulatory system. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   TERMLIMITS (Columbus, Ohio) _ As term limits gradually take
effect in 18 state legislatures across the country, the time
strictures so popular with voters are turning seasoned leadership
out of office, nipping political careers, and prompting unusual
party maneuvers. A new sort of fast-forward politicking spawned by
term limits is exemplified here in Ohio where the majority
Republican leadership is attempting to name three different
statehouse speakers across the next three years in advance of term
limits that start with the elections this November. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLERGY-HIRING (Undated) _ Not only are synagogues across the
spectrum of Judaism finding it increasingly difficult to hire new
clergy, so, too, are Roman Catholic and Protestant churches.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SCHULZ (Undated) _ ``Peanuts'' creator Charles M. Schulz
died Saturday night, turning his farewell note in Sunday papers
into an epitaph for both a comic strip and its creator. Schulz was
77.
</P>
<P>
