<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   NEWYORKER-CARTOONS (New York) _ Under the fine lines and smooth
washes of The New Yorker magazine's cartoons, it's stormy weather.
The magazine's funny men are frowning. Some say the old New Yorker
style they helped to create is in ruins. Others say it is about
time. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS-AND-MONEY (Chicago) _ ``Sensation,'' the exhibition of
cutting-edge British art, was meant to increase the audience at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art but ended up hauling it into a court battle
with Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani over city financing. Now the show
has a new life in a different context: nearly 400 people convened
here on Saturday to examine the relationship between arts and
society in the wake of the exhibition. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ The Writers on Writing Series.
This week by novelist Maureen Howard.
</P>
<P>
   WEILL-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ The Brooklyn Academy of Music's
celebration of the centenary of Kurt Weill's birth builds to
serious business with a film festival beginning and a production of
``Der Weg der Verheissung'' (``The Eternal Road''), an epic musical
and theatrical interpretation of Jewish history. But the opening
program, ``Weill Style,'' was mostly a delightful lark. By James R.
Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   DANISH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The historical fact is that in
1931 a Danish painter named Einar Wegener became the first man ever
to be transformed surgically into a woman, and in ``The Danish
Girl'' David Ebershoff uses the bare facts of that story to create
his first novel. Richard Bernstein reviews.
</P>
<P>
   PUPS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Pups,'' produced, directed and
written by a filmmaker who goes by the single name Ash, takes a
knowing look at adolescents informed but not educated by television
and movies in a less than perfect United States. By Lawrence Van
Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DUEL-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Duel'' provides a quick sketch
of the careers of the combative Alexander Hamilton, champion of a
strong federal government, and Aaron Burr, the war hero and
charming ladies' man whose political accomplishments never matched
his potential. By Walter Goodman .
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN-INTERNET (London) _ Richard Branson is diving head first
into the digital economy. Call it the dot-comming of the Virgin
Group PLC. The brash, 48-year-old British billionaire, who founded
Virgin Atlantic Airways 15 years ago with one jumbo jet, now owns a
hodgepodge of more than 200 Virgin-branded businesses. Now he
intends to turn his tarmac-and-mortar world into something a bit
more virtual. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS-2000 (Menlo Park, Calif.) _ On the eve of the official
release of Windows 2000, Microsoft's first new business-oriented
operating system in four years, the software giant is endeavoring
to switch business users, large and small, to a new, more powerful
operating system that it says offers a host of benefits. But last
week, a growing rumbling among early users and analysts suggested
that Windows 2000 might not be a runaway success. By John Markoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICAL-REPORTS (Undated) _ The Internet, whose
armies have laid waste to the conventional beliefs of retailing,
brokerage houses and help-wanted advertising, has had a more subtle
impact on political journalism so far. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAME-BATTLE (Washington) _ Because they were late to
the Internet and e-commerce, many of tiny, often remote places in
the world are only now discovering that the two-letter Internet
addresses set aside for them in the early 1990s have been lost to
far-away companies. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   COREL-MERGER (Undated) _ Can two losers from the Windows world
marry and find happiness _ or at least better sales _ in the Linux
world? It may seem like a long shot, but that is the bet Corel
Corp. appears to have made in announcing last week that it will
merge with Inprise/BorlandCorp. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Brief news items from the computer
world, including news on AT&AMP;T's new communications center and
drDrew.com's condom give away.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Many e-commerce rookies approached
this post-Christmas season with apprehension, given the dearth of
remaining advertising money and questions about how many of their
customers would return. Few had as much to worry about as those
companies whose core function was selling gift certificates online.
But so far this year, most of these sites report that weekly
revenues are actually increasing, despite the fact that
post-holiday sales to consumers have leveled off. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Last week's Web site attacks were a
vivid reminder that technology's sword of individual empowerment
has a wicked double edge. But the term for the attack technique _
denial of service _ has the potential to assume an equally ominous
meaning as telecommunications giants continue to merge their large
holdings. The Digital Commerce column. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   BEER-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Guinness Bass Import Co., which
distributes and markets Guinness stout in the United States, is
overhauling its sales pitch to make the brand seem less
intimidating to those Americans, particularly those in their
mid-20s, who typically favor imported beers. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan. ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this
week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   FALSE-ADS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Two years ago, the authors of ``The
Beardstown Ladies' Common-Sense Investment Guide'' watched their
sales deteriorate when the group of women acknowledged that their
dust-jacket boast of having beaten the stock market with 23.4
percent annual returns was actually inflated by a computer data
error. The cover of the group's ill-fated investment guide has
inspired two false advertising lawsuits in California and New York
that have resulted in diametrically opposing legal judgments. By
Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Brief news items from the media world,
including news on the San Francisco Examiner, the internet industry
magazine The Industry Standard, and a computer-generated
newscaster.
