<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING DOWN TO THE WIRE IN SAN FRANCISCO 
INVESTOR QUANDARY FOR AN INTERNET MAGAZINE 
A STAR IS BORN, OR MORPHED, MORE LIKE IT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the self-imposed deadline looms for the Hearst Corp. to find
a buyer for The San Francisco Examiner, speculation is intensifying
about who would run a combined newsroom with The San Francisco
Chronicle if they ended up merging.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still not certain if The Examiner, the newspaper that
gave William Randolph Hearst his addiction to journalism more than
a century ago, will fold. Any potential buyer has to make a move by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, under pressure from local politicians and the
Justice Department, Hearst sweetened its sale offer, including not
just the afternoon newspaper's name and its circulation list but
its office building, delivery trucks and a printing plant.
</P>
<P>
   The economic foundation of a newspaper, however, is advertising.
Under a joint operating agreement the San Francisco Newspaper
Agency handles printing, distribution and advertising sales for The
Examiner (daily circulation 107,129) and The Chronicle (circulation
456,742). Hearst has offered about $660 million for The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to sell or shut The Examiner has had problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which must approve of the dissolution of
the joint operating agreement, has been closely watching the case,
particularly in the wake of recent federal court decisions blocking
plans to end a joint agreement in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   In Honolulu, it was the state attorney general who went to court
to try to keep the city a two-newspaper town. In San Francisco, it
was Curt Reilly, a former mayoral candidate who has reason to
dislike The Examiner: In 1993, he broke an ankle in a scuffle with
The Examiner's editor, Phil Bronstein. A hearing on Reilly's suit
is set for March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Barnett, a law professor at the University of California
at Berkeley, said Sunday that he did not expect Hearst to extend
its deadline if no suitors appeared. ``Hearst might go ahead and
consummate the merger, make it a fait accompli, and let Justice
sue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   Investor Quandry for an Internet Magazine
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard is the fastest-growing publication in the
Internet field. Advertising is up by more than 400 percent in the
last year. Times are good.
</P>
<P>
   Times are also good for Flatiron Partners, an Internet-focused
venture capital firm that has established more than three dozen of
some of the best-known Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the magazine's parent, Industry Standard
Communications, raised $30 million from private equity groups to
expand the business. The lead investor in the group of five?
Flatiron Partners.
</P>
<P>
   So how will The Industry Standard cover the foibles, failures or
successes of Flatiron and the other companies Flatiron has invested
in?
</P>
<P>
   The potential conflict was such that Jonathan Weber, editor in
chief of the magazine, wrote an editor's letter emphasizing the
magazine's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the first to admit that The Standard is not likely to
be the best source for hard-hitting journalism about IDG (or, for
that matter, about The Standard itself),'' he wrote of IDG Books
Worldwide, majority owner of the magazine. ``But the new partners
have only a modest stake, and they are a good fit for us in part
because they present fewer potential conflicts than many other
possible partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said in an interview that the arrangement was an issue of
concern for not only the magazine but for the media world in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think certainly it is an issue that is increasingly common
for media organizations,'' Weber said. ``But certainly the issue of
covering them is a real one.'' He said that he was reassured by the
fact that Jerry Colonna, managing partner of Flatiron, had worked
at Information Week magazine, where he was the editor for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are editorially sophisticated about the media and that
helps us,'' Weber said. ``But it is a legitimate question to raise,
and I don't think that most news organizations do a very good job
of covering their owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber added that IDG Books was still the magazine's principal
owner. Flatiron has one seat on The Standard's board and the $30
million put in by the investment group _ of which Flatiron's was
the largest part _ represents 15 percent of the ownership in The
Standard.
</P>
<P>
   Orville Schell, dean of the graduate school of journalism at the
University of California at Berkeley, said there was room for
concern in the new arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Industry Standard has grown like one of those creatures in
a low-budget film,'' he said. ``But all of these fast-growing
nouvelle media outlets are in the territory where they have to be
very careful about not losing their journalistic souls. There are
gale-force winds of money blowing around out there, and it's not
always easy to know how to deport yourself given such pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
<P>
   A Star Is Born, or Morphed, More Like It
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Diane Sawyer. Ananova Ltd., the interactive-services
division of the Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency,
has developed a computer-generated newscaster _ part bombshell,
part Max Headroom. The newscaster _ also named Ananova _ will begin
broadcasting news from a Web site (www.ananova.com) in April. Later
this year, it will give information from British databases, tapping
into the resources of ticket outlets and weather services.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hird, director of new media at the Press Association, said
a colleague had suggested that the Press Association ``was sort of
faceless, so we decided to create a virtual face, a virtual star.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are a lot of technophobes around who don't
necessarily like to get their information from a database grid but
from a human voice and face,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hird said that the next stage would be more utilitarian.
``She'll be able to say, `Such-and-such movie is playing at your
local cinema,' or she'll say, `I know you wanted tickets to ``The
Lion King,'' but it was sold out. I found some. Would you still
like to see the show?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hird said the virtual anchor's hair is blue-green in part to
avoid the blonde-brunette conflict that bedevils so many
broadcasters who are women, and in part to make the figure appear
not quite human.
</P>
<P>
   ``In focus groups, the more human she looked, the more people
generated their own opinions of her, which were not all positive.
So we tried to make her look a little bit otherworldly. And they
tended to favor that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
