<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Feb. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A moisture-laden storm system will move across New England on
Monday bringing heavy snow near the Canadian border while ice and
rain fall farther south. Earlier, heavy rain will fall into a
shallow layer of cold air trapped in many valleys from central New
York to central and northern New England resulting in a damaging
accumulation of ice on trees and power lines. The ice may reach a
thickness of an inch or more in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Periods of rain will douse southern New England and the
Northeast Coast. Locally heavy rain and a few rumbles of thunder
will occur during the midday and afternoon as very mild air surges
north along the Atlantic Seaboard. Later Monday afternoon, the rain
will end as drier air arrives from the west. Farther west, patchy
snow will linger near the eastern Great Lakes where gusty breezes
from the north will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   A band of showers and a few potent thunderstorms will precede a
cold front as it moves toward the Southeast Coast. In the wake of
the front, cooler and drier air will spread south through the Ohio
Valley and interior Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Tranquil conditions will cover the Plains. Areas of low clouds
will linger near a front from the southern Missouri Valley to east
slopes of the northern Rockies. Otherwise, ample sunshine will
cover the region.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of Pacific disturbances will bring wet
weather near the Northwest Coast. Farther east, snow will be
locally heavy along west-facing mountain slopes from northern
California to central Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Severe Icing
</P>
<P>
   A few interior Northeast valleys will begin the day with heavy
icing. Ice is not uncommon in New England. However, severe icing
only occurs when either the frigid air cannot be dislodged or gelid
surface air is replenished from a new source. Monday's icing will
be caused by arctic air stuck in a few valleys of New England as
mild, moist air precedes a storm. The second process led to the
great icestorm of January 1998 in northern New England when
sub-freezing air kept slipping under a wedge of warm, moist air.
Monday's icing will be much shorter in duration and far less
widespread.
</P>
</TEXT>
