</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-INTERNET-900(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPROACHING THE WEB AS VIRGIN TERRITORY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Richard Branson was fiddling with one of his new
Virgin-brand mobile telephones in the living room of his Notting
Hill town house here last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to think how it works,'' he said, staring at a
special button on the phone _ a red button, with the Virgin logo.
The button connects customers by voice to operators who also handle
distribution for the Virgin.com Web site. With such a call,
customers can order plane tickets, CD's and an assortment of other
products that Branson usually hawks by nondigital means. After
trying fitfully to explain the red-button function, he finally
conceded that he wasn't sure how it worked, and gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of those anti-mobile phone guys before we did Virgin
Mobile,'' he explained, referring to the cellular phone service
that he started in November and that has already signed up 300,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Hands-on technical savvy or not, Branson is diving head first
into the digital economy. Call it the dot-comming of the Virgin
Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Branson, the brash, 48-year-old British billionaire who founded
Virgin Atlantic Airways 15 years ago with one jumbo jet plying the
London-New York route, now owns a hodgepodge of more than 200
Virgin-branded businesses. And he intends to turn his
tarmac-and-mortar world into something a bit more virtual.
</P>
<P>
   Having slapped the Virgin logo on planes, trains, soda, vodka,
clothing, movie theaters, music stores, a radio station, a
financial services company and even a wedding coordinator, Branson
means to expand his year-old Virgin.com Web site into a worldwide
e-commerce portal that he hopes will take on some of the qualities
of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics say he is already too late to the Internet market
and will surely stumble. ``A lot of traditional businesses have
made these kinds of plans and they've never worked out,'' said Noah
Yasskin, an analyst at Jupiter Communications in London.
</P>
<P>
   But Branson sees himself as specially suited for an
entrepreneurial leap onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, unlike Amazon.com _ which began as a book
distributor and is now a diversified digital middleman _ the Virgin
Group has many of its own products to sell. That doesn't mean,
though, that Branson plans to hold his Web customers hostage to the
Virgin brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If British Airways is selling better products than Virgin
Atlantic, we'll sell the British Airways product,'' he said. ``If
Fidelity is offering a better financial product than Virgin Direct,
we'll recommend the Fidelity product.''
</P>
<P>
   Branson says he will not get snagged on the sticking point that
has caused other brand-name companies to stumble on their way to
cyberspace _ the fear of cannibalizing the established offline
brands. ``It's a fact of life,'' he said, ``that the Internet will
kill off some of our business and severely damage a lot of
conventional industry.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the matter of management and money, which in
the case of the privately held Virgin Group resides chiefly in one
man: Richard Branson, boss and banker, rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   Having sold 49 percent of his Virgin Atlantic unit to Singapore
Airlines for $965 million right before Christmas, Branson has cash
to burn. And unlike most dot-com's, he notes, his money is real _
not the paper wealth of newly minted Internet stock.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the advantages Branson describes, Virgin is
entering the Internet arena too late to claim the ``first mover''
edge that Web executives like to tout.
</P>
<P>
   Yasskin, the Jupiter analyst, says that most of the major
sectors of the Web are already carved up by companies like Yahoo
and Amazon.com. ``At least in the U.S. market, Virgin will have a
very hard time competing,'' he said, adding that outside the United
States ``Virgin still has a little time to grab some market
share.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Branson maintains that the Virgin brand is so
strong internationally _ the company is already Britain's biggest
advertiser _ that his relatively late Internet move will not hurt
his chances. In fact, he said his timing might present an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not lost hundreds of millions of pounds on the Net in
the few years the Net was developing,'' he said, a not-so-veiled
reference to companies like Amazon.com that have spent and lost
large amounts of money building their clientele. ``Our approach is
to come on the Net when the amount of people who are logging on to
the Net are considerable, and where we can actually see real
profits reasonably quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks may be self-serving, but for Branson and his
privately held company, it is crucial to quickly turn a profit.
Otherwise, he may find it necessary to relinquish some control over
the Virgin Group by raising money in the public stock market _ in
order to compete for big-time capital with the likes of Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   While he says that an initial public offering is on his mind, he
has no immediate plans for one, predicting that he can break into
the European Internet market without a major cash outlay for a
brand-building campaign. But the U.S. market is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America we're well ahead in the major cities,'' he said,
speaking of Virgin's brand recognition. ``But out in the sticks,
we've still got some way to go. America will be the toughest nut to
crack. We will have to spend big bucks in America.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the Internet pioneers who have paid handsomely to
simply get their name out, Virgin already has dozens of branded
products to help keep its name in the public eye. Branson said, for
example, that he intends to have ``Virgin.com'' painted onto the
sides of his planes in place of the ``No Way BA/AA'' slogan that
has adorned Virgin's fleet since his nemesis, British Airways,
announced an abortive plan for a far-reaching alliance with
American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Without the dot-com money of a publicly traded company, Branson
seeks attention for himself and his company in ways beyond paid
advertising. Virgin generates press releases on an almost daily
basis, and he is not above publicity stunts like the Virgin Mobile
rollout in November. Creating a stir widely chronicled in the
British tabloids, he held a parade of sorts in the West End of
London, riding a float on which he surrounded himself with nude
models talking on Virgin Mobile phones. The slogan for the new
company: ``What you see is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   He also primes the publicity pump by making himself freely
available for interviews. ``It's cheaper than buying a full-page ad
in The New York Times,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, wielding his brand identity against Internet upstarts is
one thing. Taking on one of Europe's fasting-growing communications
powers is another. And that is precisely the collision course he
has set for himself with Virgin Mobile, a joint venture with the
Deutsche Telekom unit One2One. Despite its 300,000 subscribers in
Britain, Virgin Mobile, will be up against the combined 42 million
European subscribers of Vodafone AirTouch and Mannesmann, which
announced plans for the biggest industrial merger ever the week
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Branson predicts that Virgin Mobile will be able to gain ground
on Vodafone when the licensing begins this spring for Britain's
next generation of wireless telephones _ digital devices that are
to combine voice, Internet access and other digital features.
Toward that end, he has put together a group of investors that
include the Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen and the venture
capitalist George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   But again, Branson may be a bit late, some contend. ``It's going
to take Virgin years to build a network,'' Yasskin said. ``And by
the time they do, they will have missed the huge growth period.
Anyway, the incumbents always have an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Branson nonetheless says that he will be able to compete with
established players like Vodafone. ``There is no reason we can't
offer anything that Vodafone can,'' he said. ``We will by no means
be as big as them, but we will have a slice of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   All of his businesses that have succeeded so far have done so by
carving out a niche in a mainstream industry by emphasizing service
and style _ whether it be Virgin Atlantic, with its interactive
movie and game system in every seat in economy class, or Virgin
Bride, a one-stop shop for weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin's philosophy, Branson said, is to improve upon
established businesses by adding a Virgin-esque sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   With Virgin Mobile, for example, he is taking the unusual step
of giving away an earpiece with a built-in microphone with each of
the company's mobile phones, so users do not have to hold them to
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine got a brain tumor, and before he died we had
dinner and he said his surgeon was convinced that using a mobile
phone may have been a factor,'' Branson said, raising a
product-liability specter that the head of a public company might
be likely to suppress.
</P>
<P>
   And the Virgin Web site will cater to Branson's digital naivete.
``Any jargon that I don't understand'' will be stripped out, he
said. ``I assume that I am representative of the vast majority of
the people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That thinking may explain why for Branson _ who in the past has
attempted a solo, round-the-world balloon flight and who owns an
island in the Caribbean _ taking his business onto the Internet
does not seem as as much fun as some of his previous endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't excite me in the same way that starting Virgin
Atlantic did,'' he admitted. ``It's because I could deal with
people. And with the Internet, you're one step removed from the
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
