<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-NAME-BATTLE-     02-13 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-NAME-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC ISLANDS SEEK CONTROL OF `DOT-COM' DESIGNATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 49 residents of Pitcairn Island, a British
territory in the South Pacific, are proud descendants of the
infamous Bounty mutineers. So perhaps it is fitting that they are
now leading a mutiny of sorts on the Internet _ a rebellion of the
little guys that has already spread to one other Pacific island and
is expected to mushroom among tiny nations and territories
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   What has these mini-polities in a roil is the loss of a dot and
two letters _ the suffixes originally assigned to denote the
territories in Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
   In Pitcairn's case, its suffix, known as a top-level domain, is
.pn, and it ended up controlled by a British company after Tom
Christian, the great-great-great-grandson of the Bounty's head
mutineer, Fletcher Christian, cut a deal with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Why are these little suffixes such hot properties? Because all
the good names that end in dot-com have been taken. So a customer
that wants, for example, a domain based on the name apple, goes to
one of dozens of renegade registrars around the globe and buys a
domain like apple.pn.
</P>
<P>
   But that practice may be about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a petition signed by all but two of Pitcairn's adult
inhabitants, the U.S. government and the Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, on Friday confiscated .pn
from the registrar company that had been passing it out and gave it
back to the island community.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unprecedented and controversial act, and Icann
officials expect it will be just the first of many showdowns
between early Internet profiteers and small countries and
territories. Because they were late to the Internet and e-commerce,
many of these tiny, often remote places are only now discovering
that the two-letter Internet addresses set aside for them in the
early 1990s have been lost to far-away companies.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Touton, Icann's vice president and general counsel, said
several small countries and territories had already made inquiries
about reclaiming their domains. He said that at its board meeting
in March, Icann, which runs the Internet's address system, expects
to consider a formal proposal to restore to all nations and
territories sovereign control of their domains.
</P>
<P>
   The next big showdown could come from another South Pacific
territory, American Samoa, whose designated country code, .as, is
similar to the English ``Inc.'' in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations that the governor of that island might have several
years ago signed it over to insiders to market at a profit in
Denmark has become a political scandal in Samoa, a cash-strapped
territory with a long history of political corruption.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, American Samoa's Legislature, or Fono, explored the
question of who gave control of .as to a Samoan man now living in
Hawaii and who was behind a partnership with a New York company
that markets it in Scandinavia.
</P>
<P>
   Afoa Lutu, director of the island's Legislative Reference
Bureau, said the investigation was started out of concern that the
territory's domain was being sold ``without any benefit to the
territory in times of deep financial trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Dot-as domains are currently available for $45 a year from a New
York company, GDNS. The number already registered is not known, and
GDNS officials could not be reached for comment on Friday. In the
past, however, one source close to the operation referred to it as
a ``nice little business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcairn's island council first began trying to reclaim its
domain in 1997, after the island realized it was seeing no
financial benefit from Christian's arrangement. The island
currently has just one satellite phone and no e-mail capabilities.
But Icann said the council wanted control of the domain both to
raise money to bring Internet connectivity to its residents and to
build a Web page with information about the island.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are 246 ``country codes,'' all of which were
created and assigned by Jon Postel, one of the Internet's founders.
The question of whether governments should be able to make
sovereign claims to them has been brewing since the Clinton
administration in 1998 selected Icann to take over international
administration of the domain name system.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Icann's government advisory committee is expected to
deliver its policy recommendations for handling such disputes.
Officials at the Commerce Department, which helped draft the
proposal, said the document was intended to preserve the spirit of
the informal and hard to implement rules that had been followed by
Postel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope,'' said Andrew J. Pincus, general counsel for the
department, ``is that these principles can be used to craft
agreements that facilitate delegation of'' the country codes ``in a
manner that serves the interests of the relevant local community
and reduce conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will be considered by Icann at its next board
meeting in Cairo on March 7 through 10.
</P>
<P>
   Critics assert that the document goes beyond Postel's informal
rules and gives too much power to governments and to Icann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The document, as I've seen it, is essentially a sop to Icann's
authority,'' said Antony Van Couvering, who works with a coalition
of companies that traffic in country-code domain names and opposes
giving countries sovereignty over their domain names.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in that (document) that talks about due
process for discovering if a domain has been badly managed,'' he
said. ``There's nothing in there that talks about what if it's
badly managed by a government.''
</P>
<P>
   Postel's original guidelines for country codes clearly stated
that to get control of a domain, a registrant had an
``administrative'' partner within the country or territory that
owned the suffix and that ``these designated authorities are
trustees for the delegated domain, and have a duty to serve the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Internet gold rush began, a number of companies
looking to enter the domain name registration business found codes
for islands and small countries that had not yet been assigned,
then found someone in those areas to get the domain for them.
</P>
<P>
   Those contacts were sometimes government officials, and the
agreements were not always just for profit. For example, the
profits from the sale of domains for the Cocos Islands, .cc and
.cs, have financed Internet connections for residents.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, however, the domains were set up with no formal
authorization, sometimes without the knowledge of the communities
in question. Such apparently is the case in American Samoa, where
the domain was claimed in 1997 by a man named Joseph Matua of AS
Domain Registry, whose address is a post office box in Pago Pago.
It is now being marketed by GDNS to companies in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to find out who gave permission or authority to
the private business to market the domain dot-as and what if any
benefits have been received by this private business in the
marketing of this,'' Lutu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here,'' he added, ``is what is the government
doing when its top domain is being used by a private company
without input, without policy guidelines _ and what benefits is the
American Samoa government receiving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
