<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEER-AD-COLUMN-NYT     02-13 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUINNESS TRIES LIGHTER IMAGE TO ATTRACT A NEW GENERATION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, Heineken has proclaimed in a popular British
campaign that it ``refreshes the parts other beers cannot reach.''
Now a British competitor of Heineken is mounting an ambitious
campaign in the United States, asserting that it offers similar
refreshment.
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness Bass Import Co., the unit of Diageo PLC that
distributes and markets Guinness stout in the United States, is
overhauling its sales pitch in substantive ways meant to make the
brand seem less intimidating to those Americans, particularly in
their mid-20s, who typically favor imported beers. That demographic
group is often put off by the iconic, even imperial, image of
Guinness _ not to mention widespread perceptions that it's more
sour and chewy than the signature bread of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A revamped advertising, promotional and public relations
campaign, carrying the new theme ``Guinness refreshes the spirit,''
began running last week. Guinness Bass plans to beef up the budget
for the campaign, with ads being created by the company's longtime
agency, Weiss Stagliano Partners in New York. Spending is to be
increased to $40 million for 2000 from the mid-$30 million range
previously; about half is for advertising and the rest for
promotions and public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The shifts for Guinness are indicative of the responses by a
wide variety of marketers to the challenges they face in seeking to
appeal to a generation of consumers substantially different from
its predecessors, yet still retain the loyalty of current, older
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comes from what our current consumers think of the
brand,'' said James Thompson, vice president for marketing at
Guinness Bass in Stamford, Conn., summarizing the results of
research, ``and from people who want to try the brand, who need
that extra push to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a momentum behind the Guinness brand, which has more
than doubled its sales in the U.S. in the last five years,'' he
added. ``But if we reached just 1 percent of the American beer
market, that would double our sales again.'' Guinness Bass shipped
9.5 million cases of Guinness to distributors in 1999, an increase
of 8.8 percent from 8.7 million cases in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign replaces one that has run in the United States
for almost three years and which was known as ``The perfect pint''
because it concentrated on the physical attributes of Guinness like
its color, creaminess and carbonation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally, we used to call it the Pavlov's dog campaign,''
said Adam Stagliano, president and account planning director at
Weiss Stagliano, because those ``very product-centric ads were
about the incredible power of Guinness, and the anticipatory
process of drinking the product, to get people salivating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted to celebrate product virtues, not combat
perceived vices,'' he added, referring to the beliefs that Guinness
is a heavy, highly caloric drink best when served warm. ``But if
you just play on the success of the past, you're already falling
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   So the new campaign, appearing in what Thompson called key
markets across America like Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles,
New York and San Francisco, is intended to eschew hero-izing the
sensory appeal of the product, he said, in favor of ``focusing much
more on the emotional benefit, which starts where the senses
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that ``whatever you're doing, Guinness can make it
just that little bit better,'' Thompson said. And that is conveyed
primarily by presenting the brand being enjoyed in a more rich
social context with greater energy and colors that have been
lightened up.
</P>
<P>
   Darker, moody ads, each of which showed a sole drinker
contemplating a glass of Guinness, are being supplanted by cheery
paeans to sociability that honor gregarious groups.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a television commercial begins with three friends
in a bar, then shifts to a surreal, brightly lighted reverie
involving a train filled with people singing ``Carmina Burana,'' a
1930s cantata that is featured in contemporary works of the
hip-hoppers Sean (Puffy) Combs and NAS.
</P>
<P>
   A humorous radio spot lays it on a bit thicker. An announcer
describes how someone sipping a Guinness ``is experiencing a
connectedness with his fellow Guinness drinkers, a shared
appreciation for their moment together'' and declares: ``That's
what Guinness is all about. Embracing life.''
</P>
<P>
   And pastel-colored print ads and posters associate Guinness with
vigorous activities like a crew team rowing on a river.
</P>
<P>
   Can the new tack work? There's a tale told along Madison Avenue
about the pitfalls of the previous approach: A British cigarette
brand named Strand was introduced with a campaign developed from a
research insight that smokers tended to see themselves as lone
wolves.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the story goes, the campaign came out with the
theme ``You're never alone with a Strand'' _ and British smokers
hated it. The reason? They believed buying the brand branded them
as lonely losers, not loners.
</P>
<P>
   So in America, where loneliness is typically deemed next to
godlessness, it makes sense to portray Guinness drinkers in
bunches. After all, even the bottles come in packs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
