<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., S.C.)  
 PERFECTING THE DOUBLE-DUTCH MACHINE  
 GREETING CARDS FOR HEALTH  
 NO MORE SOGGY BAGELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 of Tahira Reid is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1985, when Tahira Reid was in third grade at Public School 97
in the Bronx, she dreamed up an invention that would allow her to
double-dutch jump-rope even when she couldn't find two friends to
swing twin ropes in egg-beater fashion for her. Her poster drawing
of the hypothetical double-dutch machine won her a first prize in a
schoolwide competition.
</P>
<P>
   Reid went on to jump for a professional double-dutch team in
junior high, whirring in and out of the speedy ropes while she
danced hip-hop and performed gymnastics. But she didn't much think
about her double-dutch machine again until she was a sophomore at
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Troy, N.Y., and enrolled in an
introductory engineering design class whose theme was ``Challenging
the Limits in Sports and Recreational Activities.''
</P>
<P>
   There, with the help of classmates, she began working up a more
sophisticated version of her third-grade idea. Two and a half years
later, Reid, who is now a senior at RPI, has received a patent for
the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I just figured, hey, it would be a cool
project,'' Reid says. ``I didn't foresee a patent or anything.''
When Reid came up with her idea, recalls Burt Swersey, who teaches
a course in invention at RPI, ``I said, `Wow, this is a great idea.
There's a market for it but nobody's making it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reid is not the first to envision a double-dutch machine. A
handful of inventors have already patented different permutations
of the idea. But, according to Swersey, none of them is practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we teach here is that a lot of people have great ideas,
but you have to reduce them to practice,'' he said. Reid and a
group of students working on a second prototype hope eventually to
produce a double-dutch machine that can serve as a training device
for jumpers who want to hone their skills as well as for kids who
just want to have fun. Reid's fellow students currently on the
project are Kevin Haynes, Maneesh Shrivastav, Kwasi Frye and
Colleen Conlon.
</P>
<P>
   The machine consists of two drive systems that sit 10 to 15 feet
apart and about 30 inches off the ground. Each drive system has its
own motor, which, through the help of a set of pulleys, turns two
arms that grasp two different ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Two of these pulleys are connected with a belt configured in a
criss-cross manner. This criss-cross causes the ropes to turn in
the contrapuntal fashion that simulates the double-dutch pattern
that jump-roping children love.
</P>
<P>
   The double-dutch machine has already gotten some national
recognition. Two years ago Reid's team received a National
Collegiate Inventors and Innovators Alliance grant for $10,000 to
cover patent and prototype costs. And the device was part of an
alliance exhibit at the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum
of American History.
</P>
<P>
   Swersey acknowledged that Reid was still refining the invention.
``This double dutch is a good idea but the way it stands now it's
not quite right,'' he said. ``Tahira and her teammates are working
to come up with design features that will really make it low cost
and practical for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent 5,961,425 was assigned to Reid and to Andrew Burdick, an
aeronautical engineering student at RPI who worked on the original
prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Be My Valentine, and Get a Cancer Test
</P>
<P>
   There are as many ways to woo as there are varieties of candy in
a 2-pound Whitman's Sampler. Some suitors demonstrate their love
with flowers, others with perfume. But a Valentine's Day card that
features a colon-cancer screening kit?
</P>
<P>
   ``Colon cancer is the second-leading cause of cancer,'' said Dr.
March Seabrook, a gastroenterologist in West Columbia, S.C., who
has patented such a card. ``Unfortunately, we don't do a good job
screening for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook's card includes an at-home version of what is called a
``fecal occult blood test.'' The recipient smears a tiny stool
sample onto different testing strips and then mails the samples to
a laboratory, which tests for blood in the stool _ a sign of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   So far Seabrook produces only the birthday version, through his
company, Health Cards. But his patent says the cancer-screening
card can be tailored to any occasion: birthdays, Christmas, Yom
Kippur, Father's Day, Mother's Day and, of course, Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook received patent 5,954,369.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Coffee to Go, But Hold the Leaks
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers of all stripes are bound together by a single common
experience, according to Brett Stern, an industrial designer in
Manhattan. And that is? Leaking coffee cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning I go out for a cup of coffee and a bagel,''
Stern said. ``By the time I get to my office, the coffee has leaked
out of the top of the container, soaked the napkins and made the
bagel all soggy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern's solution is a dime-sized piece of hydrophobic material
that sticks on top of the coffee-lid vent hole. ``You need the vent
hole there to allow steam to escape,'' Stern said. ``Otherwise the
lid would pop off.''
</P>
<P>
   The material allows air molecules to escape but is impervious to
liquid molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, who is looking to license his invention, received patent
5,988,426.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
