<HEADLINE>
NEW AT&AMP;T SYSTEM DISPLAYS A `MILLIONAIRE' BONUS  
 THE DOCTOR IS NOW ONLINE AND TAKING REFERRALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There sure are a lot of people who want to be a millionaire
these days.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Bedminster, N.J., AT&AMP;T held a grand opening for
its new $90 million network operations center _ mission control for
one of the world's most complex communications webs.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders, or at least members of the media, are rarely invited
to peek behind AT&AMP;T's veil. So dozens of reporters showed up to ooh
and aah at the cavernous hall's complex-looking computer displays.
</P>
<P>
   But the most striking aspect of the event was only tangentially
related to AT&AMP;T _ although it was yet another testament to the
dominant television program at the moment, ABC's ``Who Wants to be
a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   On a wall screen, a computer displayed the number of current
business calls, compared with a chart for the previous Thursday,
Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The older chart showed a typical pattern, with a high volume of
calls during the day trailing off steeply into the evening. But the
graph showed a spectacular spike at 10 p.m., at the TV program's
conclusion, representing hundreds of thousands of calls to the
toll-free line for would-be contestants _ and untold revenue for
``our friends at AT&AMP;T,'' as the show's host, Regis Philbin, would
put it.
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   The Doctor Is Now Online, and He's Taking Referrals
</P>
<P>
   Forget toasters and airline miles _ and privacy, for that
matter. In what could be a first in Internet marketing, a new Web
site devoted to discussing sex and relationships is giving away
condoms to anyone who registers, and yet more condoms for referring
friends to the site.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is all part of the rollout of drDrew.com, an
online spinoff of the popular nighttime TV talk show and radio
program ``Loveline,'' starring Dr. Drew Pinsky, a 41-year-old
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Like the broadcast programs, the site is aimed at teen-agers and
young adults who are trying to sort out the issues of sex,
relationships and dating.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might be reluctant, of course, to give their own
names and e-mail addresses to a company distributing condoms. And
many other people might not want friends and colleagues to give out
theirs, either. But in fact, friends-and-family referrals are a
goal of the promotion; each referral that results in a registration
will yield another condom for the person who passed along the name
and address.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Sinclair, vice president of marketing for drDrew.com, said
the company was simply trying to promote safe sex, as well as
attract attention to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Although the registration form for the condoms asks for the
person's name, address, e-mail address, gender and age, the company
said it would use the street addresses only for mailing the condoms
and would not add those addresses to its database. Registered
members will receive drDrew.com's online newsletter and periodic
e-mails about future events.
</P>
<P>
   Members of drDrew.com can get advice on sex and sexual health
from Dr. Pinsky, as well as chat with other members, attend online
forums with celebrities and read features like ``Get a Life, Then
Get a Man'' or a how-to on preparing aphrodisiacs.
</P>
<P>
   Through the promotion, the Los Angeles-based company will send
out a three-pack of condoms, labeled with drDrew.com's logo, to
anybody who registers for the site or who has already registered.
The site's promoters plan to give away a million condoms through
the site, as well as on college campuses and at bars and nightclubs
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But be forewarned: One must be at least 16 years old to receive
the condoms; anyone younger than 16 who registers for the site will
receive drDrew.com stickers instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
</TEXT>
