<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANISH-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     02-13 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANISH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DANISH GIRL': RADICAL CHANGE AND ENDURING LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The historical fact is that in 1931 a Danish painter named Einar
Wegener became the first man ever to be transformed surgically into
a woman, changing her name to Lili Elbe and eventually leaking her
story to the press. In ``The Danish Girl'' David Ebershoff uses the
bare facts of Wegener-Elbe's story to summon a rich imagined
universe in which the main event is less the sexual transformation
itself than the way that transformation affected other people.
</P>
<P>
   This is Ebershoff's first novel, and it is a promising one.
``The Danish Girl,'' as Ebershoff tells us in a helpful afterword,
does not try to tell a true story. He has not only imagined most of
what he writes about Wegener's inner life, but he has also
fabricated all of the other characters in the book, most important
among them Wegener's blue-blooded American-born wife, Greta Waud,
who like Ebershoff comes from Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his novel, which takes place in Copenhagen, Paris and
Dresden (where the historical Wegener underwent his surgery), is
told with such psychological delicacy that one has the sense things
must actually have transpired the way Ebershoff presents them. His
writing is of a highly refined kind; his story is marvelously
furnished with period details, from the smell of the Danish cheese
that drifted from next door into a Copenhagen art gallery to the
look of the Elbe River in the early Dresden spring. Most important,
Ebershoff has written an unusual and affecting love story centering
on a confrontation with the mystery of the other.
</P>
<P>
   What makes his imaginative elaboration of a real historical case
especially compelling is his portrayal of Greta, who is a
wonderfully successful character, more so in many ways than Einar.
As the story begins, Greta and Einar are in their Copenhagen home
painting when Greta asks her husband to do her a favor. Will he
model a pair of shoes and a dress that she is using in a portrait
of Anna Fonsmark, a Danish opera singer who has failed to arrive
for a sitting?
</P>
<P>
   Einar puts on the dress, feeling its silky texture, and then:
``A strange watery feeling was filling Einar as he stood on the
lacquer trunk, the sunlight moving across him, the scent of herring
in the air...Einar was beginning to enter a shadowy world of dreams
where Anna's dress could belong to anyone, even to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Einar's reverie is interrupted by the appearance of
Anna herself, who along with Greta jokes about his appearance.
``Greta said, her voice soft and careful and unfamiliar, `Why don't
we call you Lili?'''
</P>
<P>
   From that point, though the central event of the book is Einar's
inexorable transformation into Lili, Ebershoff's story belongs to
Greta and the quietly determined struggle she wages to allow her
love to triumph over her needs. Ebershoff sketches in a rebellious
and privileged life for Greta: her escape from the rigorously
conventional environs of Pasadena (where a first marriage ended
tragically) to the life of a Copenhagen portrait painter.
</P>
<P>
   She is the kind of woman who, as Ebershoff writes, could ``cross
her mother and debate her father and snub all of Pasadena and
Copenhagen alike, but in her chest was a bottomless well of
tolerance for the man she loved.'' She could say to herself that
she had no interest in dining with her husband, who was dressed up
as a girl, but she ``would keep such a thought to herself, biting
her lip until she could taste her own blood.''
</P>
<P>
   While Greta emerges with complexity and fullness, Ebershoff
doesn't manage quite as well with Einar and Lili, who are treated
all along as two separate people, as if in deference to Einar's own
preference in the matter. Lili's belief that she possesses an
individual will separate from Einar's and her early experiences of
sexual awareness are presented with a wonderful, believable
intimacy. The game that Einar plays, that he and Lili are not the
same person but live lives entirely apart from each other, is also
an element of stubborn reality that makes up a part of the
challenge to Greta's love and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But this game strangely limits Einar as a character, making him
into something so automatic and unreflective as to strain
psychological credibility. Similarly, in Ebershoff's handling of
it, Lili's experience takes place in such a circumscribed world
that it presents almost no practical complications for Greta.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that Ebershoff wanted to avoid any of the cheap
situation-comedy possibilities that Einar-Lili would present. But
in doing so, he skips over events _ like Einar-Lili's meeting in
Paris with a childhood friend with whom he once had a tormented
homoerotic relationship _ that would have caused more turbulence
than they do in the sometimes unconvincingly subtle world of ``The
Danish Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are small questions about a book whose core, the
patient and enduring love that Greta forges for her husband and
that her husband fails to understand, is complex and deep. There is
a moment near the end of the novel when Lili, her transformation
nearly complete, says something that for the first time brings
Greta face to face with the fullness of her loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and me, we were married,'' Greta says quietly, ``and we
lived in that small dark space between two people where a marriage
exists.'' That statement is a kind of mourning, a valediction, and
it is also a poignant evocation of the human condition. Ebershoff
is telling us that love does involve a small dark space. The
intelligence and tactfulness of his exploration of it make his
novel a noteworthy event.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DANISH GIRL'
</P>
<P>
   By David Ebershoff
</P>
<P>
   270 pages. Viking. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1744EST &QL; 
