<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT RETREATS ON RESIGNATION ORDER TO ACCUSED
GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ President Abdurrahman Wahid changed tack
Sunday and told his defiant security minister _ Indonesia's most
prominent general _ that he could keep his job while he is
investigated for human-rights abuses in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him to resign but he said he preferred to be
investigated by a legal process, and I said, `OK,''' Wahid said
after a two-hour meeting with his security minister, General
Wiranto. ``We have to give him a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first direct demand by the president, who returned
Sunday from a two-week tour abroad during which he had prodded
Wiranto almost daily to step down. And it was the first direct
refusal by the general.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's acceptance of the refusal was seen here as a retreat,
although there may be other steps yet to come in what may be an
elaborate and face-saving game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Many Indonesians remained confused by their garrulous president,
and some analysts said he may have devalued the power of his word
by failing to demand obedience.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it was notable that during two weeks of
sparring, Wiranto failed to garner strong support from within the
military, with several prominent commanders asserting their
allegiance to civilian control.
</P>
<P>
   While the president may have appeared weak or vacillating in
terms of his personal command, he did emphasize the supremacy of
law Sunday, placing the general's fate in the hands of the attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would allow Wiranto to wait until the attorney
general decides whether he should stand trial for the violence and
destruction that followed a vote last August in East Timor for
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the right to change my ministers,'' the president said.
``But we have to abide by the law. If the results of the report
implicate him, then he must resign, as I have already said
before.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what he has said is that he wanted the general to
resign immediately, even before any results or preliminary findings
are made. But he has declined to exercise his right to fire his
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman said Sunday that he would
immediately form a team to investigate accusations contained in a
report by a special government commission that named Wiranto as
``morally responsible'' for the horror in East Timor because he was
commander of the armed forces at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid began demanding Wiranto's resignation as soon as the
report was issued. The general had already been weakened two days
earlier when the president ordered his removal from the military
because he is a serving cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   The president's confusing style seems to have the effect of
pummeling his targets in his chosen direction with a mixture of
verbal rabbit punches, jokes and expressions of personal regard. He
is a difficult man to understand or to grapple with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem,'' he said Sunday. ``Wiranto and I are
good friends. It is the media that perceives us to be enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president must be held responsible for the perceptions
of the media, said Dewi Fortuna Anwar, a political analyst who was
a top aide to former president B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   The past two weeks had created unnecessarily a sense of
nervousness and uncertainty, including a surge of coup rumors to
which Wahid had himself contributed directly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are the losers here,'' she said of the president and the
general. ``And it was quite unnecessary. And it could all have been
done in a more dignified way.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the president had stated that one reason he
wanted the general to resign was to strengthen confidence among
foreign investors and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the effect, in the short term at least, may have been the
opposite. Jakarta's stock exchange and the value of its currency
have slipped during the past two weeks and some analysts said they
expected further slippage in the coming week following Sunday's
seeming retreat by Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his seemingly impulsive verbal fits and starts, however,
there is a consistent direction to the president's policies, toward
democracy, openness, tolerance and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to rule by fiat, Wahid is revolutionizing leadership
in Indonesia following 32 years of autocratic rule by former
president Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   By delegating the outcome of his standoff with Wiranto to his
highly respected attorney general, Wahid is subordinating both the
executive and the military to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia under Suharto, the law and the courts were simply
tools of his personal policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the strands of these changes will intersect as
Suharto faces a court summons on charges of corruption. He is
expected to try to avoid the summons by pleading ill health. But
the coinciding legal proceedings against the general and the former
president signal broad changes for Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
