<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ANGOLA-WAR-NYT &LR;      02-13 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS SEIZE THE OFFENSIVE AGAINST GOVERNMENT TROOPS IN ANGOLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RACHEL SWARNS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUAMBO, Angola _ The astonishing news crackled over the radios
in this crumbling town of faded colonial mansions and rolling green
hills. One by one, the radio announcer said, the nearby rebel
strongholds were falling into government hands.
</P>
<P>
   And for three months, hope blossomed here.
</P>
<P>
   The mortars stopped falling. Relief workers made plans to send
thousands of refugees home. And Silvano Chingala Mindo, a
19-year-old student who saw his two friends killed by shrapnel last
October, began to believe he might live long enough to become a
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the waves of war are once again lapping over
Angola, and over this weary city. The guerrillas are storming
through the countryside, villagers are fleeing to refugee camps and
the fragile hopes that buoyed this bullet-pocked town are waning.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of back-to-back victories late last year, the
government apparently thought it had finally triumphed over the
guerrillas known as Unita _ &UR;  &LR; the Portuguese acronym for the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, which until
1975 was a Portuguese colony. Now, in the seemingly endless war
that has raged ever since, pitting Unita's leader, Jonas Savimbi,
against his fierce rival, President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the
rebels have seized the offensive once more.
</P>
<P>
   Unita claims to have killed 882 government soldiers over the
past month. This week, the government, which had repeatedly boasted
that it had destroyed 80 percent of Unita's war machine, publicly
acknowledged that the battle is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Paulina Wenda discovered the rebels were still a potent force
last week when they opened fire on her village in nearby Mbave. She
grabbed her children and they ran barefoot, leaving their hut,
their pots, their clothes, their land.
</P>
<P>
   She had heard the radio broadcasts and the government officials
who claimed they were finally winning. ``But there's no
difference,'' Wenda, 35, said wearily as she stood in a refugee
camp near here. ``We're still losing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Military experts say the government underestimated Unita, and
they predict the guerrillas will continue fighting to capitalize on
the rainy season here that has hobbled the government's tanks and
jets in thick mud and dense clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had Unita on their knees and it's not so,''
said Johann Smith, a military analyst, who served as the South
African Defense Force's attache to Luanda, the capital here, in
1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've absorbed the initial shock of the successes against
them,'' said Smith, who still monitors the conflict and Unita.
``They're up and running. And they're definitely going to use this
window of time to strengthen their position.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the action has been military, however. After the
government drove the rebels from their traditional strongholds of
Bailundo, Andulo and Jamba between September and December last
year, Unita announced that it wanted to reopen negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast on government radio last week, dos Santos
said he believed Angola was stable enough to hold national
elections next year and invited Unita's soldiers to lay down their
arms and organize their political party.
</P>
<P>
   That news was enough for Veronica Chilombo, 36, who lost her
left leg in an accident, to leave her village, which had been under
rebel control. For two days, she hobbled on wooden crutches until
she reached a hospital here in government-controlled Huambo, where
she could finally ask for an artificial leg.
</P>
<P>
   Valdemar Franco Secesec, a 25-year-old nurse, said he was
heartened by commercial flights flying into the airport again and
the trucks rolling in on roads that were once too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have hope that one day soon this war will end,'' Franco
said. ``You have to have hope. There is nothing else to keep us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been no clear signs that the two sides will
actually come together.
</P>
<P>
   The war here used to have an ideological base: dos Santos was
backed by Russia and Cuba, Savimbi by the United States. Gradually,
it has turned into more of a battle for Angola's huge spoils _ the
oil controlled by the government, and the diamond mines by Unita.
</P>
<P>
   There is still much finger-pointing on both sides about the
failure of the 1994 peace treaty that gave Angola its longest
cease-fire in 30 years. The fighting resumed in 1998, with Unita
initially making strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of easing, this civil war has now spread beyond its
borders, spilling into neighboring Namibia, which late last year
allowed the Angolan government to fight from its soil, where the
conflict has already claimed dozens of civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the two sides talk peace and wage war, and ordinary
people suffer. Strangely enough, in this still-graceful town of
red-tile roofs and elegant leafy plazas, such contradictions seem
oddly logical.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is a place where the only hotel has shiny water
faucets, but no running water; light switches, but no electricity
during the day. A graffiti artist has scrawled the word ``paz'' or
``peace'' on a building still riddled with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a war that ebbs and flows, where the winners on one day
are often the losers on the next. The government controls most of
the cities and towns, but Unita is still strong in the countryside.
And it is often difficult to tell where and when the fighting ends
and the peace begins.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Doctors Without Borders, which runs a clinic for
refugees here, accepted the official word about peace in the
region, and sent trucks rumbling out into the countryside to screen
poor children for malnutrition. But two weeks ago, they stopped,
frightened by new reports of violence and by the shelling that
jolted their nurses from sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local staff didn't want to go anymore,'' said Gunilla
Priebe, a nurse with the organization. ``And we trust their
information more than the official information. It's more
reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals, teen-agers like Chingala, gossip and giggle and lean
against a dilapidated building that has long since lost its glass
windows and wooden doors. The girls laugh when asked whether they
think the war is ending. It is something they cannot imagine. All
they know is war.
</P>
<P>
   Chingala does not laugh. He was walking home from school with
his friends last October when the shell exploded. He survived
unscathed, but when he saw their bloodied bodies, he thought he saw
his own fate.
</P>
<P>
   And so he prays for peace because he wants to grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if peace stays, I will have a future,'' he said.
``They say Unita has no longer any possibility to win offensives. I
heard it on the radio. I just hope it's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
