<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      02-13 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TARGET DATE FOR ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN   AGREEMENT REMAINS ELUSIVE
 (ms)  
By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A target date for a framework agreement on a
permanent peace between Israelis and Palestinians slipped by here
Sunday as contacts between the two sides remained frozen, with no
signs that the impasse might be broken.
</P>
<P>
   At a cabinet meeting largely devoted to the recent flare-up of
violence in Lebanon, Prime Minister Ehud Barak reportedly said that
a few more weeks of discussions on the framework accord were
preferable to moving straight into talks on a full peace treaty, as
suggested by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Oded Eran, the chief Israeli negotiator, said that if
negotiations resumed, a framework accord could be reached in
another four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the talks have ground to a halt. The Palestinians
suspended them last week, a few days after a Feb. 3 meeting between
Barak and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader. The meeting ended
in disagreement over the area of the next scheduled West Bank land
transfer when the Israelis ruled out a handover of villages around
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate doomed the Feb. 13 deadline, so when it came and
went Sunday there was no surprise, only a deepening sense that the
momentum of peace efforts generated by Barak in his first months in
office had all but evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli commentators wondered whether Barak's ambitious
deadlines for progress in peace talks would prove nothing more than
hollow boasts. Shimon Peres, the former prime minister who serves
in Barak's cabinet, said Sunday that the target dates were risky
gambles.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the latest Israeli-Palestinian accord, a
permanent peace agreement is supposed to be reached by Sept. 13,
resolving such profoundly divisive issues as the future of
Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees and Jewish settlements, and the
delineation of borders. But after Sunday's missed target date for a
framework accord, the prospects for concluding a comprehensive
treaty in seven months seemed decidedly dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Yaser Abed Rabbo, the chief Palestinian negotiator, put the
blame squarely on Israel, saying that it had ``violated'' the
deadline while reneging on commitments to hand over more West Bank
land to the Palestinians under the terms of interim peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Growing Palestinian frustration with Barak was reflected in a
poll published Sunday indicating rising support among Palestinians
for armed attacks against Israel. In the poll, conducted by the
Center for Palestine Research and Study in Nablus, support for
armed attacks had risen to 43 percent among those polled, the
highest since June of last year, when Barak took over from his
right-wing predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu. The margin of error is
3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police went on alert Sunday after receiving information
pointing to a planned terrorist attack, setting up checkpoints on
roads leading to and from the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
