<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEWYORKER-CARTOONS-AR     02-13 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORKER-CARTOONS-ART-1195(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAGGLE OF CARTOONISTS, BUT IT'S NOT ALL SMILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under the fine lines and smooth washes of The New
Yorker's cartoons, it is stormy weather. The magazine's funnymen
are frowning.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5 a small gallery in Manhattan, Davis &AMP; Langdale, held a
reception for ``Artists of The New Yorker,'' a show to celebrate
the magazine's 75th anniversary. It was not an official New Yorker
party. It was not even a big party. But it was an event.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran New Yorker artists mixed with newcomers: Robert Weber,
James Stevenson, Al Ross, Frank Modell, Michael Maslin, Lee Lorenz,
Arnie Levin, Edward Koren, Liza Donnelly and Roz Chast rubbed
shoulders with Jules Feiffer, David Levine, Ed Sorel and Danny
Shanahan. Dead artists _ Ludwig Bemelmans, Whitney Darrow Jr.,
Helen Hokinson and Charles Saxon _ watched from their drawings on
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   There were some notable absences, too. The New Yorker's cartoon
editor, Robert Mankoff; its art editor, Francoise Mouly; and her
husband, Art Spiegelman, the most controversial new New Yorker
artist, were not at the party.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was no insurrection, but protest was in the air.
The cartoonists who looked back at the magazine's history were
hardly misty-eyed. At the reception and in private interviews, they
smoldered and wondered at the changes they had seen.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about all the editors: They talked about Harold Ross
as if he were a god. They talked about William Shawn as if he were
their lost daddy. They talked about Tina Brown as if she were a
cold date. They talked about kitsch. They talked about abandonment.
Some said that the old New Yorker style they had helped to create
lay in ruins. Others said it was about time.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and '30s, when Ross was editor and Rea Irvin was
art editor, The New Yorker helped create the idea of cosmopolitan
Manhattan. In time, as editors got married and moved to the
suburbs, the style became more suburban. The city still appeared in
The New Yorker, but by the 1950s it had become, as Koren put it,
``a memory of urban life.''
</P>
<P>
   For cartoonists, said Lorenz, a former art editor and artist for
the magazine since 1958, ``coming into New York was a social
occasion.'' Most of them lived outside the city. ``You would come
in one day a week, drop off the material. You would start making
rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker was the first stop. The magazine paid per square
inch of published work, and cartoonists often drew big, hoping for
more money. (Now it's a flat payment: $1,200 for a cartoon; $4,000
for the first cover and an additional $500 for each successive one
in the same year.)
</P>
<P>
   After the New Yorker stop, they moved on: Collier's, The
Saturday Evening Post, Esquire, Sports Illustrated, Ladies' Home
Journal, American Legion, True, Cavalier, Playboy. ``At the end of
the day,'' Lorenz said, ``you'd go to `1,000 Jokes,' published by
Dell, and the editor would sop up whatever was left.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a Tuesday trip and a Wednesday trip, said Koren, the
master of fuzzy creatures, who started at The New Yorker in the
mid-1960s. Tuesdays were for the heavy hitters: Charles Addams,
Barney Tobey, George Price, William Steig, Peter Arno. Wednesdays
were for newcomers. ``For lunch we'd go to the Blue Ribbon or the
Lobster,'' Koren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross had a great sensibility about what cartoonists could
do,'' said Modell, who started drawing for The New Yorker in 1945.
``Some did horses well, others did automobiles. I did angry men and
sexy women and dogs. George Price drew angry men but not
businessmen. Whitney Darrow did businessmen. Dedini, Darrow and
Arno did sexy women. Hokinson did club ladies. There were only two
types of women in those days, sexy doxies and wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the steady artists were fed ideas and captions by
gagmen. And if you wanted to become a New Yorker cartoonist, being
a gagman was a way to get your foot in the door. Stevenson, a
writer and cartoonist known for his loose drawings of the perplexed
middle class, remembers his start. Beginning in 1956 he sold gags
for $75 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't supposed to tell anyone what I did. Cartoonists
wanted people to think they were funny,'' he said. ``If someone did
ask what I did for The New Yorker, I'd just say, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to get in, so one of the growth industries at
The New Yorker was bringing bad news. After James Geraghty became
art editor in 1939, he hired Modell as his assistant. ``I was a hit
man,'' Modell said. ``If an idea was OK'd, Geraghty would see the
cartoonist. But if it was a rejection, he would say, `Frank will
see him.' The mortality rate was worse than for babies in 1910
Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid awkward encounters with expectant artists and writers,
Ross kept building more walls. George Booth, who started drawing
his mad bull-terriers and psychotic cats for The New Yorker in the
1970s, has done some historical research: ``At one point a mirror
was hung up in the hallway so you could see who was coming in and
not run into him. It was a lovely atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell recalled an encounter with James Thurber: ``I was the new
boy. I heard someone coming down the hall'' toward a steep
stairway. ``He was a tall, lanky, thin guy. He was practically
blind and not opposed to having more drink than he should. He had
his hand over one eye to put all the energy he had for vision into
the one good eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell continued: ``I became worried. If I let a million-dollar
talent kill himself falling down the stairway, what would happen to
me?'' He touched Thurber's shoulder and asked, ``Can I help you?''
Thurber bellowed, ``Get out of my way,'' and then, Modell recalled,
``he went down like a stack of dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Modell said, ``it was an absolutely utopian time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the bomb dropped. The Newhouse family took over the
magazine, fired Shawn and put Robert Gottlieb in his place. ``When
Shawn's time came to an end, we were all shocked and hurt,'' Modell
said. ``We lost Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The betrayal was not only personal but aesthetic, or so many of
the old cartoonists think. ``Gottlieb liked wordplay, puns, and
some thought it was horrible,'' said Sorel, who now draws covers
for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Tina Brown. ``Tina wanted the magazine to be
competitive on the newsstand,'' Lorenz said. ``She began to
encourage material that was right on top of the news. There were
pictures of the Clintons, the Bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnie Levin, the cartoonist of loopy lines, said, ``There would
be 40 artists piling up on the same topic.''
</P>
<P>
   And the effect? The cartoons are ``not quite as philosophically
pointed as they used to be,'' and ``the drawing has diminished,''
Koren said.
</P>
<P>
   Modell said, ``There's no heart there, and you can feel the
effort of the artist, how he has his hand on the pulse of the
world.'' But not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people look back, they say cartoons aren't as funny
today,'' said Chast, who specializes in drawing homely types with
odd domestic obsessions. ``But if you pick up any issue from any
year, maybe two or three cartoons are complete side splitters, and
two or three completely miss the boat, and the rest will be OK,
funny but not sublime.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chast was once accused of drawing badly. When she started
appearing in The New Yorker in 1978, ``she caused tremendous
anger,'' Lorenz said. ``She was primitive. She made no attempt to
have correct perspective. And there were letters from people
canceling their subscriptions. Other artists were angry, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But now almost every New Yorker artist reveres her. Chast knows
that there's ``less emphasis on the craft of drawing,'' she said,
but she does not think that means standards have disappeared. ``I
like a drawing not to repel me.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, both inside and outside The New Yorker, many
cartoonists are striving for a certain arty repulsiveness.
``There's a whole generation of younger cartoonists inspired by R.
Crumb, Art Spiegelman, Bill Griffith and Harvey Kurtzman,'' Jules
Feiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   With traces of underground styles reaching The New Yorker, some
of the old cartoonists have found themselves out of work. ``When
Tina came, it was like kissing a beautiful girl and not getting
kissed back,'' Modell said. ``Tina never bought any drawings of
mine. Now I'm like an old mule who still goes to the pump. If I
have an idea, I have to get rid of it, so I'll fax it to The New
Yorker, then Playboy.'' But lately, he said, he has sold nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Booth is more philosophical: ``I haven't done any covers since
the 1980s. But things go in cycles, and you just pull your skivvies
up around your armpits and go on.'' He continued: ``I think The New
Yorker wouldn't be in existence if Tina Brown hadn't come in and
raised hell. She was running into an audience that didn't read.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartoons, Modell noted, are there to defuse readers' anxieties
about encountering ``great slabs of type,'' the way clowns defuse
the intensity of the high-wire act. ``But now,'' he added,
``there's so much cacophony _ photos, ads _ that there's no need
for cartoonists. If I ran the magazine, I wouldn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some people who don't lament the lost New Yorker. Not
surprisingly, they are the ones who made their reputations
elsewhere. Surprisingly, they are among the few who actually live
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a reader of The New Yorker, and I didn't have the
ambition to be a New Yorker cartoonist,'' said David Levine, who is
best known for his pen-and-ink caricatures in The New York Review
of Books but now does pencil caricatures for The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a gag cartoonist. Two years ago Tina Brown called me
to have lunch. She was fighting for a losing magazine. She decided
caricature was the only entertaining way for the public to deal
with the onslaught of interviews and biographies. Her changes were
made to fit the craving of an audience no longer as literate as it
had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer, who is known for his squiggly, talking-head cartoons in
The Village Voice, has a similar story. ``I grew up reading The New
Yorker, but it was the furthest thing from my ideal. I was too
Bronx for Arno. I grew up loving comic strips.''
</P>
<P>
   And what he calls his ``abrasive social and political
commentary'' was far from The New Yorker's ideal. ``William Shawn
broke out in hives when he saw my stuff, but Tina didn't have that
problem. She wanted me in the first issue.''
</P>
<P>
   So under a host of pressures the old cartoon culture has
crumbled. Few cartoonists go into the city regularly. Many have
families and other jobs _ as animators, artists and authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized the fax machine worked fine,'' Chast said.
</P>
<P>
   Koren said: ``The collegiality has evaporated.''
</P>
<P>
   Mischa Richter, 90, who started drawing cartoons 45 years ago,
said: ``The New Yorker made celebrities once. Now it wants
celebrities to make The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   Even drawing itself may be in decline. ``Kids don't draw
anymore,'' Sorel said. ``Comic art in America started at the turn
of the century, and it's ending at the turn of another century.
There is no longer a New Yorker style. Anything goes. A New Yorker
cartoon is anything the editor says it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell takes a simpler view of the new New Yorker: ``I could be
a great admirer if they would buy my cartoons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
