<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-VALENTINE-495&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THEIR FUNNY VALENTINE, ALL 4 TONS OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Jim Seiple, 21, wanted to take his girlfriend,
Stephanie Cahill, 19, someplace special for an early Valentine's
Day celebration. So Seiple, a clerk at Shop Rite, took Cahill, a
hospital dietitian, to Philadelphia's most famous heart _ the
18-foot tall, 4-ton papier-mache and fiberglass model at the
Franklin Institute, the science museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better thing to see than the big heart?'' said Seiple,
who was marking the holiday early because he had to work late on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs expensive, candlelit restaurants? One of the most
romantic places in Philadelphia turns out to be a science exhibit
intended to teach schoolchildren about the circulatory system.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Cataldi, the host of a morning radio show here, was
married in front of the heart on the last day of 1999 by his friend
Edward Rendell, the former mayor. The heart was a fallback
location. Rendell had originally suggested that he marry Cataldi
and his fiancee, Gail Cox, at the convention center that afternoon
_ just the two of them, and 999 other couples who happened to have
registered for the millennium wedding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox ``didn't like the idea of the 2,000 people,'' Cataldi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we said to the mayor, `Is there any chance we could have a
private wedding?' He said, `I'm doing something at the Franklin
Institute at 11. How about the heart?'''
</P>
<P>
   Cataldi agreed, with one stipulation: ``I said, `OK, we'll do it
at the heart, but you have to turn off the thump. The thump grosses
me out.'''
</P>
<P>
   The model, which visitors can climb through, has a soundtrack
that loudly simulates the sound of a heartbeat. The museum turned
it off long enough for the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Now the museum is considering what it is calling a heart
transplant. The model may be moved to another wing as part of a $50
million renovation designed to bring the 67-year-old building's
low-tech exhibits into the high-tech present. The heart shares
space with the Wright brothers' biplane, the hall of electricity _
with simulated thunder and lightning and a van de Graaf generator
that makes static electricity _ and a planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   The question museum officials are asking is: Can the heart,
which was created as a temporary exhibit, survive the move?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a little bit of papier-mache and fiberglass and
chicken wire with a thump in the background,'' said the institute's
president, Dennis M. Wint. ``The problem is our doorways are
smaller than the heart.'' In order to move it, the model would have
to be dismantled and put together again.
</P>
<P>
   As visitors climb through the pink, red and blue heart, they
follow the path of the red blood cells. Touring it the other day,
Jeff Guaracino, the museum spokesman, said that he, too, has come
under the model's romantic spell. ``I will tell you I had a kiss in
the heart,'' he said, recalling a recent visit with a date. ``It
was at the right ventricle. It was just a spur-of-the-moment kiss
in the heart.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For nearly 50 years the heart has been a popular landmark for
children on school trips. Strolling through the heart, Guaracino
was surrounded by a group of laughing, screaming, shouting boys and
girls from St. Andrew's elementary school in suburban Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Kirk, 10, said she felt inspired. ``I want to be a heart
surgeon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Shay, 8, said: ``I like the veins. They're blue. That's my
favorite color.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Ford, 9, took a decidedly unromantic view of the exhibit.
``What I like about the heart is that it looks exactly like the
heart _ not a Valentine's card.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
