<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MOSER-PROFILE-NYT     02-13 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBASSADOR FIGHTS TO RESTORE AUSTRIA'S IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the diplomat's smile, the fatigue showed on
the face of Ambassador Peter Moser, Austria's representative to the
United States, the lack of sleep etched beneath his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He had been up since  just as he had every morning for
most of the last two weeks, making urgent telephone calls to the
Foreign Ministry in Vienna. He dispatched his wife to her sister's
home in New York, knowing that it would be impossible to find time
for her in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nightmare,'' he said of what has gone on since Feb.
4, with the swearing-in of a new Austrian government that includes
the far-right, anti-immigration Freedom Party led by Joerg Haider,
who has praised some of Hitler's employment policies. ``You think
of the job of a diplomat as a dream under usual circumstances,''
Moser said. ``Well, what is going on now is the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not feel real,'' he said. ``It is surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day the embassy's mailbag bulges with scores of letters
from Americans condemning Austria; some are filled with threats and
obscenities. ``There are serious letters, and then others are just
offensive,'' said Moser, a 58-year-old career diplomat. ``Maybe
people get a personal relief if they call us names.''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a coalition government that includes Haider's
party has turned Austria into a pariah within the 15-nation
European Union, which has severed routine contacts with Vienna. The
Clinton administration has protested by withdrawing the American
ambassador, and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger has been
warning of the possible emergence of ``the extreme hateful right''
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has forced Moser to dive into the whirlpool of
Washington's 24-hour news cycle, as he tries to persuade Americans
_ and the large foreign press corps based here _ that Austria is
being unfairly tarred.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 days, there have been appearances on CNN and on
PBS' ``NewsHour,'' as well as a news conference on Friday at the
National Press Club, the first solo news conference in Moser's
33-year career in the Austrian diplomatic service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haider is not Austria, and Austria is not Haider,'' he said at
the press club on Friday in a sometimes awkward effort to distance
the people ria from the government that they have put in
place _ and that he must now represent.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that while the Freedom Party might be xenophobic, it
was not fascist, and that while Haider might be a hot-headed
opportunist prone to outrageous remarks (such as his praise for
Nazi labor policies and for the veterans of the SS), he is not a
Nazi. ``We from the diplomatic establishment have to walk behind
him, after him, and pick up the pieces,'' Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his spacious office in the Austrian embassy, Moser
took a seat at a small conference table and slowly sipped from a
glass of water. Behind his desk was a stack of papers, topped by an
English translation of a book by Haider outlining his right-wing
political philosophy. On the cover is a photo of the well-tanned,
carefully coifed, ever-grinning politician, who could easily pass
for an American television anchorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was given to me,'' the ambassador says. ``I don't think I
will read it.''
</P>
<P>
   He resists offering a personal appraisal of Haider's character.
``My personal feelings, I am not being paid for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to salvage Austria's reputation was certainly not the
assignment Moser expected when he arrived in Washington last year.
His initial goal, he said, was to expand trade and to encourage
Americans to think of his nation of 8 million people as the
economic hub of central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion as a professional diplomat is that I'm
very sad and sorry because what we built up over the years is now
being questioned,'' he said of Austria's efforts since World War II
to portray itself as a peace-loving member of the European
community, and to distance itself from its Nazi past, when Austria
embraced German rule under the Austrian-born Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was unfair to single out Austria for condemnation
when political parties similar to Haider's exist across Europe and
could, like the Freedom Party, enter government someday soon. ``One
day they will wake up and find that they have similar problems,''
he said. ``All of these remarks of Haider, which remember the Nazi
history, are a wonderful instrument to distract attention from this
fact.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not deny, however, that his job is made more difficult
by the perception that Austria is unwilling to confront its
history, a view that grew stronger outside Austria after voters
there elected Kurt Waldheim president in 1986 despite revelations
about his service in Hitler's army. ``Yes, I think there are many
people _ not only in the Freedom Party, but many, particularly
older people _ who have not done this process of atonement,'' Moser
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador could be considered another victim of the war. He
never knew his father, an Austrian soldier in the German army, who
was sent off to the front two days after his only child was born in
Vienna in June 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born on a Saturday and he left on a Monday,'' the
ambassador said. After his father died in German-occupied Lithuania
in 1943, ``my mother brought me up alone,'' he said. `'She couldn't
remarry because there were not many men after the war. She worked
hard at whatever job she could get.''
</P>
<P>
   He did well in school, received a law degree in 1964 and entered
Austria's diplomatic academy the next year. His career as a
diplomat has taken him to posts as diverse as New Delhi, India;
Seoul, South Korea; and Sofia, Bulgaria. His favorite posting was
in Los Angeles, where he was consul general from 1979 to 1985. ``We
lived in a house with a swimming pool in a wonderful neighborhood,
just outside Santa Monica,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the carefree sunshine of southern California is far from his
thoughts these days, as Moser rushes through Washington's winter
chill from one difficult interview to another, trying to limit what
he acknowledges is the ``permanent damage'' to Austria's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst is over, I think the crisis is over,'' he
said. ``But when the dust settles, it will be a lot of work for us
to get back what we have lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
