<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ZEILE-NYT &LR;      02-13 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ZEILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' ZEILE WOULD RATHER SWITCH THAN FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todd Zeile was asked to switch to first base before, and he was
furious. Zeile was in his first full season with the St. Louis
Cardinals in 1990 and had been assured by his manager _ Joe Torre _
that he would be the everyday catcher, that there were no plans to
shift him to another position to get playing time for Tom Pagnozzi.
</P>
<P>
   When Pedro Guerrero got hurt, however, Torre plugged the hole by
moving Zeile to first and using Pagnozzi as the catcher, and Zeile
was angry. ``I think he looked at it like he had failed,'' Torre
said recently, in a phone interview. ``He was pretty steamed.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch lasted exactly 11 games, and although Torre made
Zeile his permanent third baseman the next year, Zeile has long
since gotten over his reluctance to change positions. He will be
the Mets' first baseman this season, stepping in where John Olerud
served the team so well the past three seasons, after a decade of
playing third base.
</P>
<P>
   His switch from third to first, to a position where he has
played only 77 games in his 11-year career, will be among the most
closely watched issues in the Mets' training camp that opens later
this week. The Mets' everyday infielders _ Olerud, second baseman
Edgardo Alfonzo, shortstop Rey Ordonez and third baseman Robin
Ventura _ combined to make 27 errors last season. Zeile made 25
while playing third base for the Texas Rangers, and now he will
essentially be playing a new position, after signing a three-year
deal with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it, analyzed it, talked to our scouts and our
people who had seen him play first base,'' said Steve Phillips, the
Mets' general manager. ``Our view was he'd make a smooth and simple
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   There is work to be done. The Mets have asked Keith Hernandez,
considered the best defensive first baseman of his era, to counsel
Zeile, to coach him on his footwork, on holding runners and
covering the first-base hole and charging bunts and balls hit in
front of him. Because so many players have moved to first base at
the end of their careers _ Ernie Banks, George Brett, Willie
Stargell and Carl Yastrzemski, to name a few _ there could be a
misperception that first is an easy position to play, or that it is
somehow of lesser importance.
</P>
<P>
   When Hernandez played, for example, he was the key to the entire
Mets defense; Olerud, tall and rangy and sure-handed, gave them
stability, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good first baseman, it takes the pressure off of
the infielders,'' Hernandez said, ``as far as knowing they have to
make a nice throw. It's nice for them to know you can be off-line
with a throw and have a good pair of hands over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud joined the Mets before the 1997 season, as Manager Bobby
Valentine recalled, ``he was a lousy first baseman who had no
mobility.'' In time, he was almost a prototype for the Mets: At 6
feet 5 inches, he could reach the throws of Ordonez, whose range
and necessarily quick release sometimes leads to throws that sail
high or sink low. ``Personally, what I thought John did best was
have that range around the bag,'' Valentine said. ``Not on balls
hit in his area, but on throws to first.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, a former standout pitcher, could throw, making him
something of a threat to baserunners. He is left-handed, a distinct
advantage at first base. And after working with the Mets' coaching
staff for a time, he embraced some of the concepts employed by
Valentine, such as holding the runner while in motion, faking back
to the bag. (Not all players readily accept such change. When
Rafael Palmeiro was the first baseman for the Baltimore Orioles,
for instance, he did not like signaling the pitcher to indicate
when the runner's lead had grown substantially.)
</P>
<P>
   Zeile is right-handed, which means that throwing to second or
third will be more difficult for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easier play for a left-hander,'' Hernandez said. ``You
have left-handed first basemen for the same reason that you have
right-handed third basemen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question of angles. Zeile is 6-1, and he will not have
Olerud's range on throws to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think height is that important,'' said Hernandez, who
is 6-feet tall. He won't have Olerud's experience.
</P>
<P>
   But according to two who have managed Zeile and managed against
him, he has other assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good hands, good baseball instincts,'' said Torre, who
has high respect for Zeile's professionalism. ``He'll do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Riggleman, Zeile's former manager with the Chicago Cubs,
said: ``I just don't see any problems with him playing first base.
Obviously he's not as tall as Olerud, but he's a hair taller than
Steve Garvey'' _ the former Dodger who was considered a good first
baseman _ ``and he's athletic enough. He'll get a feel for picking
the ball up in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile already has that, having gone through years of training as
a catcher. Torre noted that one of Zeile's habits as a third
baseman _ the instinct to drop to one knee and block the ball, not
always a good trait in a third baseman _ will serve him well as a
first baseman, because he will have more time to make a play. He
can drop to a knee to stop the ball, then throw to the pitcher
covering the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile is considered to have an accurate arm, and the part of his
defense that diminished the most in recent years _ his range, in
reaching balls hit to his left and right _ will not be as big an
issue now that he is playing first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment for me is not going to be catching the
ball,'' Zeile said, ``but getting used to the intricacies of the
position. Holding runners, bunt defenses from the other side of the
diamond, getting used to the guys around me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to blocking and catching balls, as a catcher; I had
some of that hand action. Hopefully, that will go a long way at
first.''
</P>
<P>
   But what might be of most help for Zeile and the Mets is his
willingness to adapt. Zeile could have signed elsewhere and played
third base, but he chose to play first for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd will buy into whatever they ask him to do,'' Hernandez
said. ``He's very happy to go to New York. He's not a me-me guy.
He's a good guy and he wants to do well. It's going to help him,
having those other infielders. They'll help make him feel
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile will likely bat sixth, behind the left-handed hitting
Ventura, and it may be that at the end of games, the Mets might use
someone more experienced at first to finish games. Charlie Hayes,
signed as a backup, could be inserted as part of a double-switch;
Valentine will examine his options more closely as the season nears
and he has seen Zeile's daily adjustments at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I gathered from Todd, he's a very willing
participant,'' Valentine said. ``It's going to be challenging, but
I believe its going to be a very successful spring.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
