<SLUG> BC-TV-DUEL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DUEL': HEADY DAYS WHEN WORDS LED TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable aspect of the famous duel between
Alexander Hamilton and Aaron Burr was that it took place at all.
Monday night's ``American Experience'' notes that challenges in
matters of honor were not unknown among politicians in the
Revolutionary era. (Hamilton was involved in 11 of them.) But by
and large they were settled without bloodshed. The point seems to
have been to advertise one's courage without undue risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the personalities and the politics, the ambitions and the
animosities of these two Revolutionary eminences actually drew them
onto a field of honor on July 11, 1804. ``The Duel'' provides a
quick sketch of the careers of the combative Hamilton, champion of
a strong federal government, and Burr, the war hero and charming
ladies' man whose political accomplishments never matched his
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Their clash, briskly reported Sunday night, began when Burr
defeated Hamilton's father-in-law, Gen. Philip Schuyler, to become
the senator from New York. In much stronger language than one hears
in this year's subdued version of negative advertising, Hamilton
described Burr as ``unprincipled, both as a public and a private
man.''
</P>
<P>
   The language only got hotter in the 1800 election, when, by the
rules of the time, Burr tied Thomas Jefferson for the presidency
and after days of deadlock became vice president. Like many vice
presidents to come, the ambitious Burr found himself without power
and, in 1804, he decided to run for governor of New York as a
Federalist.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was a leader of the forces against him in what one of
Sunday night's historians calls the country's dirtiest political
campaign. (One newspaper published a list of 20 prostitutes who
named Burr as their favorite customer.)
</P>
<P>
   Burr lost, and the upshot was his challenge to Hamilton for
calling him despicable, among other things. The encounter took
place across the Hudson in New Jersey to evade a New York law that
made dueling illegal.
</P>
<P>
   There remains some disagreement as to who fired first and
whether Hamilton missed on purpose. But Burr's intention was
apparently clear; his bullet struck Hamilton in the stomach, and 36
hours later the man described Sunday night as ``the architect of
the American Constitution and the designer of American capitalism''
died. Burr ended up in exile, his reputation destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: THE DUEL'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Red Hill Productions and Oregon Public Broadcasting
for ``The American Experience.'' Carl Byker and Mitch Wilson,
directors; written by Carl Byker and David Mrazek; produced by Carl
Byker; Linda Hunt, narrator. For Oregon Public Broadcasting: Dave
Davis, executive producer; John Lindsay, executive in charge. ``The
American Experience'' is produced by WGBH/Boston. Margaret Drain,
executive producer; Mark Samels, senior producer; David McCullough,
series host.
</P>
<P>
   With: Russell Hunston (Alexander Hamilton), Rene Auberjonois
(voice of Alexander Hamilton), Alan Semok (Aaron Burr) and Brian
Dennehy (voice of Aaron Burr).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
