u e BC-WEILL-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     02-13 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEILL-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIVELY, STAR-FILLED EVENING OF WEILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Academy of Music's monthlong celebration
of the centenary of Kurt Weill's birth builds to serious business
with a film festival beginning on Feb. 17 and a production of ``Der
Weg der Verheissung'' (``The Eternal Road''), an epic musical and
theatrical interpretation of Jewish history, on Feb. 28. But the
opening program, ``Weill Style,'' conceived by Ken Bloom and
presented on the evening of Feb. 10 in the academy's Opera House,
was mostly a delightful lark.
</P>
<P>
   With an array of singers from opera, Broadway, cabaret and pop
spinning out Weill show tunes, the evening belonged largely to
Jerry Orbach, who led with ``Mack the Knife,'' acted as M.C. and
ended with ``September Song.'' But it was a show waiting to be
stolen at any moment, and for this listener it was stopped most
definitively early on when the Broadway star Donna Murphy sang
``Pirate Jenny'' from ``The Threepenny Opera'' with compelling
passion. This despite strong competition later from Patricia
O'Callaghan, a classical and cabaret singer, in ``Sailor's Tango,''
and from Ann Magnuson, a film and television actress, in ``The Saga
of Jenny.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson received fine support from Hudson Shad, a strong-voiced
male vocal quintet with a wry tone set by its bass, Wilbur Pauley.
That group performed other numbers as well, but no one worked
harder throughout the evening than Eric Stern, the music director,
who bounced deftly from piano to podium and even took a vocal turn
in ``The Trouble With Women.''
</P>
<P>
   In a program consisting of little but highlights, others were
offered by Samuel E. Wright in ``Lost in the Stars,'' Keith Thomas
and Michelle Robinson in ``Moon-Faced, Starry-Eyed'' and Mark
Linn-Baker in ``Tchaikovsky.'' (But Orbach, who introduced this
tongue-twisting Danny Kaye vehicle as being made up of the names of
Russian composers should expect to hear from Ukrainians, wanting to
separate out their compatriot Bortniansky.)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Hadley did not entirely shed his operatic gravity in an
odd coupling with O'Callaghan in ``It Never Was You,'' but he fared
better on his own in ``Lonely House.'' Only Duncan Sheik, a rock
singer, failed to hold his own in this company, in ``Alabama
Song,'' or even with Stern in ``The Trouble With Women.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening was enriched by reminiscences. Dick Van Patten
described playing Isaac, at age 8, in the premiere production of
``The Eternal Road'' in 1937 in New York and never being quite
sure, from night to night, that the angels would intervene in time
to stay Abraham's sacrifice. Hesper Anderson, the daughter of the
playwright Maxwell Anderson, a Weill collaborator, spoke feelingly
of the composer and his wife, Lotte Lenya. Nanette Fabray's fragile
rendition of ``Green-Up Time,'' too, was more in the nature of a
reminiscence.
</P>
<P>
   The year's Weill celebrations, at the Brooklyn Academy and
elsewhere, might wish to take their theme from the show title
``Happy End.'' Here, at any rate, was the happiest of beginnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
