<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VOTE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER DETAINED AFTER ZIMBABWE REFERENDUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ A leading opposition figure was detained here
Sunday at the end of a two-day referendum on a new constitution
that was marked by charges of sporadic intimidation and voting
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Tendai Biti and several other members of the Movement for
Democratic Change and the National Constitutional Assembly were
taken into custody outside a polling place in a township here as
they urged people to vote down the proposed constitution, some of
their colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just intimidation,'' said Dr. Lovemore Madhuku, vice
chairman of the group, which was formed to fight for a new
constitution but has ended up fighting against the one proposed by
the president's hand-picked commission. ``They just want to show
that you cannot contest this.''
</P>
<P>
   The new constitution, which would strengthen the powers of the
presidency and give the government the right to seize white-owned
land without compensation, is a crucial test for President Robert
Mugabe,
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is suffering through the most painful economic crisis
since the country won independence from Britain 20 years ago. In
April, Mugabe and his governing Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front face parliamentary elections pitting them
against a surging new opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the proposed constitution is likely to hint at the
outcome of those elections. As a result, the contest being waged
over it has taken on a far greater importance for both Mugabe and
his supporters and for those who hope to see him unseated.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all of the attention directed at the contest,
however, turnout was light at many polling places. In a country
where turnout is typically low, opposition groups hoped their
campaign, coupled with the country's continuing economic problems,
would bring out people who traditionally do not bother to vote. But
the absence of long lines in many places suggested otherwise and at
least hinted at a victory for Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Sunday night, the country's chief election
organizer, Tobaiwa Mudede, said he could not estimate the total
turnout, because bad weather had delayed reporting from many rural
polling locations. Counting is expected to begin Monday morning,
with results likely to come by the end of the day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   How the opposition's charges of irregularities and intimidation
will affect the process remains to be seen. With information still
trickling in Saturday night from around the country to the
headquarters of the National Constitutional Assembly, no clear
patterns had emerged. But what they had heard so far was certainly
troubling, leaders of the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the arrests of several campaigners at the
township polling place here, the group said that monitors at one
polling place were ejected by the police several hours before the
polls closed. At another, at a school in Gutu in the south, a
monitor said, the principal threatened him with a gun and told him
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   And in Mutare in the east and Chivi in the south, monitors
observed ballot boxes that apparently had been removed from polling
places before the end of balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now these reports are sporadic, but we haven't heard
from a lot of other areas,'' said Isaac Maposa, a member of the
group.``Some people are hundreds of kilometers from phones so we
don't have everything and I am sure we will be hearing worse
stories than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariyo Mariyawanda Nzuwah, chairman of the National Election
Directorate, said at the news briefing that no reports of tampering
had been received following the first day of balloting and that he
was confident the vote would be viewed as fair. ``We think we did a
fairly reasonable job,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tony Hawkins of the University of Zimbabwe said that while
problems were almost inevitable in organizing votes in young,
developing nations such as Zimbabwe, the flaws in the weekend's
balloting were more troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the international community is going to
recognize this, because of the low turnout and because of the
absence of observers,'' he said. ``And all these little incidents
do is add to the general perception that the vote has not been well
run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
