<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5605 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-HOMICIDE-AZR     02-13 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-HOMICIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOMICIDE' FILM OFFERS CLOSURE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - Homicide: Life on the Street was one of those shows
that you could always count on six or seven people get ting
together to watch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not six or seven in a living room. Six or seven in the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's a bit of an exaggera tion, but Homicide's anemic rat
ings never kept up with its stellar reputation. Perhaps no show in
television history was so praised by so many critics and seen by so
few viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Time for one more chance.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime fans of the show, Homicide: The Movie serves as a
welcome treat, as well as a satis fying conclusion to the late, la
mented series.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who didn't catch on the first time around, it's
not that simple. Instead, the NBC movie, which reunites all the
major cast members _ yes, the ``dead'' ones, too _ is a two-hour
tease, a reminder of what we should have been watching all those
years and now have to do without.
</P>
<P>
   The series, created by Tom Fontana and Barry Levinson, hung on
by a thread every year, its future clouded in doubt, until the end
of the 1998-99 season, when NBC axed it. Fans were crushed. All
those loose ends, still untied. All those fans, unsa tisfied. There
may not have been many of them, but they were vo cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show seems to have a life beyond any of our control,'' Fon
tana told TV critics in California recently.
</P>
<P>
   NBC talked with Fontana about making a movie, but he was in
different to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at that point . . . emo tionally trying to let go of the
show,'' Fontana said. ``And I made the what-I-thought impossi ble
statement of, `Well, if you get all of the actors back, I'll do
it.' And little did I know they would actually accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now all he needed was a dra matic reason to bring them all back.
Thus, Lt. Al Giardello, now a front-running mayoral candi date, is
gunned down at a rally. While Giardello fights for his life in the
hospital, the squad reunites to find the shooter.
</P>
<P>
   As eager as the fictional cops were to work together again, the
actors were, as well, making the reunion sound like a real-life ver
sion of the end of Mr. Holland's Opus.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everybody that was per forming, it was like watching . .
. the Homicide hall of fame,'' said Callie Thorne, who returns as
De tective Laura Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it plays for viewers as well. This is not always a
good thing. Too often, if you're famil iar with the show, you know
what's coming next.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Frank Pem bleton (the always intense Andre
Braugher) returns, you know it's only a matter of minutes till he's
back in the ``box,'' conducting an interrogation the way Leonard
Bernstein conducted an orches tra.
</P>
<P>
   Predictable as it may be, how ever, Braugher still nails his
character. And there are a couple of legitimate surprises. Plus, a
few of those nagging loose ends are finally tied up.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana says this is likely the last we'll see of the Homicide
crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has turned out to be . . . a remarkable closure for us, and
a remarkable celebration for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's swell for them. As for the rest of us? We cannot in good
conscience complain about what might have been. It was. We just
missed it, and have only our selves to blame. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8974. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
