<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC-VIETNAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM BAT TLE LINES STILL DRAWN IN AMERICAN MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN 
 AND KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - It was the most patriotic of times or it was the most
seditious of times.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades after the Vietnam War, that battle line still is
etched in the American psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The painful memories are rushing back with the revelation that
Scottsdale activist Gary Tredway actually is Howard Mechanic, a
fugitive from a 1970 conviction for his part in the war-and-peace
tumult.
</P>
<P>
   His crime was to lob a jumbo firecracker by slingshot at police
and firefighters after someone set fire to the ROTC building at
Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt, but under a new federal get-tough policy, he
was sentenced to five years in prison. He ran away.
</P>
<P>
   Among Phoenix area residents with the Vietnam War era seared
into their memory, sentiments are divided over what should be done
with Mechanic. They range from forgive-and-forget to one Phoenix
veteran's harsh judgment, ``Shoot the SOB.''
</P>
<P>
   A Scottsdale war widow says a five-year term is a cheap price
for Mechanic to pay, compared with the death of her Marine husband.
</P>
<P>
   OPINIONS SHIFT &QL; 
But over time, opinions about what was right and wrong about those
turbulent times have shifted, sometimes 180 degrees. A disabled
veteran takes the surprising view that Mechanic should do mostly
community service. And a peace activist of the time doesn't rule
out prison.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. Marines first went to Vietnam to fight Communist
forces in 1965, no one imagined that more than 3.4 million U.S.
troops would serve in Southeast Asia over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As the cost rose in dollars and lives _ in the end, 58,000
Americans had died and 153,000 were seriously wounded _ opponents
of the war took to the streets in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the demonstrations were peaceful, but some turned
violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did anything illegal, but I witnessed a lot of mayhem
myself,'' recalled Phoenix resident Bridget Carroll, who lived in
Washington, D.C., at the time. ``A favorite target then was turning
over ice cream trucks. I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   She was tear-gassed, ``an extremely unpleasant experience,'' as
police tried to break up a demonstration blocking traffic. FAMILY
BEARS SCARS &QL; 
Carroll, 51, remembers how her opposition to the war was confirmed
when her father, who fought in World War II, told her, ``The war is
wrong. Too many young men your age are dying for no reason, and
this has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The family still bears the scars of Vietnam, a cousin so
traumatized by guard duty in Vietnam that he hasn't left the house
since coming home in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says Mechanic must accept the consequences of his action
now. In her own view, though, he sentenced himself to a 30-year
break in his life, and that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic lobbed his firecracker in protests over a tragedy that
shook the country: National Guardsmen had opened fire on unarmed
youths at Kent State University in Ohio, killing four and wounding
nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea what a horrible injustice that was,'' said
Renz Jennings, who has been active in Arizona politics for decades
and recently served on the Corporation Commission. ``I was just
outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when critics of the war were branded as
unpatriotic and worse.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, now 58, was the youngest member of the Arizona
Legislature in 1968-69 and the only open opponent of the Vietnam
War. One day, red, white and blue armbands were handed out to
legislators. Jennings wore his, but put a black mark of protest on
it.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague called him a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe if you think your country is making a mistake, it's
patriotic to say so,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   `HYSTERIA' DURING PERIOD &QL; 
As for Mechanic, whom he knows personally from serving together on
the Clean Elections Institute board, Jennings says there have to be
consequences. But he considers the original five-year sentence too
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a hysteria during that period,'' Jennings said,
``and the establishment was going to make people pay, and pay
dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix insurance agent Kevin O'Keeffe, 54, agrees that the
sentence is too tough. At this point, he says, community service
makes more sense.
</P>
<P>
   That's not what he would have said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a firm believer in the government, that we should be
there,'' said O'Keeffe, who graduated from Marquette University in
Milwaukee in 1968. ``To be honest with you, I didn't know that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the war receded into history, his perspective changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my cousin and a lot of friends,'' he said. ``What a
waste.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration that led to the Kent State tragedy was sparked
by President Richard Nixon's ordering a military incursion into
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters took to the streets, as they had before by the
hundreds of thousands, to attack this escalation of a war that had
raged for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were very passionate times,'' recalled John Kromko, 60,
a front-line activist in the anti-war movement at the University of
Arizona who later served in the state House of Representatives as a
Democrat from Tucson. ``People on both sides overreacted.''
</P>
<P>
   `THEY HATED US' &QL; 
Kromko said he was nearly shot in a student takeover of UA's
historic Old Main, where the Reserve Officer Training Corps program
had its headquarters. He was jailed briefly for inciting to riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hated us,'' he said of the war's supporters, and the
effort to suppress dissent made sentences as harsh as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Kromko said he can't second-guess Mechanic's conviction or
whether he should serve at least some time behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this probably should just be forgotten about,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot that people can't forget.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam veterans still feel the scalding surprise of coming home
to scorn instead of thanks for their service.
</P>
<P>
   A Mesa woman made the mistake of wearing her Navy uniform when
she returned on leave to southern Illinois. She was pelted with
eggs and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   HECKLED ON FLIGHT &QL; 
Chandler resident Lou Ortiz, retired after 28 years in the Air
Force, remembers flying home to New York after his 1967-68 tour in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He got on the plane in San Francisco, dressed in uniform with
all his ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   His two seatmates starting heckling him with comments about baby
killers. Ortiz replied that he just wanted to sleep and closed his
eyes. Their voices dropped to mumbles, but he couldn't shut out the
sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the military,'' said Ortiz, 71, who won a bronze
star, the Army's medal for heroism or meritorious service. ``I was
following my orders, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes a straightforward view on Mechanic: Make the fugitive
serve the full sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Like many, then and now, Ortiz thinks citizens and politicians
torpedoed the military strategy for the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it was lost,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Other veterans have changed their views on the protest era.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us were torn over that Vietnam crucible,'' said
Patrick Young, who as a Navy corpsman serving with the Marines
nearly lost his legs to a land mine in Vietnam in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Now 52 and retired to a remote area north of Sun City, Young
underwent 18 operations to save his legs and worked 27 years with
the Disabled American Veterans as an advocate helping other
veterans pursue disability claims.
</P>
<P>
   Is he bitter about the protests of the 1960s and '70s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I would have been very negative,'' Young said.
``But in maturing over 30 years, I've realized that many of the
veterans who joined in the protests when they came home helped
bring the war to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic, he said, ``deserves some punishment.'' But Young would
change the sentence to a minimum of six months in jail and 4{ years
of community service, perhaps helping veterans groups.
</P>
<P>
   In setting punishment, Kromko said, ``the absolutely key thing
is that anti-war protesters were right.''
</P>
<P>
   MANY `MISGUIDED' &QL; 
Not necessarily, said Brian Wardell, who has focused on covert
actions in Vietnam for his master's program in history at Arizona
State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that many of the protesters were
misguided,'' he said, although he understands the outpouring of
protest about the Cambodian invasion and Kent State, which occurred
when he was 12.
</P>
<P>
   Lam Bui of Tempe, who was drafted into the Vietnamese army in
1971, views the demonstrations as having prolonged the war.
</P>
<P>
   `If we didn't have those people (demonstrating), the war might
have lasted maybe three years, or maybe 100 days like the Gulf
War,'' he said. ``I'm sure the U.S. soldiers who got hurt were
hurting even more to see people like Jane Fonda in Hanoi.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the Mechanic case, ``five years is too long,'' Bui
said. ``My heart is changed now. I've been living here for 25
years, and I don't have any hatred anymore. It's over.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporters at Jon.Kamman(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-4816 and Kathleen.Ingley(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8171. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Painful memories of the Vietnam War era _ from tear-gassed
demonstrators to heckled veterans _ are rushing back with the
revelation that a Scottsdale activist is actually a fugitive from a
1970 conviction for his part in violent protests. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
