<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IS IN THE WIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 
(PHOENIX) - For the third consecutive winter, fewer snowbirds are
flocking to the Phoenix area.
<TEXT>
<P>
   East Phoenix businesses that rely on winter visitors are re
porting a 25 percent downturn in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix recreational-vehicle park owners say it's the calm
between two eras.
</P>
<P>
   The World War II generation pushed the retirement industry into
overdrive the past two decades. But illness and death are depleting
their ranks, and the number of occupied spaces in RV resorts is
down.
</P>
<P>
   But next year, the first wave of baby boomers turn 55, which
makes them eligible for age-re stricted retirement parks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides demographic changes, the most commonly cited factors in
the decline are worsening traffic and air, higher prices, the
disappearing desert, lower Canadian exchange rates, Canadian public
health-insurance limits.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of some of the most popular parks in the Phoenix area
say this is the first winter in years that they weren't filled in
January. They also have fewer confirmed reservations for next year.
Record numbers of homes are for sale in some places.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Maureen West ex plores what's happening with snowbirds,
a Valley tourism staple once as reliable as base ball spring
training and jack-o-lope post cards. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Over the past 20 years, members of the World War II generation have
pushed the retirement industry into overdrive. But illness and
death are depleting their ranks, and the number of occupied spaces
in winter visitor RV resorts is down. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
