<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5609 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MECHANIC-PROFILE-AZR &LR;      02-13 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC-PROFILE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE ON RUN FOUND GOOD LIFE IN VALLEY OF SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY PETER CORBETT  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Howard Mechanic, who helped form a radical anti-war
group at Washington University and picketed the 1968 Democratic
National Convention in Chicago, was a brilliant student with a
scholarship to law school when a single act of violence set him on
a 28-year run from the law.
</P>
<P>
   His conviction for lobbing a giant firecracker at firefighters
in a Vietnam War protest May 5, 1970, a day after the Kent State
killings, caught up with him over five days last week. His
carefully reconstructed life unraveled when anti-growth Scottsdale
City Council candidate Gary Tredway was exposed as Howard Mechanic,
51-year-old fugitive. On Friday, Feb. 11, he began serving his
long-delayed, five-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   His identical twin brother, Harvey, said he wishes his brother,
younger by eight minutes, would have served his sentence and gone
on with life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably would have been out in a year or two,'' said
Harvey Mechanic, now a Los Angeles lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Howard ran.
</P>
<P>
   A rising tide of anti-war sentiment flooded across the nation to
middle American campuses in the late '60s, and the Mechanic twins
were right in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   While Harvey joined students occupying the Columbia
administration building in 1968, Howard connected with about 20
radicals to form the Washington University Liberation Front in the
fall of 1969.
</P>
<P>
   WULF's efforts to stop the war were focused on driving the
Reserve Officer Training Corp off campus, said Robert Zeffert, 57,
a St. Louis consultant who joined Mechanic in the anti-war group.
</P>
<P>
   The group met a few times a week, hunkering down in apartments
and campus hangouts to plan anti-ROTC demonstrations and prepare
thousands of mimeographed leaflets for its marches, Zeffert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our sole extracurricular activity, and we thought we
were going to change the world,'' he said. &QL; 
TURBULENT TIMES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Described by those who know him as brilliant, committed to his
ideals and a loner, Howard Mechanic's long, strange trip from his
wealthy suburban Cleveland hometown of Shaker Heights, Ohio, to
Scottsdale is a reminder of the turbulent times from which he
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Shaker Heights, known for cultural and religious diversity, is
roughly akin, physically, to Phoenix's Biltmore neighborhood. It
was in this middle-class setting that Cleveland natives Ralph and
Rose, who died several years ago, raised Harvey and Howard and
their sister, Marilyn.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Mechanic, 81, was too busy raising a family for political
activism, Harvey said. Now living in suburban Beachwood, Ohio, the
World War II veteran was an appliance repairman who fixed stoves by
day and brought TV sets home at night to repair. His father owned
one of the first motorcycle dealerships in Cleveland. Ralph
invested in apartments and became a landlord, an enterprise that
son Howard would later be successful at in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Mechanic also would later befriend Jack Berger, a
Scottsdale man he knew for 18 years who fixed the TVs at Mechanic's
12-unit apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, the Mechanic twins played touch football and
playground basketball at the school across from their home. Both
were gifted students and National Merit Scholar finalists in 1966,
their senior year at Shaker Heights High School. Howard earned a
scholarship to Washington University in St. Louis. Harvey attended
Columbia University in New York. &QL; 
CLASSMATES WENT TO WAR &QL; 
Some of their classmates were shipped off to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Mechanic remembers that he and his brother drew a number
of about 360 in the draft lottery, which was based on birthdates,
so they were unlikely to ever serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey doesn't recall strong political disagreements at home, as
there were in many families at the time, but Ralph objected to
Howard's long hair and clothes, his brother said.
</P>
<P>
   The older twin said he and his brother didn't smoke or drink in
high school, but like many of their era, smoked marijuana in
college. Both were politically active on campus.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1968, Howard and Harvey joined thousands of war
protesters at the 1968 Democratic National Convention. Through
clouds of tear gas, as police flailed away with nightsticks,
protesters chanted, ``The whole world is watching! The whole world
is watching!'' in the first riot televised live. &QL; 
HOTBED OF ACTIVITY &QL; 
Washington University, with 8,000 students, became a hotbed of
political activity and legitimate protest turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters smashed windows at the main library. In February
1970, students burned down the Army ROTC building. A St. Louis
judge ordered Mechanic and other activists to stay away from the
ROTC program.
</P>
<P>
   The night of May 5, 1970, was perhaps the most violent. A day
after four unarmed students were killed by Ohio National Guardsman
at Kent State University, Howard Mechanic and hun dreds of
protesters converged on the Air Force ROTC building, which was set
ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic was never accused in the fire, but a witness said he
used a slingshot to lob two cherry bombs, one of which exploded
near an officer standing guard.
</P>
<P>
   He has always denied throwing the firecracker, his brother said.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic and four others were arrested. He was convicted under a
strict 1968 anti-rioting law that prohibited obstructing
authorities during civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic was convicted Oct. 19, 1970, and sentenced to five
years in prison. On May 22, 1972, that conviction was upheld in a
federal appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic disappeared and a warrant was issued.
</P>
<P>
   WULF members thought Mechanic was unfairly punished. However,
``people were sort of irritated that he skipped bail,'' Zeffert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kogan, who also was convicted, served about 18 months,
according to Zeffert.
</P>
<P>
   Within months after Mechanic fled St. Louis, a man named Gary
Tredway was born in the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly gravitated to the Gentle Strength Cooperative, a
Tempe hangout for hippies, vegetarians and other counterculture
figures. He also founded Pure Planet Products, a mail-order company
that sells health items.
</P>
<P>
   Tredway pursued other business ventures, including a used-auto
dealership in the early 1980s. About 13 years ago, he bought the
Abode Resort Apartment Hotel of Scottsdale, a residential complex
not far from Scottsdale Fashion Square, for $420,000. It became his
home, as well as a source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Tredway married Ingrid Gold, a nurse midwife, in 1980, and they
divorced in 1984, according to her father, Ray Gold.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's son, Ari, a 19-year-old freshman at St. John's
College in Sante Fe, would not say whether he knew of his father's
past.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and acquaintances say Tredway was an introvert. When
girlfriend Janet Grossman was asked to describe Tredway's
personality, she shrugged and said, ``He's not very outgoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the way Tredway and Grossman met five years ago reflects
the social shyness. As she puts it: ``I answered his personal ad in
New Times looking for a left-thinking, non-smoking vegetarian.'' &QL; 
DEDICATION TO CAUSES &QL; 
Despite his reclusive nature, however, one thing goaded Tredway
into public exposure: a dedication to social and political causes.
He became an officer at Gentle Strength, a co-founder of the Clean
Elections Institute and a treasurer at Arizona for Clean Elections.
</P>
<P>
   His big blast in local politics was aimed at cleaning up
elections. He also wrote letters to the editor against government
waste, environmental degradation, urban sprawl and the use of taxes
to subsidize private business.
</P>
<P>
   Tredway first appeared as a Maricopa County property owner in
1983, when he and Ingrid Gold bought a house on East Whitton Street
in Phoenix, for $81,500. The following year, Tredway signed his
interest in the property over to Gold.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1984, Tredway opened a business he called Recycled Auto,
in an industrial section of south Phoenix on Buckeye Road. In a
handwritten entry on a Maricopa County business record, he said the
business dealt in ```used cars, parts, wrecker.'' A year later,
Tredway changed the name of the business to Prime Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Tredway also began buying and selling real estate. He seemed to
prefer such unglamorous areas as Sunnyslope and south Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he turned a hefty profit on a Sunnyslope hilltop
property. He bought it in March for $117,000 and sold it in August
for $250,000 cash.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Johnson, an attorney who assisted Tredway with that
transaction, said ``he struck me as a hippie,'' who paid little
attention to his dress or his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who said he has not seen Mechanic in about 10 years,
remembered Mechanic as a man who kept to himself and kept the
conversation strictly on business.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Mechanic's acquaintances say they knew him by his social
consciousness rather than his personality or history.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brittle, who shared environmental causes with Tredway for
seven years, said he always wondered why he never smiled. Asked
whether he knows Tredway, Brittle shrugged and said, ``Does
anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bolef, 79, a retired Washington University physics
professor, remembered that the young man he knew as Mechanic
vanished after the fire at the ROTC building. But he was stunned to
learn that Mechanic had been convicted in the case, fled
prosecution and created a new life in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that he disappeared,'' Bolef said. ``And now
that he's surfaced again, under circumstances which ruined his
life, all I can do is weep for him.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Republic writers Alexa Haussler, Diana Balazs, Carol Sower, Dennis
Wagner, Jerry Kammer and Senta Scarborough contributed to the
article. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Peter.Corbett(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-4815. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Howard Mechanic, who helped form a radical anti-war group at
Washington University and picketed the 1968 Democratic National
Convention in Chicago, was a brilliant student with a scholarship
to law school when a single act of violence set him on a 28-year
run from the law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
