<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY-NYT &LR;      02-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERSONALITY ISSUES THAT CLOUD THE GRIFFEY TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even at 30 years old, Ken Griffey Jr. still has a smile fit for
a prom king, broad and beaming. He donned the billed crown of the
Cincinnati Reds the other day and grinned, and it was all
feel-good: Hometown kid eschews the biggest dollars to sign with
his hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   It's more complicated than that. Jim Bowden, the Reds general
manager, skillfully negotiated a staggeringly one-sided deal for
one of the greatest players in history, someone with the physical
power to eclipse Henry Aaron's career home run record, someone with
the box office appeal to convert the Cincinnati Reds from a
small-market team to a big-revenue club after they move into their
new ballpark in two years.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowden has adopted a future covered with personality land
mines. It may be that he can muster more savvy and avoid the
problems, and in a decade, Griffey's place in the record books will
be secure and the Reds may be one of the game's best franchises. Or
the potential trouble Bowden has courted may one day erode the
Reds' stability. Griffey is already bigger than the Cincinnati
organization, and there is a price to be paid for that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Griffey Jr. beamed, Griffey Sr. stood to the side and teased
him. The widely accepted perception is that sometime soon, Senior
will replace Jack McKeon as the manager _ maybe this season, if the
Reds don't play well, or maybe next season. And the feel-good stuff
will be jeopardized by human nature and disposition.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Sr. was the manager of the Orioles at the outset of
the 1988 season. His son, Cal Ripken Jr., was the team's best
player, a star who had not missed a game in almost six years.
Another of his boys, Bill Ripken, was the second baseman. But after
Baltimore lost its first six games to start that year _ the start
of a record 21-game losing streak _ Ripken Sr. was fired and
replaced by Frank Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball had always been a strong root in their relationship
with their father, and quite naturally, the Ripken brothers were
furious, feeling as if Cal Senior had been made a scapegoat after
the team had been built with too little talent. Bill Ripken
immediately changed his uniform number to 7, that of his father.
Cal Ripken had little to say publicly at the time, but in a book
published several years ago, he acknowledged in careful Cal-speak
that he was pretty angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I felt deeply for my father,'' Ripken
wrote, in his book ``The Only Way I Know.'' ``I couldn't imagine
how painful this must have been for him, who had been so loyal to
the franchise for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the organization had been changing subtly, but now all
of a sudden I didn't recognize it at all. That firing _ not the
firing itself, but the way it happened _ made it clear to me that
this organization wasn't the Orioles anymore, not as I'd known
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the subsequent Baltimore managers, coaches baseball
officials have come to believe that the firing of Cal Ripken's
father was a defining moment in the player's relationship with the
Orioles. Since then, he has maintained a distance from the
organization, not overtly fighting the club's decisions but never
truly embracing them, either, and the resulting tension was never
settled.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Ripken's work ethic and dedication to baseball was
unquestioned, his celebrity powerful, particularly in Baltimore.
The Orioles have had a disparate clubhouse for years, and many
smart baseball men who have worked on the Baltimore staff believe
that it stems, in part, from Ripken's own distrust of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   So Griffey goes to the Reds as the game's biggest star, bigger
than the team, a bigger star now than Ripken was in 1988. Griffey
also is extremely sensitive and record-setting holder of grudges.
</P>
<P>
   He would never play for the Yankees, he once indicated, because
when he was a kid, some of George Steinbrenner's coaches told him
to leave the clubhouse. The Mariners paid him a huge salary, openly
credited him with saving baseball in Seattle, offered him a
contract of nearly $150 million to keep him with the team forever _
and Griffey somehow reached the conclusion the team did not want
him.
</P>
<P>
   Given these dynamics of personality, what happens when the Reds
want to replace McKeon? If Griffey Sr. isn't the leading candidate
to step in, he really has to be now, doesn't he _ lest the Reds
anger Griffey Jr. And assuming that change is made, what will the
other Reds think? Will they believe their center fielder runs the
team? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that Griffey Sr. has worked hard to put himself
in position to manage, and he might be terrific. But what if he
isn't? What if he inevitably follows the path of just about every
baseball manager and the Reds decide to fire him? What happens
then?
</P>
<P>
   Suppose they want to make a change in four years, or five, when
Griffey Jr. might draw to within 100 homers of Aaron? Can they risk
alienating a star who will become a national hero? Will Griffey Jr.
react negatively _ as he has repeatedly _ and in a matter involving
his father, wouldn't that be understandable? Would he ask the Reds
to trade him, in the same way he forced his way out of Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   The time for such speculation has passed for the Reds and
Bowden, who have embarked on a path that will require success.
Anything less will be a mess. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
