<SLUG> BC-RAIL-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIC RAIL: $43 MILLION A MILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARY JO PITZL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The electric-rail line that Phoenix proposes to build
would cost nearly $43 million a mile.
</P>
<P>
   That's up 72 percent from a 1997 estimate of $25 million, the
last time Phoenix voters considered a transit tax.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a bargain compared with the costs of building a
new inner-city highway. If the defunct Paradise Freeway were
resurrected, that central Phoenix span would cost nearly $74
million a mile, according to the Maricopa Association of
Governments.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the March 14 Phoenix Transit 2000 election say the
high cost of new freeway construction is a key reason that it's
time for the nation's sixth-largest city to get serious about a
transit system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at $42.9 million a mile, even the pro-transit crowd gulps.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 figure was a ``guesstimate,'' said Wulf Grote, project
manager for Valley Connections, a 3-year-old regional planning
group that supports creation of Valley commuter trains.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix segment is a key part of the project. If built, it
would enable other Valley cities to link their own rail lines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the rail project for the urban area wasn't clearly
defined, so planners used estimates from other cities with rail
systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's price tag is the result of more-detailed studies, a few
years of inflation and, in some places, a different alignment,
Grote said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1997, it was assumed the rail project would use
the right of way of the Union Pacific Railroad between Tempe and
Phoenix. That's not an option now, because the railroad has
withdrawn its offer, Grote said.
</P>
<P>
   So the project would have to take the more expensive route of
running in the street. The double-track rail line would run in its
own lanes, separate from vehicle traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Street operation is pricier for several reasons, planners say.
Those include tying traffic sig nals into the rail operation, so
that trains could extend a green light as they approached an
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Another expensive upgrade in the plan would involve the use of
low-floor rail vehicles, which make boarding easier for everyone,
including people with handicaps and parents with strollers. Earlier
projections had counted on high-floor trains, such as those used in
San Diego and Salt Lake City, Grote said.
</P>
<P>
   The train's general route has been sketched: From Chris-Town
Mall along Central Avenue to downtown Phoenix and then east past
Sky Harbor International Airport to the Tempe border.
</P>
<P>
   But only the Central Avenue segment, from Camelback Road to
either Jefferson or Washington streets, has been clearly defined.
Rails would run in the middle of Central, taking out two lanes of
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Planners are still toying with whether to run the rail on
Jefferson or Washington, or both. It hasn't been decided whether
the rail would run down the middle or at the side of those streets.
</P>
<P>
   West of Central, it's even less clear. The rail would generally
run along Camelback, from Central west to 19th Avenue, to a
terminal near Chris-Town Mall. But whether the rail would run in
those busy streets, or on another alignment, has not been
determined _ and won't be _ before the March 14 election.
</P>
<P>
   Planners are even talking about some sort of elevated structure
at busy intersections to speed the train and avoid conflicts with
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Although transit backers are quick to compare the costs with
those of freeways, it's not that easy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 12 percent of the rail budget would be devoted to
the cost of park-and-ride lots, a maintenance yard and the
communications network that would link rail cars. For freeways,
these comparable items come from separate budgets and are not
calculated into the per-mile cost of road.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the freeway network's safety features, such as the
ongoing installation of cable barriers in the freeway medians,
aren't reflected in the Valleywide average cost of $34.6 million a
mile.
</P>
<P>
   Rail also includes some costs that aren't factored in with
freeways, including train cars, stations and the installation of
overhead wires.
</P>
<P>
   Although the current freeway network averages $34.6 million a
mile, it would cost more than that to build a new freeway through
the developed, heavily congested portions of central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix planners point to the defunct Paradise as an example of
what a new urban freeway would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1995, the Paradise was planned as an east-west freeway
slicing across the Valley near Camelback Road, from Glendale to the
Squaw Peak Freeway. It was dropped from freeway plans after an
unsuccessful election.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Paradise was estimated to cost $54.3 million a
mile, more than twice the $25.3 million average for the rest of the
freeway network. That's because the freeway would have run through
developed neighborhoods and commercial areas, requiring expensive
land acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring in the 36 percent rise in per-mile freeway costs over
the last five years, the Paradise today would cost $74 million per
mile to build. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at MaryJo.Pitzl &QL; 
(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8963. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The electric-rail line that Phoenix proposes to build would cost
nearly $43 million a mile. But it's less than building a new
inner-city highway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
