<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SNOW-MESA-AZR &LR;      02-13 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOW-MESA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IS IN THE WIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MAUREEN WEST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MESA, Ariz.) - ViewPoint RV and Golf Resort in Mesa, one of the
Phoenix area's largest snowbird retreats, has room to grow by more
than a third _ adding 700 spaces.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if its owners can figure out what the coming wave of
baby-boom retirees want.
</P>
<P>
   Other park owners and real estate developers are wondering, too.
</P>
<P>
   What do retiring boomers want? Condos instead of block-long RVs?
Million-dollar rock-star-style tour buses with big-screen TVs and
megabuck stereo systems? Casitas with adjoining basketball,
volleyball and tennis courts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the cusp of change,'' said Dan Austin of the Arizona
Winter Visitors Association, based in Apache Junction.
</P>
<P>
   If past trends continue, park owners stand to gain in future
decades from an avalanche of new people into their parks. On the
other hand, the boomers may not show up. They may all be flyfishing
in Wyoming or volunteering in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Next year will be the first season for baby-boom snowbirds,
those born between 1946-64. They begin turning 55, which is old
enough to live in the 55-and-over RV parks.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly is room for them. For the past two seasons, the
winter-visitor numbers were down. Visitors are coming later and
staying shorter. Most parks are operating at capacity this month,
but in past years they would have been fully occupied long before
this.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ADD $1 BILLION TO ECONOMY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 320,000 Snowbirds normally pump $1 billion into
Arizona, according to Arizona State University's Center for
Business Research.
</P>
<P>
   Some migratory elders have switched from urban Arizona to the
rural parts of the state. Cheaper rent, real desert and small-town
life are winning out over the Phoenix area's high-priced traffic
jams and desert-eradication progress. Yuma, Lake Havasu, Casa
Grande are booming, and are cheap: A space that would cost $2,200
in the Phoenix area for the season is $1,700 in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many parks are 15 to 25 years old, and their residents have
grown older, too. Motorized chairs and oxygen tanks on wheels can
be found on the asphalt paths where bicycles and tennis shoes still
hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   MORE HOMES FOR SALE &QL; 
Last year, ViewPoint had 29 homes of former residents for sale.
This year they had 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illness, death or lack of travel mobility are the most common
reasons people give for selling,'' said Kerin MacWilliams, director
of business operations for ViewPoint.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Regal RV Resort, the largest park in the Valley, had 94
units for sale this year, up sharply from previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Al Lynch of British Columbia, a winter resident of Mesa Regal RV
Resort, said many Canadians were missing this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a little lonely around here,'' the 69-year-old
said wryly. Every year, he and his wife, Pat, weigh the costs. This
year, health-insurance costs them $7 a day, and it will become more
expensive as they grow older.
</P>
<P>
   In eight years, the Lynch's annual park rent has increased to
$2,800, from $1,800. One of their neighbors was lured away by a
rural park that paid moving costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are missing,'' said Reta Blanchette of
Waverly, Minn., as she enjoyed an afternoon block party of longtime
friends. ``But the baby boomers are looking.''
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE BABY BOOMERS &QL; 
But just because boomers are reaching early retirement age doesn't
mean they are going to retire like their parents did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are going to be mobile for a number of years,''
Austin predicted. ``They may want to come to the Valley for a
month, and then divide their time between such places as Yuma,
California and Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Goff, 53, of Marysville, Calif., is spending January and
February in Quarzsite and Yuma, traveling in her 45-foot tour bus.
She traveled in a caravan to Yuma last week with three friends. Her
husband still works, but joins her when he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many baby boomers have spent their lives in the cities earning
money, and now they want to get out in the country. But that
doesn't mean they want to rough it,'' Goff said. Her $300,000 tour
bus features leather coaches, real wood, lots of closets and two
televisions. ``It's our home on wheels,'' she said. The booming
stock market, more than Social Security, will pay the gas bills.
</P>
<P>
   CHECKING OUT THE PHOENIX AREA &QL; 
Several new retirees used the Apache Junction KOA camp ground as a
base last week while they checked out the Phoenix area &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Cash, 57, a retired fire chief from Elko, Nev., scanned the
newspaper classified ads looking for an apartment. His wife
Phyllis, 52, is a retired nurse. They have a Dalmation and a
turtle, who are also retiring. One of their objectives is to be
near their son who lives in the Phoenix area. And Phyllis' mother,
84, is traveling with them in their RV. Next year they may buy a
place, but still roam around.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the campground, Jean Guy Couture, 57, of Quebec, a
retired principal, and his 56-year-old wife, Tharcyle, were
spending six weeks on the road in a small van. That's all the time
they wanted to take this year because she is a substitute teacher.
Next year, they may extend their stay to three months. The future
is very much on their mind and they are trying to figure out what
to do. They want to ``see the color of the country, and not be tied
to one place,'' Couture said.
</P>
<P>
   They are disappointed by offerings geared to winter visitors
along their way. In Brownsville, Texas, they said everything for
retirees was built around gambling or shopping.
</P>
<P>
   INTERESTS SHIFTING &QL; 
ViewPoint's co-owner Cecil Ash, says the park is receiving more
requests for classes on foreign languages, financial management and
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The interests of retirees seems to be shifting, he observed,
from pure recreation to productive activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education in general is becoming a bigger thing that will
figure into these communities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Physical fitness and sports are increasingly popular, and many
parks are ramping up those features. Golf and tennis continue to be
a major draw.
</P>
<P>
   It's very hard to get enough people for square dancing,
horseshoes and shuffleboard, park recreation managers say.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity pop or rock stars from the past may fill an
entertainment gap. Last year, Ash brought in '60s singer Brenda
Lee, who was a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Although more parks say they are planning more extravaganzas and
catered dinners, others says the casual style is not expected to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potlucks and paper-plate dinners will be still be around,''
said Bonnie Waite of Orangewood Shadows RV Resort in Mesa. ``People
want to take it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE STAYING AROUND &QL; 
They might want to take it so easy, however, that they don't move
on at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, more ViewPoint residents than usual _ about 300 of
the 1,700 units _ stayed on through the summer, with residents
asking for summer activities for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Adding new features to attract the younger crowd does not always
sit well with older residents. One community added a bigger gym and
ditched a car wash, which was a sore point with the old regulars.
</P>
<P>
   The newer crowd is different not only by age, but by background.
Traditional snowbirds have been from rural, small-town America.
Newer visitors are from offices in cities, with different
expectations and manners.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and managers will be listening for hints and whispers
about what new retirees will want. Changes in their expectations
could reshape Phoenix's economy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Maureen.West(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8167. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RV park owners and managers are wondering how they can meet the
needs an interests of the coming baby boomers who become snowbird
age next year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      02-13 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLAN: AVOID ISSUE OF MCCAIN'S HOT TEMPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 B
 Republic Washington Bureau 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(CHARLESTON, S.C.) _ George W. Bush intends to depict John McCain
as unable to unite warring factions, but the Texas governor and his
advisers have decided to stop short of direct jabs at McCain's
occasionally volatile temper.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's temperament is an issue that Arizona Gov. Jane Hull,
among other Bush supporters, raised last year by telling the
national news media about stormy encounters with the Republican
Arizona senator. Still, Bush campaign aides say they'll shy away
leading up to next Saturday's South Carolina primary and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to campaign strategists, Bush plans to come
at the issue in another way, by suggesting that McCain contributes
to Washington's ``poisonous'' atmosphere and is incapable of
building consensus on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   When Karl Rove, a top Bush adviser, was asked by The Arizona
Republic recently whether the campaign planned to spotlight
McCain's temper in its increasingly aggressive ads, there was a
thoughtful pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm suggesting that this is about the absence of
something,'' Rove said. ``A successful leader is someone who
persuades. Some people who do that have rough edges on them, some
of them don't. I mean, (Texas Sen.) Phil Gramm is not necessarily
the most cuddly person in the world, and yet he was able to get
Gramm-Rudman (spending limits) through when he was in the House
because he had a vision that he articulated.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, has failed to bring his colleagues together on major
bills, Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be very careful about this,'' he said. ``Look, he
positions himself as someone who is outside of Washington. He's
been there for 17 years, long enough to become chairman of a
committee that he himself boasts regulates 85 percent of America's
business interests. And yet, if you examine the career, you can't
point to a major achievement, a legislative achievement where he
has been able to rally his colleagues, persuade them of the
correctness of his vision.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's highest-profile bills of the past few years ended in
defeat, and he has pledged to continue the fight in successive
sessions of Congress. Examples include his measures to ban
unregulated contributions to national political parties, or ``soft
money,'' and to boost tobacco prices to help fund anti-smoking
programs for kids.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides did not return repeated calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   A review of McCain's record shows that he won battles to
restrict the flight zones of noisy aircraft over the Grand Canyon,
brokered an agreement that led to a ratings system for TV programs,
and sponsored a successful compromise measure protecting businesses
from large liability due to Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported other causes, from pushing for an option of
ground troops during the Kosovo war, to fighting to end the
``earnings'' test restricting Social Security benefits of senior
citizens who remain in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain is not popular among colleagues, often joking that he
will never win ``Miss Congeniality'' on Capitol Hill. His
relationship suffered with some senators whom he snubbed after he
believed he was treated unfairly during the ``Keating Five''
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In the scandal, McCain was rebuked by the Senate Ethics
Committee for bad judgment for intervening with a federal agency in
behalf of Phoenix financier Charles H Keating Jr., a major campaign
donor.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain says his unpopularity stems from his campaign-finance
reform bill, which is opposed by Senate leadership, and his
persistent criticism of his colleagues' pork-barrel spending and
ties to special interests. McCain's presidential campaign is based
partly on lessening the influence of interest groups such as the
oil and gas lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign intends to make the case that McCain's
difficulties in getting along with fellow senators are a function
of his style of governing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important question for voters to ask: Who would be
able to stop the partisan bickering in Washington, D.C.?'' Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes asked.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators have been avoiding talking publicly about McCain's
legislative style. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHARLESTON, S.C. _ George W. Bush intends to depict John McCain as
unable to unite warring factions, but the Texas governor and his
advisers have decided to stop short of direct jabs at McCain's
occasionally volatile temper.
</P>
</TEXT>
