<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Feb. 13. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MECHANIC-PROFILE _ Howard Mechanic, who helped form a radical
anti-war group at Washington University and picketed the 1968
Democratic National Convention in Chicago, was a brilliant student
with a scholarship to law school when a single act of violence set
him on a 28-year run from the law. His conviction for lobbing a
giant firecracker at firefighters in a Vietnam War protest May 5,
1970, a day after the Kent State killings, caught up with him last
week. His reconstructed life unraveled when anti-growth Scottsdale
City Council candidate Gary Tredway was exposed as Howard Mechanic,
51-year-old fugitive. By PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MECHANIC-VIETNAM _ It was the most patriotic of times or it was the
most seditious of times. The painful memories are rushing back with
the revelation that Scottsdale activist Gary Tredway actually is
Howard Mechanic, a fugitive from a 1970 conviction. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCCAIN _ As the Republican presidential primary in South Carolina
intensifies, George W. Bush intends to depict John McCain as unable
to unite warring factions. However, the Texas governor and his
advisers have decided to stop short of direct jabs at McCain's
occasionally volatile temper. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RAIL-PHOENIX _ Backers of the March 14 Phoenix Transit 2000
election say the high cost of new freeway construction is a key
reason that it's time for the nation's sixth-largest city to get
serious about a transit system. At a cost of nearly $43 million a
mile, rail is still a bargain compared with the costs of building a
new inner-city highway. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SNOWBIRD _ For the third consecutive winter, fewer Snowbirds are
flocking to metro Phoenix. East Valley businesses that rely on
winter visitors are reporting a 25 percent downturn in sales.
Besides demographic changes, the most commonly cited factors in the
decline are worsening Valley traffic and air, higher prices, the
disappearing desert, lower Canadian exchange rates, and Canadian
public health-insurance restrictions. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SNOW-MESA _ ViewPoint RV and Golf Resort in Mesa, one of the
Valley's largest snowbird retreats, has room to grow by more than a
third _ adding 700 spaces. That is, if its owners can figure out
what the coming wave of baby-boom retirees want. What do retiring
boomers want? Condos instead of block-long RVs? Casitas with
adjoining basketball, volleyball and tennis courts? Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY-HOMICIDE (Undated) - For longtime fans of the show,
Homicide: The Movie serves as a welcome treat, as well as a
satisfying conclusion to the late, lamented series. For those of us
who didn't catch on the first time around, it's not that simple.
Instead, the NBC movie, which reunites all the major cast members _
yes, the ``dead'' ones, too _ is a two-hour tease, a reminder of
what we should have been watching all those years and now have to
do without. By Bill Goodykoontz. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
