<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-WESTMINSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9-YEAR-OLD HOUND RETURNS FOR FINAL CHALLENGE AT WESTMINSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It worked for Michael Jordan. Why not a triumphant
comeback for Ch. Tryst of Grandeur? The 9-year-old black Afghan
hound, who did not compete in 1997 and 1998, is back with a
vengeance at the 124th Westminster Kennel Dog Show.
</P>
<P>
   During her professional hiatus, Tryst, as the Afghan is known,
lived at the Mill Neck, N.Y., home of her owner, gave birth to two
litters and rested on her estimable reputation as the winningest
hound ever.
</P>
<P>
   But now she is back, a bit gray in the muzzle (and not hiding
it), bent on proving that she can win at Westminster, which runs
Monday and Tuesday at Madison Square Garden. Forty-three years ago,
a distant relative, Ch. Shirkhan of Grandeur, won best-in-show at
the venerable show.
</P>
<P>
   Tryst retired after finishing a disappointing third in the hound
group at the Westminster in 1997. Although praised by the judge as
``dramatic, exquisite and exotic,'' an upstart wire-haired
dachshund upset the field.
</P>
<P>
   Tryst's road from the canine Century Village began with her
entry, sort of a cameo, at last year's Westminster. The hound did
not win her breed, but her showing encouraged her owners, the
Rechler family, and her handler, Michael Canalizo, to mount a final
campaign to win best-in-show at Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got so much support from people who thought she looked so
good,'' said Canalizo, of Freeport, N.Y. ``We wrestled with the
decision to show her again for two months.'' Then, Tryst delivered,
as if she had never been away.
</P>
<P>
   In barely eight months, she racked up 25 best-in-shows,
defeating 42,866 dogs, including every last hound. She is the
ninth-ranked dog in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for an old girl with a son and daughter about to start
their own show careers. ``She's never shown better,'' Canalizo
said. ``People say she's better the second time around. She's the
Tina Turner of dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens at the show, Tryst, and Canalizo will retire
together.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan's return is only one of the tales at the show, which
changed its rules to be certain that all 156 breeds recognized by
the American Kennel Club will be represented. Some years, a pawful
of breeds were omitted, leading aggrieved owners to wonder if the
club was finagling with the entries.
</P>
<P>
   So the show invited the top seeds _ the best five dogs in their
breed competitions in 1999 _ and received 603 acceptances. The
final field of 2,500 is led by 43 Golden Retrievers, 42 Rhodesian
Ridgebacks and 39 Poodles.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 92 best-of-breeds from last year's are returning. So are
three group winners: the Saluki Ch. Sundown Alabaster Treasure, the
German Ch. Windwalker's Yes Virginia and the Standard Poodle Ch.
Lakecove That's My Boy.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-and-a-half-year-old poodle, known as Treson, is the
nation's top-ranked dog and has won 169 best-in-shows in her
two-year show career. But being the top dog going is no guarantee
of leaving the Garden with the best-in-show rosette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not confident at all,'' said his handler, Dennis McCoy,
who will retire, along with Treson and the groomer, Randy Garren,
after the show.
</P>
<P>
   For all anyone knows, a canine equivalent of the St. Louis Rams,
unranked and unheralded, will emerge from the 2,500 entries to
upset the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Treson's ancestry bespeaks success in the best-in-show ring. His
grandfather, Ch. Whisperwind on Carousel, or Peter, won the 1991
Westminster crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treson is very much like Peter, a little more masculine and
stronger,'' McCoy said. ``Some people thought Peter was a bit
unisex, a little effeminate. Treson has a bigger head and a bigger
neck. But he's so much like Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the judge of the non-sporting group chose Treson the
winner, declaring that he exuded ``poodleyness.'' Who could ask for
anything more?
</P>
<P>
   But poodleyness was not enough. A six-pound papillon, Ch. Loteki
Supernatural Being, won best-in-show and leaped into his silver
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Treson is one of the most extravagantly groomed dogs in dogdom,
a pompadoured, teased and shaved paragon. But don't let Treson's
elegant coif fool you. He's really a regular guy until he's in the
spotlight. ``He's playful and fun, but when he's in a ring, he
says, `Look at me!''' McCoy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giant Schnauzer Ch. Skansen's Tristan II heads into the show
suffering from morning sickness (she's due in April) and sciatica
that required chiropractic treatment to keep the 4-year-old from
leaning on one leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fly a lot and the crate probably got banged around,'' said
Bill McFadden, who handles Tristan for Marilu Hansen of Newton,
N.J., and Arthur T. Brown of Lakesport, Calif. The chiropractor
will be on call at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Being the country's second-ranked dog offers McFadden little
comfort that Tristan can beat the other 11 Giant Schnauzers in her
breed, let alone overwhelm the Akitas, Malamutes, Boxers, Great
Danes and other working group dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two types of Giant Schnauzers: the American, like
Tristan, and the European,'' said McFadden. ``The judge in the
breed has only judged Tristan once, and from my information, he
likes the European type.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe McFadden is putting the judge on notice: Remember why
Tristan was 1999's apotheosis of schnauzerliness. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SKATE-KWAN-NYT &LR;      02-13 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-KWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN IS BIDING HER TIME ON AND OFF THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Michelle Kwan won her fourth national figure skating
title Saturday night, but her victory carried more of a sense of
farewell than coronation. She gave the impression that she was
holding on, biding time, and time may be running out on her
Olympic-style career.
</P>
<P>
   She pronounced herself satisfied with her long program, but in
truth she had been failed by her jumping, by her listless
enthusiasm and by music and choreography so bleak and dull that it
pushed the audience away instead of drawing it in.
</P>
<P>
   She won only because her challengers are not yet out of braces,
still in the awkward stage where artistry lags behind eagerness.
With 25 seconds remaining in her long program, 15-year-old Sasha
Cohen of Costa Mesa, Calif., seemed ready to topple Kwan with an
elastic, elegant routine, but she fell on a triple toe loop and the
judges marked her harshly. Cohen's scores, as low as 5.4 for
technical merit, seemed artificially low, as if Kwan had to be
propped up for political reasons, like some Third World potentate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would have won if I had landed the jump,''
Cohen said. ``Michelle is a world and Olympic skater. She is well
known and she has a reputation that I don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Kwan, she possessed a champion's resilience and
determination, improvising with a triple toe loop at the end of her
program, giving her six triple jumps overall. And she has a
dramatic eloquence that none of her young challengers express can
yet express.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of myself,'' the 19-year-old Kwan said. ``I was
strong this week. I didn't give an inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong perhaps, but vulnerable, too. She fell both in the short
program and long program. She has not skated cleanly in both
programs since the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, where
caution cost her a gold medal. That same tentativeness was evident
Saturday night. Skating to the somber soundtrack from the movie,
``The Red Violin,'' Kwan said, ``It suited my mood perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She needs to change her direction and revisit her image and
work on something more dynamic and use music that will bring people
into the performance instead of alienating them,'' said Jirina
Ribbens, a figure skating expert from New York City and a longtime
fan of Kwan's. ``She needs to attack. She's a talented athlete, a
mature, lyrical skater, but these qualities are not being showcased
to the utmost of their possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the Nagano Olympics, Kwan faced one younger
challenger in Tara Lipinski. Now she faces at least four _ Cohen;
the 14-year-old Sarah Hughes of Great Neck, N.Y., who finished
third on Saturday while skating a more ambitious program than
Kwan's; 15-year-old Jennifer Kirk of Newton, Mass., who finished
seventh and has a beautiful tightness in her jumping; and
14-year-old Naomi Nari Nam of Irvine, Calif., who finished second a
year ago and eighth this year as she struggled to adjust to her
growing body.
</P>
<P>
   A maximum of three American women will qualify for the 2002
Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City. A real possibility exists that
the team will not include Kwan. It is reflective of figure
skating's cruel winnowing that someone 19 years old can be in
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Like Michael Weiss, who defended the men's national title
despite the fact that Timothy Goebel landed three quadruple jumps,
Kwan remains on top with her artistry while she continues to fall
behind the technical advances in jumping. Hughes became the first
American woman to land a triple salchow-triple loop combination on
Saturday while Kwan could not complete the much easier triple
toe-triple toe. And while Kwan hopes to perfect a triple-triple
combination, Hughes is already working on a quadruple jump and a
triple axel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder because I know I'm not getting younger and my legs
won't keep up with me,'' Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   To many at the national championships, she seemed distracted,
unfocused. Kwan is in college now, a freshman at UCLA, and it has
been a struggle to balance the rigors of school and skating. She
admitted that her motivation was sometimes difficult to summon.
``The only time you see a sparkle in her eyes is when she talks
about school,'' said one prominent skating coach.
</P>
<P>
   She was hit with a flurry of questions the past week: Does she
really want to continue in Olympic-style skating? Is she enjoying
herself? Is she continuing out of desperation, unfulfilled after
winning a silver medal at Nagano? Is she cornered by commercial
endorsements tied to her appearance in Salt Lake City?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think I'm going to turn pro,'' Kwan said.
``That's not where I want to be right now. I might not be
professional ever. You might see me until 2006. This is what I love
doing. You might not see a smiling, happy face all the time, but
this is where I want to be. Deep down I feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some coaches and agents said that there appeared to
be a sort of tug-of-war for control of Kwan's skating between her
coach, Frank Carroll, and her father, Danny Kwan. Said Carroll:
``They are a tight family. He is concerned about her skating. He is
with her all the time, I am not. It's like any coach's relationship
with parents. Usually we get along fine. There are great times and
not so great times, but I'd say our relationship is very good. I
like Danny.''
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the world championships next month in Nice,
France, Carroll said that Kwan must dedicate more time to training,
that he will no longer allow her to run through her free skate if
she misses the triple-triple combination. Already, she has scaled
back school to one class.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, she can't have a life,'' Danny Kwan said. Then,
to suggest that he was joking, he said, ``Noooo.''
</P>
<P>
   Still the questions persist. Does she have the determination to
increase the difficulty of her jumps? Or the strength?
</P>
<P>
   ``At my first nationals, people said, `She's the jumping
bean,''' Kwan said. ``Now I'm `artistic, beautiful on the ice.' I
want to be well-rounded. And I want to be the jumping bean again. I
can do it. I have to bring it up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
