<HEADLINE>
DIGEST OF THE DAY'S FINANCIAL STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's Consumer Chief Is Expected to Resign
</P>
<P>
   H. Eugene Lockhart, president of the core consumer unit at AT&AMP;T,
intends to step down barely a year after joining the company,
executives close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart's future plans are unclear. His departure would
probably not be seen as a significant operational blow to AT&AMP;T. But
it could raise questions about the ability of C. Michael Armstrong,
AT&AMP;T's chairman, to identify and retain key executive talent.
</P>
<P>
   Beardstown Ladies Go to Court
</P>
<P>
   Courts in New York and California have made diametrically
opposing judgments in lawsuits that challenge dust-jacket claims on
the ``The Beardstown Ladies' Common-Sense Investment Guide.'' The
guide claimed returns from the ladies' investment approach that
were much higher than actual returns. The publisher now faces
several legal challenges stemming from those claims. Those suits,
and others like them, question whether some of the standard puffery
on a book jacket amounts to free speech protected by the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank to Form Internet Fund
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank's International Finance Corp. unit will announce
Monday that it has teamed up with Softbank of Japan to create a
$200 million fund that will finance Internet start ups in 100
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   A New Season for Gift Certificates
</P>
<P>
   Companies that sell gift certificates online report that weekly
revenues so far this year are actually increasing, despite the fact
that post-holiday sales to consumers have leveled off. The
companies are apparently benefiting from the nation's labor
shortage: As companies struggle to attract and retain workers, many
are turning to corporate gift programs _ and online gift
certificates, they say, are a cheap and easy way to award perks.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer Internet Backbone Providers
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Web site attacks were a reminder that technology's
sword of individual empowerment has a double edge. But the term for
the attack technique _ denial of service _ has the potential to
assume an equally ominous meaning as telecommunications giants
continue to merge their holdings. For example, upon completion of
the Worldcom-Sprint merger, a single company would control nearly
half of the Internet's backbone.
</P>
<P>
   This Guinness Is for You
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness Bass Import Co., the unit of Diageo that
distributes and markets Guinness stout in the United States, is
overhauling its sales pitch in substantive ways meant to make the
brand seem less intimidating to those Americans, particularly in
their mid-20s, who typically favor imported beers. That demographic
group is often put off by the iconic, even imperial, image of
Guinness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
