<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-LANDRY-REMEMBER-A     02-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-REMEMBER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM LANDRY IS REMEMBERED FOR THE FIRE WITHIN HIS DIGNIFIED
PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1-4 were sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He became famous for his appearance _ the sideline stoicism, the
courtly attire, a continence in the midst of a brutal sport, and of
course, for his hat.
</P>
<P>
   But to his players, to his colleagues in National Football
League and to the state of Texas, longtime Dallas Cowboys Coach Tom
Landry represented much more. He was a father figure, a football
innovator, even the gentlemanly and noble symbol that helped buoy
Texans at a time when a state's identity seemed all too wrapped in
the stigma of the assassination of President Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Landry was the coach of what came to be known as America's Team,
and if he appeared more professor or bank president than football
coach, then that set a standard, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He conducted himself with such dignity and poise, it set the
example for how you should live your life,'' Charlie Waters, a
Cowboys safety for 11 seasons said of his former coach, who died of
leukemia Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't understand the weight of his influence. Because
he wasn't a yeller and screamer, people thought he didn't motivate
or make people better with his approach and his presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he had, for example, a look he gave his players, and we
all hated it when he gave us that look. It was haunting, because
the look said, `Why are you letting yourself down? Why are you
letting me down?' Tell me that didn't motivate. None of us wanted
to disappoint Coach Landry.''
</P>
<P>
   The diverse, lengthy and Football Hall of Fame career of Landry,
who was 75, inspired many _ contemporaries and competitors alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``People search for heroes in this world,'' said Gil Brandt, the
Cowboys longtime front office executive, said in a recent
interview. ``And years ago, some of those people turned on their
television every Sunday and saw a guy who wasn't dissolving into
fits of anger, who wasn't using bad language, who was mannerly and
well-dressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet, he was still driven and competitive and won
championships. Is that not a worthy hero?''
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Mara, the Giants co-owner, knew Landry as a former
Giants assistant coach and later as the head coach of a chief
rival. For 30 years, when the Cowboys came to the New York area to
play the Giants, the two would have dinner on the eve of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess his reputation is someone who's aloof,'' Mara said.
``But there was a lot of fire burning inside him. You might know
part of him by looking at him, but you didn't know it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's impassive demeanor in public indeed was a trademark,
but it concealed, for example, a dynamic football mind. He
single-handedly revived the shotgun formation in the modern era of
football, he devised the 4-3 defense _ pro football's model defense
_ in the 1950s, he was the first to computerize the strategy and
game planning of a NFL team in the 1960s and his flex defense was
revolutionary in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   An engineering major at the University of Texas, Landry could
draw up a football play so precise and interconnected, it looked
like the plans for a high-rise building. And it would stand the
test of time, too.
</P>
<P>
   Respect for Landry in the NFL ran deep. After several years as
the Giants defensive coordinator, he became the first coach of the
Cowboys in 1960, a hapless expansion franchise that won just four
games in its first two seasons. But by 1966, Dallas was in the NFL
championship game. Landry's Cowboys didn't have another losing
season until 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty consecutive winning seasons,'' George Young, the former
Giants general manager and now the league's deputy vice president,
said recently. ``That gets you plenty of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Young often tells the story of his preparations for Super Bowl
V, when Landry's Cowboys played the Baltimore Colts, for whom Young
was the offensive line coach.
</P>
<P>
   All week the Colts prepared for the Cowboys defense they had
seen on film all season, but Young kept asking: What if they change
it up on us?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told, `They won't do that. This has been Landry's
defense for years and he's not going to change it now, not when
he's playing the biggest game of the year.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, wouldn't you know, that's exactly what he did to us.''
</P>
<P>
   His former players, and his colleagues, acknowledged that much
of Landry's reputation was well-earned. He was extremely private
and not known for grandiose gestures or self-promotion. Some who
knew him for 50 years never knew he was a bomber pilot in World War
II who narrowly avoided death in a harrowing crash landing in the
French countryside.
</P>
<P>
   He liked to read and spent countless hours across four decades
traveling the country in the football off-season to appear at
functions that raised money for the Fellowship of Christian
Athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Landry's reputation for keeping his players at a distance was
legendary and well-deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he forced himself to do that because he knew he'd have
to be honest with players he had to release,'' Waters said. ``And
he couldn't be emotional about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the former Cowboys fullback Walt Garrison was once
asked if he had ever seen Landry smile, Garrison answered: ``No, I
only played nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry coached five Hall of Fame players in Dallas _ Roger
Staubach, Randy White, Bob Lilly, Mel Renfro and Tony Dorsett _ and
an equal number as an assistant with the Giants. He also helped
develop two of the most prominent coaches of the 1980s and '90s,
Dan Reeves and Mike Ditka, both of whom played for Landry and then
worked as assistants under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shaped my philosophy on everything,'' Reeves said. ``I
followed his philosophy on football and how he handled himself on
and off the field. He was a tremendous influence on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry won two Super Bowls and his teams appeared in five. While
he was criticized for turning his players into robots, he coached a
number of charismatic, iconoclastic players, including Don
Meredith, Duane Thomas, Thomas (Hollywood) Henderson, Pete Gent and
Lance Rentzel.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he coached a different kind of team, one that relied
on organization and ingenuity, a forward-thinking team that often
seemed in contrast to the dusty, blood-and-guts tradition of
earlier eras in the league. Symbolically, Landry's team played
mostly on artificial turf and usually in the sun, and often, for
television purposes, late on Sunday afternoons, which cultivated
their popularity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, to some at least, Landry's teams put a new face
on the city of Dallas in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Coach Landry's legacy,'' Waters said. ``Is what he did
for our city and state. For a lot of people in America back then,
all they knew about Dallas was that President Kennedy had been
assassinated there. They associated the place with that great loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stigma was real and it was a burden we all inherited,
including Coach Landry who was raised in Mission, Texas. But Coach
Landry helped us turn the corner on that with the way he handled
himself _ in bad times and good times. He was the conductor for all
that changed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the man on the sideline in the hat, an image so abiding
that when he was inducted into the Cowboys Ring of Honor at Texas
Stadium, they put a small outline of a fedora next to his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of the Cowboys started with Tom,'' Staubach said.
``The Cowboys will always be more than just another team because of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And Landry's friends and admirers, Staubach included, insist
that on occasion at least, the stoic coach did smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom wanted to show Roger Staubach how to run a quarterback
bootleg once,'' Brandt said. ``And he got behind the center and ran
the play, except that Tom had an old knee injury and he limped
badly as he ran around that corner with the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Tom says: `OK, do it like that.' And Roger took the ball
from center and ran it just like Tom did, hobbling and limping all
the way around the corner. Tom just burst out laughing and so did
everyone else. Guys were falling down they were laughing so
hard.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-ANGOLA-WAR-ART-NYT &LR;      02-13 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ANGOLA-WAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS SEIZE THE OFFENSIVE AGAINST GOVERNMENT TROOPS IN ANGOLA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By RACHEL SWARNS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUAMBO, Angola _ The astonishing news crackled over the radios
in this crumbling town of faded colonial mansions and rolling green
hills. One by one, the radio announcer said, the nearby rebel
strongholds were falling into government hands.
</P>
<P>
   And for three months, hope blossomed here.
</P>
<P>
   The mortars stopped falling. Relief workers made plans to send
thousands of refugees home. And Silvano Chingala Mindo, a
19-year-old student who saw his two friends killed by shrapnel last
October, began to believe he might live long enough to become a
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the waves of war are once again lapping over
Angola, and over this weary city. The guerrillas are storming
through the countryside, villagers are fleeing to refugee camps and
the fragile hopes that buoyed this bullet-pocked town are waning.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of back-to-back victories late last year, the
government apparently thought it had finally triumphed over the
guerrillas known as Unita _the Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, which until 1975 was a
Portuguese colony. Now, in the seemingly endless war that has raged
ever since, pitting Unita's leader, Jonas Savimbi, against his
fierce rival, President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the rebels have
seized the offensive once more.
</P>
<P>
   Unita claims to have killed 882 government soldiers over the
past month. This week, the government, which had repeatedly boasted
that it had destroyed 80 percent of Unita's war machine, publicly
acknowledged that the battle is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Paulina Wenda discovered the rebels were still a potent force
last week when they opened fire on her village in nearby Mbave. She
grabbed her children and they ran barefoot, leaving their hut,
their pots, their clothes, their land.
</P>
<P>
   She had heard the radio broadcasts and the government officials
who claimed they were finally winning. ``But there's no
difference,'' Wenda, 35, said wearily as she stood in a refugee
camp near here. ``We're still losing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Military experts say the government underestimated Unita, and
they predict the guerrillas will continue fighting to capitalize on
the rainy season here that has hobbled the government's tanks and
jets in thick mud and dense clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had Unita on their knees and it's not so,''
said Johann Smith, a military analyst, who served as the South
African Defense Force's attache to Luanda, the capital here, in
1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've absorbed the initial shock of the successes against
them,'' said Smith, who still monitors the conflict and Unita.
``They're up and running. And they're definitely going to use this
window of time to strengthen their position.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the action has been military, however. After the
government drove the rebels from their traditional strongholds of
Bailundo, Andulo and Jamba between September and December last
year, Unita announced that it wanted to reopen negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast on government radio last week, dos Santos
said he believed Angola was stable enough to hold national
elections next year and invited Unita's soldiers to lay down their
arms and organize their political party.
</P>
<P>
   That news was enough for Veronica Chilombo, 36, who lost her
left leg in an accident, to leave her village, which had been under
rebel control. For two days, she hobbled on wooden crutches until
she reached a hospital here in government-controlled Huambo, where
she could finally ask for an artificial leg.
</P>
<P>
   Valdemar Franco Secesec, a 25-year-old nurse, said he was
heartened by commercial flights flying into the airport again and
the trucks rolling in on roads that were once too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have hope that one day soon this war will end,'' Franco
said. ``You have to have hope. There is nothing else to keep us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been no clear signs that the two sides will
actually come together.
</P>
<P>
   The war here used to have an ideological base: dos Santos was
backed by Russia and Cuba, Savimbi by the United States. Gradually,
it has turned into more of a battle for Angola's huge spoils _ the
oil controlled by the government, and the diamond mines by Unita.
</P>
<P>
   There is still much finger-pointing on both sides about the
failure of the 1994 peace treaty that gave Angola its longest
cease-fire in 30 years. The fighting resumed in 1998, with Unita
initially making strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of easing, this civil war has now spread beyond its
borders, spilling into neighboring Namibia, which late last year
allowed the Angolan government to fight from its soil, where the
conflict has already claimed dozens of civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the two sides talk peace and wage war, and ordinary
people suffer. Strangely enough, in this still-graceful town of
red-tile roofs and elegant leafy plazas, such contradictions seem
oddly logical.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is a place where the only hotel has shiny water
faucets, but no running water; light switches, but no electricity
during the day. A graffiti artist has scrawled the word ``paz'' or
``peace'' on a building still riddled with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a war that ebbs and flows, where the winners on one day
are often the losers on the next. The government controls most of
the cities and towns, but Unita is still strong in the countryside.
And it is often difficult to tell where and when the fighting ends
and the peace begins.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Doctors Without Borders, which runs a clinic for
refugees here, accepted the official word about peace in the
region, and sent trucks rumbling out into the countryside to screen
poor children for malnutrition. But two weeks ago, they stopped,
frightened by new reports of violence and by the shelling that
jolted their nurses from sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local staff didn't want to go anymore,'' said Gunilla
Priebe, a nurse with the organization. ``And we trust their
information more than the official information. It's more
reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals, teen-agers like Chingala, gossip and giggle and lean
against a dilapidated building that has long since lost its glass
windows and wooden doors. The girls laugh when asked whether they
think the war is ending. It is something they cannot imagine. All
they know is war.
</P>
<P>
   Chingala does not laugh. He was walking home from school with
his friends last October when the shell exploded. He survived
unscathed, but when he saw their bloodied bodies, he thought he saw
his own fate.
</P>
<P>
   And so he prays for peace because he wants to grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if peace stays, I will have a future,'' he said.
``They say Unita has no longer any possibility to win offensives. I
heard it on the radio. I just hope it's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
