<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5639 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ASBESTOS-EPA-SPI &LR;      02-13 2270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-EPA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA FEARS NEW VICTIMS OF ASBESTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER and CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency investigators are scouring store
shelves to see if consumers are unknowingly buying asbestos, and
the lethal fibers have turned up in some of the products they have
tested.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators caution against overreacting to the
preliminary test results. But some of the findings, involving
commonly used household products, could be a cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   The asbestos industry stymied the agency almost a decade ago,
winning a suit to overturn the EPA's ban on asbestos. Nevertheless,
agency staffers say, they have a responsibility to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ban or no ban, we still have an obligation to take whatever
actions necessary to protect the public health,'' says John Melone,
director of EPA's National Program Chemical Division. ``There are
too many flags going up about possible problems with asbestos for
us not to pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, Neil Pflum, EPA's asbestos coordinator for the
southwest states, is examining building products found in
home-improvement stores.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, Keven McDermott of EPA's Pacific Northwest
Investigative Response Team and her partners are testing potting
soil, vermiculite and other lawn products for asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   In Libby, Mont., Paul Peronard is EPA's on-scene coordinator.
His emergency response team has found lingering asbestos from a
vermiculite mine that closed ten years ago. He wants the agency to
consider whether the public is at risk from millions of bags of
home insulation sold across North America by W.R. Grace &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   These environmental investigators have to work with two stinging
realities:
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. and Canadian asbestos industries won their suit
to overturn EPA's ban on asbestos in 1991, tools to regulate
consumers' exposure are virtually nonexistent. And asbestos has
been known as a relentless killer for a century.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths from the microscopic fibers came in waves.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in World War II, who manhandled enormous amounts of
heavy asbestos insulation into warships and tanks, died by the
thousands. Most suffered for decades the slow, lingering deaths of
suffocation from asbestosis and the lung cancer it spawned. Others
died just months after being diagnosed with mesothelioma, a
fast-spreading cancer of the lining of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Construction workers, spraying asbestos-laden fireproofing onto
the steel skeletons of tens of thousands of new buildings in the
'60s and '70s, were the next wave of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The body count grows today. The EPA is worried that new victims
could be exposed to the dusty and deadly fibers of deteriorating
asbestos applied to schools, warehouses and buildings a generation
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the eventual death list the hundreds of vermiculite
miners and their families from the Grace mine in Libby, and the
workers throughout the country who processed the ore.
</P>
<P>
   Count in firefighters who wore coats and used hoses woven from
asbestos fabric, race car drivers and test pilots who used thinner
asbestos material to protect themselves from exploding fuel, and
automotive mechanics who changed brake shoes and pads.
</P>
<P>
   The list of victims is long.
</P>
<P>
   Public-health experts say that since the latency period -- the
time from exposure to when the disease surfaces -- can be as long
as 40 years, the body count from asbestos will grow well into this
new century. Doctors estimate that asbestos will kill more than
250,000 Americans over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   What is unknown is the risk to the multitude of people who had
far lower exposure to asbestos than the miner, the builder or the
shipyard worker -- the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA investigators testing products off store shelves are
concerned about exposure to a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos is a generic term used to describe a number of
naturally occurring fibrous minerals including chrysotile, amosite,
crocidolite, anthophyllite, actinolite and tremolite.
</P>
<P>
   All have been proved to kill.
</P>
<P>
   The asbestos fibers found in attic insulation and garden
products is tremolite, a natural contaminant of vermiculite. In
other products, Canadian chrysotile is usually the asbestos added
for fire protection, strength or abrasive qualities.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the asbestos industry, depending on what type of
fiber they're handling, has been quick to point fingers at other
types as being more dangerous. For example, the Canadians insist
their chrysotile is safe, but American tremolite is the killer.
U.S. firms say just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asbestos is asbestos,'' says Peronard. ``They all present a
health hazard and that's enough to trigger EPA's concern.''
</P>
<P>
   In Libby, where hundreds of vermiculite miners and their family
members have died or become ill with asbestosis, lung cancer or
mesothelioma, it is microscopic fibers of tremolite asbestos that
are doing the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Tremolite fibers are thin and needle-like and under the
microscope appear like javelins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The health experts that we're working with in Libby are
telling us that the 1 percent asbestos content that allows EPA
action may be higher then the threshold often linked to cancer,
especially when the asbestos is tremolite,'' Peronard says. ``This
is something we want to pin down.''
</P>
<P>
   Peronard and his team arrived in the Northwestern Montana town
in November, three days after the Post-Intelligencer began a series
of articles on the severe health problems of the miners and their
families exposed to asbestos from the now-closed vermiculite mine.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the vermiculite was sold by Grace as attic
insulation and as a soil enhancer for gardens. For the 30 years it
operated the mine, Grace shipped millions of tons of vermiculite
throughout North America.
</P>
<P>
   Peronard and his colleagues from the U.S. Public Health Service
question the whether Grace's attic insulation, called Zonolite,
contains enough asbestos to be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're testing the insulation in the homes in Libby and will be
asking other regions to check it out,'' Peronard says. ``We're not
saying it's dangerous, but we want to find out what we're dealing
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace stopped mining the vermiculite in Libby when it closed the
mine in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, while two of McDermott's team members, Jed Januch
and Dave Terpening, were gathering bags of vermiculite and lawn
products in the Seattle area, they found 10 bags of Grace's
Zonolite stacked in a garden store in Kent.
</P>
<P>
   EPA tested the contents of the large green and brown bag and
found asbestos contamination. The Post-Intelligencer bought a bag
at the same store, had it tested at a different lab and asbestos
was also detected.
</P>
<P>
   In their preliminary testing, McDermott and her team found
asbestos fibers in two other garden products being sold locally,
but she said ``A lot more testing has to be done before we know
what we really have.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA asbestos experts say that even if a home is insulated with
asbestos-laced vermiculite, the hazards are probably minimal unless
the homeowner disturbs it.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos specialists in the agency advise homeowners to avoid
contact with the insulation and if the material is not leaking into
the house, the risk should be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   However, they caution that if the Zonolite is being replaced or
removed in a renovation, the homeowner must use a respirator with
``Hepa'' cartridge. The little blue cloth or paper dust masks won't
keep the asbestos fibers out. Additional precautions can be
obtained from the EPA or local and state environmental offices.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, which sold millions of bags of vermiculite attic
insulation and for decades was the nation's largest producer of
vermiculite for horticultural products, repeatedly said there was
nothing dangerous in its products, a claim the company maintains
today for vermiculite being mined and sold from its mine in Enoree,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   EPA has long been concerned about the potential health effects
to workers and consumers from asbestos-contaminated vermiculite,
with its first studies going back to the '70s and '80s. Its last
report, in 1991, stated that 188,000 people were exposed to
asbestos-contaminated vermiculite in attic insulation, 32 million
from garden fertilizer and 74 million from other lawn products, but
there was no interpretation of the risks involved. Studies on the
health effects of these exposure to the public were strongly
recommended by the researchers involved, but were never funded.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan and Bush administrations failed to support EPA's
efforts to ban asbestos. And the Clinton White House, which touts
itself as ``environmentally sensitive,'' has done nothing in the
past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, EPA has renewed, at least on a small scale, its
efforts to see if the public is at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years there has been speculation over whether the
manufacturers have actually taken the asbestos out of the end
products or not,'' Melone says. ``There is a long history of
concerns with vermiculite products and what these products may
actually contain. This looks like the time to try and untangle the
maze and pin down the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA's Seattle team has purchased 16 bags of various vermiculite
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lots of calls from citizens who had read the P-I's
stories on the death of the miners in Libby from the contaminated
vermiculite and they wanted to know whether it was safe to use
these products,'' McDermott says. ``We just didn't have the
information on whether there was asbestos in these products or not,
so we decided to test them.'' She added, ``The public has a right
to know whether common household products are safe, or contain
cancer-causing ingredients such as asbestos.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the asbestos industry and some physicians insist that if
anyone is at risk from asbestos it is only workers who are exposed
to huge doses over a period of years, not consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at the National Institute for Occupational
Safety and Health disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect after several decades of a one-time acute dose (of
asbestos) of limited duration . . . may be as harmful as the
cumulative effect of lower daily doses of exposure over many years
of work,'' the agency's doctors reported in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work under the assumption that there is no safe level of
asbestos exposure. Asbestos is like a time bomb. Once you've been
exposed you don't know how your body will respond over time. Our
goal is to determine whether there is asbestos in these products
and then minimize the exposure,'' McDermott says.
</P>
<P>
   With most toxic materials it may take multiple exposures before
a dangerous level of exposure is reached. But asbestos has the
capability to cause irreversible harm with just a single exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The NIOSH doctors agree, saying a single fiber deeply embedding
itself in the right place in the lung could be all it takes to
develop Mesothelioma.
</P>
<P>
   In EPA's laboratory in Manchester, Washington, across Puget
Sound from Seattle, Januch and other team members have installed
air monitoring equipment in a 3-x4-foot sealed enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Monday they will begin working with the vermiculite products to
see if asbestos is released in normal use of the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a lot of work, but we're hoping to
accurately duplicate what the consumer does to determine whether
they are potentially exposed to when they use these products,''
Januch says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our toxicologists will evaluate the results to determine
whether there is a health risk or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, Pflum says with over 3,000 products on the market
with asbestos in them, the research that's being done on consumer
products is vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. It's very important,'' the asbestos coordinator
says. ``People just don't know that the ban was overturned.''
</P>
<P>
   Other EPA regions and headquarters helped Pflum determine which
building products commonly used in the construction of schools,
homes and public buildings should be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was to go out and see if we could find asbestos
and if we found any, see if the manufacturer warned the consumer
that the product contained asbestos,'' Pflum says.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA ordered the testing of 20 different categories of
products, a total of 50 individual samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three categories of products came back hot, containing over
one percent asbestos,'' Pflum says. ``Four others came back with
traces of asbestos.''
</P>
<P>
   Research done by scientists in preparation for EPA's 1989
attempt at banning asbestos showed that while the fibers were
encapsulated within the tiles, surfacing, pipe and other products,
they were released into the air, sometimes in heavy concentrations,
while the material was being cut, molded sanded, buffed or
otherwise worked with.
</P>
<P>
   Pflum and McDermott declined ito identify the specific products
they were examining until additional confirmation testing was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But Pflum did say that of the hot samples, those at or above
EPA's action level, two were fairly uncommon products, but one
contaminated category is something that could be found in many
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a significant number of products that come back at
over one percent asbestos, which is our definition of
asbestos-containing material, then we will urge headquarters to
consider developing a labeling rule,'' Pflum says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in EPA headquarters, Melone says he's waiting
for the reports from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they find will guide what the agency does next,'' says
Melone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
