<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILITARY-ANTITERROR-8     02-13 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-ANTITERROR-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW UNIT'S DRESS REHEARSAL FOR DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Puerto Rico, Virgin Islands)   (rk) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAM, N.Y. _ The unmarked convoy arrived in the gray-blue
light of dusk, seven dark trucks winding through Albany's suburbs
and stopping upwind of a gymnasium here. Soon groups of soldiers in
gas masks and chemical-protection suits began trudging through the
snow. They were in for a long night.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were part of a simulated gas attack on an upstate
arena, and had been told only that a small bomb had been detonated
at a basketball game, spreading vapors that sickened a dozen
spectators. As local firefighters kept their distance, the soldiers
were assigned to enter the contaminated area to find out what
happened. Was it anthrax? A blister agent? Nerve gas? A noxious
prank?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go,'' said the team's commander, Lt. Col. Robert L.
Domenici, as his soldiers tugged their equipment from the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-member team is part of a newly formed cadre of full-time
specialists created to help local police departments and
firefighters after a chemical, biological or radioactive attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is forming 27 of these groups, called Weapons of
Mass Destruction Civilian Support Teams, which fall under the
command of the state National Guards and are assigned to zones
established by the Federal Emergency Management Agency. Their
missions are to assess the scope and severity of a terrorist attack
by sampling suspected germs, chemicals or radioactive material, and
then to advise civilian agencies on how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   The team training in Latham, stationed at Stratton Air National
Guard Base in Scotia, N.Y., and assigned to cover New York, New
Jersey, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands, begins its final
Department of Defense evaluation exercises Tuesday at Fort Drum. It
is expected to be on call by April, along with nine of the other
teams around the nation. The remaining teams are scheduled to be on
duty by spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The team includes former Marines, Army rangers, a Green Beret
and an airman once assigned to a Titan 2 nuclear missile silo in
Arkansas. Once these service members were trained to kill, whether
by bayonet, smart bomb or nuclear strike. Now they form a
protection team, more likely to be deployed in Buffalo than Beirut.
Their only weapons are pistols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it a lot, about how I went from being a
killer to turning around and being a defender,'' said Tech. Sgt.
Robert J. Fruggiero, 36, of Saratoga, N.Y., who spent much of the
1980s maintaining a nuclear weapon he described as ``basically
designed to blow a hole in the ground, a half a mile in diameter,
800 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big shift,'' he said. ``And I tell you, I feel a lot
better about this, compared to what I used to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another team member, Spc. Brian A. Gordon, 24, of Coxsackie,
N.Y., and a former marine infantryman, said in characteristic
Marine Corps fashion that the change in his work was
``mind-boggling, sir.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that I knew that I was going to go in and kill
somebody with a weapon,'' he said. ``Now it's, `Here's your gas
mask, let's go in there, get the victims out and figure out what
happened.'''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the civilian support teams reach to events of the
mid-1990s. In a 27-month period from 1993 to 1995, the World Trade
Center was bombed, killing six and injuring more than 1,000; a
religious sect released sarin nerve gas in the Tokyo subway system,
killing 12 and injuring 5,500; and Timothy McVeigh leveled the
federal building in Oklahoma City with a truck bomb, killing 168
and injuring hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   ``These events changed the psyche of how we are going to defend
the United States,'' Domenici said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress passed the Defense Against Weapons of Mass
Destruction Act, which mandated increased domestic preparedness
against terrorist attacks, especially those involving chemical,
biological or nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the Pentagon decided to integrate the National
Guard into the effort, knowing that Guard units were already placed
in the most vulnerable areas, and that giving state control to the
teams would offset some concerns about the military performing
police duties, which would violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the creation of the Civilian Support Teams, which
in 1998 began an 18-month training period to prepare for this new
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome M. Hauer, who recently left his job as director New York
City's Office of Emergency Management, where he supervised the
city's anti-terrorism efforts, said the National Guard teams would
provide an invaluable capability to cities too small to support
specialists of their own. For example, he noted that the teams
would be staged with gear loaded onto trucks, near aircraft, ready
to drive or fly to places throughout their coverage area within
four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hauer also said he expected the teams to see action. ``It is my
belief that, at least in the near term, the biggest terrorist
threat is from guns and conventional bombs,'' he said. ``But the
dynamic is changing, and I think that over the next 10 years a
chemical or biological weapon will be used in the United States.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. William C. Martin, deputy commander of New York's
National Guard, watched the group's final exercise in Latham. He
said the team, with its full-time soldiers and $7.8 million in
equipment and recent training, is a departure from the recent past,
when the Guard trained mainly to reinforce active-duty forces in
missions overseas, and almost all its soldiers worked part-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so focused on a Cold War mentality that we weren't
relevant anymore'' to national defense, he said. ``Once we had the
luxury of fighting our nation's wars on someone else's soil. That
doesn't exist the same way today.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, between snow banks, Tech. Sgt. Jeffrey Quinn, 37, a
former Green Beret medic, watched over Sgt. Peter C. Nestor and
Gordon as they prepared their gear for a survey of the contaminated
area. Quinn said he had a personal motivation behind his new work.
His aunt, uncle and two cousins were badly injured in the bombing
of a hotel in Kenya on New Year's Eve, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been touched by terrorism,'' he said. ``And when I heard
they were putting together something like this, to help with
civilian casualties, and to safeguard home soil, I saw the ability
to bring some peace of mind to people. So here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The two soldiers donned their blue suits, gloves, boots, heavy
air packs and masks. They left Quinn behind and walked slowly
toward the gymnasium, dragging a cart full of detection equipment.
In this exercise, civilian casualties had been evacuated before the
team arrived, and local hospitals needed to know what chemicals had
been dispersed that made them sick.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a small exercise room, the soldiers found the simulated
remains of a bomb, and began testing the residue. Their work was a
mix of brute strength and finesse, alternately requiring moving
debris and manipulating small detection kits, which involved
breaking open jelly-bean-sized ampuls or mixing fluids and
collecting residue with cotton swabs.
</P>
<P>
   For men wearing four pairs of gloves, weighted by equipment, and
peering through face masks and plastic hoods, the work was tedious.
Their masks steamed up in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for the results of the nerve gas detection kit,
the pair slowly searched the rest of the gymnasium for other
threats. They found grainy powder on the floor, and suspected a
biological agent. Minutes later, after testing the powder, they got
a simulated reading. ``Positive hit, anthrax,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Positive hit on anthrax,'' Nestor said by radio to the
commanders outside.
</P>
<P>
   Then the operation shifted. Bernard Kirk, an evaluator from the
New York's Department of State, decided to apply stress. He
designated Gordon a casualty, and ordered him to slump over,
paralyzed as if the nerve gas in the other room had penetrated his
protective suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian, talk to me, talk to me,'' Nestor said, pressing his
mask close to Gordon's face. A muffled voice replied, ``I can't
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to drag you out of here,'' Nestor said, and lugged
him toward the door. The specialist's suit hissed as his limp body
slid along the waxed floor.
</P>
<P>
   Back outside, Quinn and his medics and decontamination crews
were scrambling. A group of soldiers ran to the door and loaded
Gordon onto a stretcher. They began washing him at a mobile
decontamination site they had built, and soon were pulling him out
of his protective suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Paul A. Fanning, a National Guard member who wandered
through the exercise taking pictures, watched as the specialist
emerged from the suit, steam rising from his tattooed arms. His
peers rushed him into the medical tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we never have to do this for real,'' the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the unit, thoughts ran a wide range. Domenici, the
commander, said he was not satisfied. It was nearing midnight. The
evaluation exercise was only days away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll eat dinner,'' he said. ``And then let's do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The exercise ended at 7 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
