<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN0214-COX     02-13 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN0214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chilly Atlanta gives McCain warm welcome
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than 1,000 people greeted Sen. John McCain on
Sunday on his first visit to Atlanta in two months for a book
signing-turned-campaign rally that offered new evidence of the
Republican's appeal to Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's bus caravan pulled into the Peachtree Battle Shopping
Center and a raucous reception on a cold, wet afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Such a crowd at a book signing in Atlanta ranks with those of
hugely successful writers such as Anne Rice and J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of support surprised and delighted McCain and his
aides as they looked out from the bus window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to beat Al Gore like a drum,'' McCain said in brief
remarks before entering the Chapter 11 bookstore for a marathon
signing session of his best-selling memoir, ``Faith of My
Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   The store sold close to 1,000 copies of the book Sunday, said
Dale Glenn, a co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   There were self-described Reagan Democrats, Roosevelt Democrats,
lifelong Democrats, independents and even some Republicans in the
line that stretched from one end of the shopping center to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Some wore caps and jackets advertising a connection to the
military. One woman, Jean Marshall, polished the POW bracelet she
had worn in the late '60s and early '70s in honor of Air Force Lt.
Michael T. Burns, who was shot down over Vietnam on July 5, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's 5 1/2 years in a North Vietnamese prison is the main
topic of the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt certain he would know Michael, and he said he did,''
Marshall said. She said she was still undecided between McCain and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Some people had waited since early morning for a chance to shake
McCain's hand and get his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also attended a fund-raising reception at the Grand Hyatt
Hotel that was hosted by Lewis Jordan, a co-founder of ValuJet
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The $250-a-head event was closed to the media, but John Sours,
the campaign's Georgia chairman, said he was expecting at least 150
people.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatically different scene when McCain came to town
in early December. Then, he traveled in a single van, accompanied
by one reporter.
</P>
<P>
   That visit was cut short when he had to fly back to Washington
to vote in the Senate. Among the events canceled that day was the
book signing.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has made no decision about how much time and
money to spend in Georgia. Its primary is the same day, March 7, as
much bigger prizes in California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has an overwhelming organizational advantage in the state,
with Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) at the top of his campaign effort
here.
</P>
<P>
   But one attraction of Georgia to the McCain campaign is that
there is no voter registration by political party, meaning that all
registered voters can participate in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   There were many Democratic and independent voters in the lines
that stretched the length of the shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Coggin clutched McCain's book in one hand and a $10
check in the other. ``I wish it could be more,'' Coggin said as she
handed the check to a McCain campaign official.
</P>
<P>
   Coggin, 40, has worked in the campaigns of former Democratic
state Sen. Julian Bond and Reform Party candidate H. Ross Perot.
She echoed many people in the line when she said, ``His character
is what attracted me. There is no way that won't transfer over to
his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Glenn, a son of the store's owner, was, at 18, the youngest
delegate to the Democratic National Convention in 1992. He was
pledged to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Glenn said, ``I am still a big Bill Clinton
fan.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 25-year-old, a new lawyer, said he will cast his ballot
this year for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
