<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-990     02-13 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIERCE ETHNIC FIGHTING IN KOSOVO TOWN ENTANGLES PEACEKEEPING
TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Kosovo _ French troops killed an Albanian gunman
during fierce fighting in the streets of this bitterly divided town
Sunday in the most sustained clashes involving peacekeeping troops
since they arrived in Kosovo eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over a dozen people were wounded, including two French soldiers,
and 17 people were arrested by early Sunday evening after French
troops _ recently accused of not cracking down hard enough on
violence here _ moved aggressively to pin down the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Both Serbs and Albanians regard Mitrovica as the last
battlefield of the war for Kosovo and as such unfinished business.
Sunday, the international troops seemed to have been caught in the
middle of that battle.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire and explosions sounded over the northern part of the
town _ home to some 9,000 Serbs, but also to 1,500 Albanians _ for
some five hours, and smoke billowed from two burning houses.
French, Italian and British troops came under fire on different
occasions. British troops, deployed last week on the central bridge
that divides the town into north and south, exchanged fire with
snipers on the north side several times. By late Sunday afternoon,
the shooting had ceased and French troops had surrounded a house
and begun to negotiate for the men inside to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   A former commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army, who said in an
interview by telephone that he had been involved in the fighting,
said Serbs had attempted to attack an area of Albanians and that
fighters of the now-outlawed Albanian guerrilla force had fought
back to defend the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine Albanians were injured today, including one of our
soldiers,'' the former commander said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs have made the north of the city a bastion of Serb control
and refuge for thousands of people displaced from elsewhere in
Kosovo. Albanians, thousands of whom have still not been able to
return to their homes in the north, consider it the last place
still to be liberated from Serb persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides assert that the other wants to control Mitrovica
because Kosovo's most valuable natural assets _ iron ore and
precious metal mines _ are scattered in and around the town.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb community leader, Oliver Ivanovic, threw the blame for
the fighting on the Albanians. ``They are not satisfied. They're
looking for big trouble,'' he said. He expected further violence
through the night, despite a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew, he said.
``They will not stop. They will do something more.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently with the agreement of the French, he was posting men
on the tops of buildings throughout the Serb area to keep watch
overnight despite the curfew. They would be wearing yellow
reflecting armbands to show KFOR that they were unarmed, he said.
Dozens of tough-looking young men moved in and out of his office
shortly before the curfew began to collect the yellow armbands.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica has been rocked by violence for the last 10 days and
several hundred British, Belgian, Danish and German troops have
been sent as reinforcements to the French who are in command of the
area. The violence, both grenade attacks and shootings, has
centered on the northern side of the city.
</P>
<P>
   There have been injuries among both ethnic communities and
nearly 1,000 Albanians have been forced to flee their homes on the
north side to the Albanian-populated south. Then, on Saturday
evening, French troops surrounded and searched the Dolce Vita cafe,
the main hangout for hardline Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest fighting Sunday occurred in the so-called Bosnian
quarter, a dense warren of alley ways close to the river Ibar,
which is mostly populated by Albanians, but where some Serbs also
live. It is an area that Albanians have vowed to defend from what
they say are Serb efforts to purge it of Albanians, and which Serbs
say is a center of terrorists who attack Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's violence began with a grenade explosion near an
Albanian bakery around 7 a.m. in the Bosnian quarter on the north
side of the river. Five Albanians were wounded in the grenade
attack and brought to the Moroccan military hospital, said Col. Dr.
Ahmed Muden, chief of the hospital. Two of the wounded were treated
and allowed home, the other three were hospitalized. One, he said,
was in a serious condition. The wounded were all men, from ages 22
to 35, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was three hours later that shooting broke out across town.
Pistol shots were suddenly answered by automatic gunfire. Two
French soldiers were wounded, one in the stomach, and one in the
arm when a gunman opened fire on their position in the Bosnian
quarter. U.N. police described it as an unprovoked attack on the
soldiers, who were part of a static guard deployed to protect
Albanians in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Italian troops on a bridge nearby opened fire. French troops
immediately moved some 30 to 40 armored vehicles into the northern
part of Mitrovica across the bridges. The shooting escalated, and
British troops came under sniper fire from across the river at
their positions on the central bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Three Serbs were wounded during the day, including one who was
with French troops when they came under fire, and another, a
civilian, who was injured in his foot outside his apartment
building, Ivanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   An Albanian man was found in the street in a pool of blood in
the middle of the day. The man was in a coma when he was brought to
the Moroccan hospital and died shortly afterward, doctors said. A
statement from the NATO-led Kosovo peacekeeping force later said
the Albanian was a gunman who had been shot dead by French soldiers
who had come under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Three men were injured in exchanges of fire with peacekeeping
troops, one of them the dead Albanian, British Warrant Officer Mark
Cox, a spokesman for the peacekeepers, said Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Some 17 people had been arrested during the day, Cox said,
including the men surrounded in the house.  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As French troops pursued the gunmen who had apparently fired on
them, automatic gunfire and grenade explosions rang out over the
Bosnian quarter. French snipers appeared on the roof of a tall
apartment building overlooking the area and an observer helicopter
hovered at a distance. Nearby, the smoke of a burning house still
rose from the charred rafters.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, the shooting ceased and negotiations began.
``They are Albanians inside. It is not clear who they are or why
they are doing this,'' said French public affairs officer, Lt.
Charles-Philippe d'Orleans, watching the proceedings. French troops
with armored vehicles had cordoned off the street. ``We gave them a
sharp riposte with the gun mounted on the top,'' d'Orleans said.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of Serbs watching nearby were in no doubt. ``They are
terrorists. They are attacking us all the time. We cannot go on
living like this,'' said Branko Barovic, a man on crutches and a
known hardliner in the town.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the exodus of Albanians from the north side
continued, a human outpouring that started when four Albanians were
killed and several Serbs were injured in a night of violence Feb.
3. Sunday, one family escaped their house as it was set alight,
U.N. police said. Flora Zabrgja, 22, and her mother Kimete
Zabrigja, 57, were among those to flee under sniper fire after four
days hold up in their apartment, terrified their Serb neighbors
would attack them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they searched the Dolce Vita, the Serbs went crazy,''
Zabrgja said. Then, she said, French troops came and told them to
go. As they headed for the bridge, shots rang out. They took cover
in a troop carrier on the bridge for two hours, and then ran the
length of the bridge with British soldiers carrying their bags for
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
