<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-TRAINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSION FOLLOWS THE JONESES TO THE METS' TRAINING CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Same time, same joke, new spin.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, when the Mets right-hander Bobby Jones arrived at
Thomas J. White Stadium for spring training, his equipment was
thousands of miles away in Tucson, Ariz. The Louisville Slugger
manufacturer, whose gloves Jones uses, had sent his stuff to the
Colorado Rockies' training camp, where it waited in the locker of
the other Bobby Jones, a left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two Joneses are teammates on the Mets. Pitchers and
catchers don't officially report until Tuesday, but the first
confusion of the season has already taken place. When Bobby J.
Jones _ the seven-year Met _ showed up over the weekend, he found
gloves belonging to Bobby M. Jones in his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a messup from the staff here,'' the right-hander
said Sunday, laughing. ``They should know I'm not left-handed by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Only John Franco has been with the club longer than Jones, who
debuted for the Mets in 1993, when they lost 103 games. When they
finally reached the playoffs last season, Jones couldn't
contribute. After the Mets beat Cincinnati in the one-game playoff
to win the National League wild card, General Manager Steve
Phillips told Jones he would not be on the postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was disappointed; he had relieved three times in September
after missing nearly four months with shoulder trouble, and he felt
he could have helped. But Phillips had also assured Jones that the
bullpen assignment was only temporary, and now Jones is back in the
rotation on a team that shed four starters over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   There will be competition for the fifth spot _ Bobby M. Jones,
Bill Pulsipher, Glendon Rusch, Dennis Springer and Paul Wagner are
the candidates _ but Jones will be in the fourth, supporting Mike
Hampton, Al Leiter and Rick Reed. He has not started since last May
22, however, and believes nothing is a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come into spring thinking that you have to compete and you
have to win your job,'' said Jones, an All-Star in 1997, who will
make $5.25 million this year. ``There are some guys who are
penciled in right now. If I'm one of them, I don't know. I've been
told by Steve that they are looking for good things from me, and
that basically tells me I'm going to be in the starting rotation. I
go about it where I'm going to go out and prove myself this
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones left spring training last year feeling as strong as he
ever had, and he was 3-0 with a 3.09 earned run average in April.
But in May, something changed. His pitches had no life, and thus
had no movement. Every pitch had to be in thrown in the perfect
location. His fastball had dropped from 87 miles an hour to 80-82
mph, and he was experiencing shoulder tendinitis that he first
attributed to a simple dead-arm phase.
</P>
<P>
   But rest never improved the condition, and a magnetic resonance
imaging test revealed a small tendon tear. Jones spent the winter
getting therapy to strengthen his rotator cuff, and threw now and
then. After playing long toss Sunday with Bobby M. Jones, he said
he th's back to where he was before the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any pain when I throw, which I did before,''
Jones said. ``Every once in a while you may have a little ache, but
I think that's just part of the healing process. But no pain during
throwing, so that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs will stay positive, as long as Jones can help it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wanted to look at it and make sure it's healed, I
don't know if I would want to do that,'' he said. ``If I see it's
not completely healed, then there will be that doubt. Maybe if I
feel something later down the road, then I'll have it looked at.
But until I'm feeling discomfort or pain, I would just assume it's
healed and go as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   As normal as life can be, anyway, when your namesake plays the
same position for the same team. Jones _ whose nickname is
``Jonesey'' _ was hopeful Sunday morning that different nicknames
would help distinguish the pitchers. After throwing together, the
two Joneses went for a run around the complex. Bobby J. planned to
ask Bobby M. if he had a nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby M. Jones does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Jonesey,'' he said. ``I think that's what they call
everybody whose last name is Jones.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
