<HEADER>
A5733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CARNEGIE-MUSIC-REVIEW     02-13 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNEGIE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING THE SPIRITUAL CORE OF TWO SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms)  
By ALLAN KOZINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Philadelphia Orchestra, just past the midway
point in its season-long survey of the 20th-century orchestral
literature, brought Bartok's Third Piano Concerto and Henryk
Gorecki's Third Symphony to Carnegie Hall on the evening of Feb. 8
in a concert conducted by Wolfgang Sawallisch.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface the two scores would seem to be at odds in every
way: the Bartok, composed in 1945, draws much of its energy from
the complex and carefully balanced relationships between the
strands of its musical fabric and from the drive and determination
inherent in the composer's style. The Gorecki, a series of mournful
Lento movements (its subtitle is ``Symphony of Sorrowful Songs'')
from 1976, draws on the consonance and repetition of Minimalism and
creates the impression of a river moving slowly to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   What they have in common is a spiritual core, touched on
differently by each composer. Bartok was dying when he wrote his
Piano Concerto, and in its central movement, marked Adagio
religioso, there is choralelike writing that has a serenity
uncommon for Bartok and a section that evokes bird calls and that
edges toward the style of another of contemporary music's mystics,
Olivier Messiaen. The Gorecki work began as an Auschwitz memorial,
but in the nine years between his first ideas for the work and its
completion, its scope was expanded and it became a hypnotic
meditation on suffering of all kinds. Its texts, sung by a soprano,
are drawn from a 15th-century lamentation, a prayer inscribed on
the wall of a Nazi cell and a folk song about the death of a son.
</P>
<P>
   Yefim Bronfman, the soloist in the Bartok, found a workable
balance between the work's beauty and the occasional acidity that
gives it its spice. Hard driven though his account of the opening
Allegretto was, it stopped short of aggressiveness. Bronfman's
gentle rendering of the slow movement let its alternately elegant
and painterly forms of prayer come through with touching beauty,
and his nimble account of the finale suggested Bartok's attention
returning to the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   The Gorecki had a freakish success eight years ago, when David
Zinman's recording on Nonesuch sold 1.5 million copies. There is a
tendency in classical music circles to denigrate such success, but
in fairness, it is not as though Gorecki wrote it to pander to
popular tastes. By the time the Nonesuch recording was released, 16
years after the work was completed, there had already been at least
two previous recordings, and sections of the piece were used in a
French film, ``Police,'' all without a great deal of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what this symphony's success shows is that there is an
audience for works _ even rather dour ones _ that are both deeply
felt and easily assimilated. This one works better on disc than in
the concert hall, where its repetitions can be wearing. That said,
the subtle changes in dynamics and coloration and the glacial
interplay of weighty string lines often seemed to set up the
moments when Gorecki added a sudden dissonance.
</P>
<P>
   Elzbieta Szmytka brought a beautiful, focused and powerful tone
to the vocal sections. In both works Sawallisch and his players
produced a big, solid, polished sound, if one that was blander than
what the Philadelphia can produce at its best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
