<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-VIGIL14-COX     02-13 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-VIGIL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis' friend to surrender
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Joseph Sweeting, one of two suspects still at large in
stabbing deaths of two men in Atlanta, will turn himself in to law
enforcement officials today, his lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The other man, Reginald ``A.J.'' Oakley of Baltimore, had been
expected to surrender to authorities over the weekend, but as of
Sunday night had not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting, Oakley and Baltimore Ravens All-Pro linebacker Ray
Lewis, 24, are charged in the Jan. 31 slayings of Richard Lollar,
24, and Jacinth Baker, 21, both of Decatur, Ga. Lollar and Baker
were stabbed to death in a fight at an intersection in Buckhead,
Atlanta's entertainment district. The stabbings occured in the
early morning hours after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting, 35, of Miami, will plead not guilty to the charges,
according to his lawyers, John Bergendahl of Miami and Steve Sadow
of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting and Oakley are being sought by local police in Florida
and Maryland, as well as by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Police say Sweeting and Oakley were partying with Lewis
and several other people after the Super Bowl at Cobalt, a Buckhead
night club. The group left the club around 3:30 a.m. and soon
afterward, according to police, a fight broke out that involved
Lewis' group and Lollar and Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, through his lawyer, Ed Garland of Atlanta, has maintained
his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   However, police say Lewis deliberately misled them, withheld
information and removed evidence, hindering their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Under Georgia law, someone can be charged with murder even if
they do not actually kill a person if they are involved in the
commission of a felony that results in a death or cover up evidence
of a slaying.
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis sat in an 8-by-12 foot cell isolated from other
prisoners in the Fulton County Jail, Lewis' grandparents, Gillis
McKinney, his aunt, Gwen Miller and an uncle, the Rev. Clinton
Stancil, prayed for his release in the jail lobby. The vigil was
organized by the Rev. J. Richard Harris of West Palm Beach, Fla.,
who said he has known Lewis since he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Several professional athletes had been expected at the vigil,
including Tampa Bay Buccaneers defensive lineman Warren Sapp and
Dallas Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders, but bad weather delayed
their flights, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' supporters said police have the wrong man behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Lewis is not a murderer,'' Harris said. ``Ray Lewis is not
a villain, he's a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members maintain Lewis tried to break up the fight
outside Cobalt and did not kill anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly believe he is innocent,'' said Stancil, who lives in
Kansas City, Mo. ``It's frightening to us that in America ...
people still go to jail for trying to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A bond hearing for Lewis was scheduled for today. Among the
witnesses expected to appear on Lewis' behalf are Ravens owner Art
Modell and Ravens' defensive back Rod Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the hearing will be two-fold: Lewis is a good guy,
and he didn't kill anyone, said Don Samuels, one of Lewis' Atlanta
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't do it,'' Samuels said. ``That's one of the factors a
judge is supposed to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuels said the defense will ask that Lewis get a reasonable
bail and be allowed to train with the Ravens while he awaits trial.
</P>
<P>
   Other people to testify on Lewis' behalf include Lewis' high
school coach, his mother, grandmother and other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lollar's grandmother, Joyce Lollar, said she has sent a
statement asking that Lewis not get bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever killed my grandson should not have any freedom,'' she
said Sunday at her home in Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Joshua B. Good,
Alfred Charles, Janet Frankston, Doug Payne, Rick Badie, John
McCosh, Rhonda Cook, Andrea Jones and Don Fernandez contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
