<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-HIRING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE IN CLERGY LEAVES MORE U.S. PULPITS UNFILLED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ohio., Mich.)   (rk) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congregation B'nai Israel in Hattiesburg, Miss., has been
without a rabbi for more than three years. Every other week, a
student rabbi flies in from Cincinnati. At other times, congregants
lead Sabbath services, run the Sunday school and even conduct
funerals.
</P>
<P>
   It is not for lack of effort that the 110-year-old synagogue has
failed to attract a rabbi. It has listed its opening with the
placement office of Hebrew Union College, the Reform movement
seminary, ever since its rabbi left, and it usually sends a
representative to Cincinnati in the spring for on-campus
recruitment at the college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to interview even when no one signs up,'' said Steve
Doblin, president of B'nai Israel and dean of science and
technology at the University of Southern Mississippi. ``We have
always felt it is critical to our health and vitality, maybe even
to our existence, to have a full-time rabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   The temple's plight is not unusual. Not only are synagogues
across the spectrum of Judaism finding it increasingly difficult to
hire clergy, so too are Roman Catholic and Protestant churches. In
the Roman Catholic Church, according to the National Pastoral Life
Center, an independent organization in New York that assists local
parishes, the number of parish priests declined by 12 percent
between 1992 and 1997, and churches are increasingly relying on lay
people for ministries once largely done by priests and nuns.
</P>
<P>
   In the Episcopal Church, ``the situation is grave,'' said the
Rev. Hugh Magers, a member of the congregational ministries cluster
at the denomination's national headquarters in Manhattan. ``As best
as I can tell, we have under 300 members of the clergy out of
15,000 who were born after 1964,'' he said. ``Members of the
council on ministry development, deans of seminaries and a lot of
bishops are beginning to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Reform Judaism, about 200 out of 893 congregations around the
country lack a full-time rabbi. Many others need assistant rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The modern Orthodox wing of Judaism has the same problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply aren't enough rabbis,'' said Rabbi Steven
Dworken, executive vice president of the Rabbinical Council of
America. ``There are more jobs open now, due to the growth, thank
God, of the Orthodox community, and filling positions in smaller
communities can be extremely difficult. We see some shuls going
into their second or third year with no rabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the ranks of Jewish clergy began about five years
ago. Before then, there were more rabbis in the job market than
pulpits to fill. ``The issue of the glut was raised with the
college in 1993,'' said Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, president of
Hebrew Union College. ``As a result, recruitment was not emphasized
and was not considered an imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Though enrollment at the college has remained stable, the number
of congregations has grown. Fifteen years ago there were 764
synagogues belonging to the Union of American Hebrew Congregations;
today there are 895. So not only are there new pulpits to fill,
but, Zimmerman said, ``large congregations need more rabbis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now at least 60 congregations with more than 1,000
members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, rural areas have always had difficulty attracting
clergy, no matter the denomination. Now, urban congregations are
feeling the pinch and are learning that openings do not necessarily
draw the wide choice of candidates of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in major metropolitan areas, we are starting to hear from
bishops and diocesan deployment officers that they are having
difficulty,'' the Rev. James G. Wilson, executive director of the
church deployment office at the Episcopal Church Center, said.
``What used to be a problem for Wyoming and Montana is now a
problem for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Arnold I. Sher, director of placement for Hebrew Union
College and the Central Conference of American Rabbis, said: ``The
shortage is affecting the large congregations that get people's
attention. Where they used to get 30 applications, now they get
maybe nine or 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Matza, chairman of the search committee at Temple Emanuel
in Grand Rapids, Mich., which is seeking a replacement for its
retiring rabbi, was involved in a search in Chicago 10 years ago
and one in Dallas 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the searches I was involved with in Chicago and
Dallas, this is very frustrating,'' he said. ``We are encountering
a lack of viable candidates from whom to select. We have had one or
two people who have expressed an interest and are coming for an
interview, but we are also considering alternatives like rabbis
with less experience than we might want or going for some period
without a rabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the robust economy is being blamed, with many young
people who in the past might have been drawn to the ministry
attracted to more lucrative fields.
</P>
<P>
   When a consulting firm ``comes knocking on the door offering
$60,000 to someone right out of college, they say, `Do I really
want to go to five years of graduate school?''' said Rabbi Aaron
Panken, dean of the New York campus of Hebrew Union College. ``When
the economy goes down, people tend to focus more on spiritual
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Dworken of the Rabbinical Council of America, and former
director of rabbinic services at Yeshivha University, said: ``We
have done too good a job educating our children and giving them
banking, legal, business and medical opportunities. Years ago, many
fellows became rabbis because they had no other choices.''
</P>
<P>
   As a professor of religion at Columbia University for 21 years,
Peter Awn said that he had seen only four religion majors at
Columbia pursue careers in the clergy. In his view, the declining
appeal of a life in ministry is more a result of rejection of
authoritarianism than of the lure of more lucrative jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People who might once have gone into the clergy as an avenue
toward social change now see it as confining rather than
liberating,'' Awn, a former Jesuit priest, said. ``A profound
suspicion of political and religious institutions has taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   But among those who do seek jobs in the clergy, quality of life
plays an increasingly decisive role as they question the long hours
and unrelenting demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, 95 percent of Hebrew Union College graduates went
directly to congregations; today that is down to 75 percent,'' Sher
said. ``Now jobs in academia, federations, Jewish centers, day
schools and hospitals are becoming more challenging and
prestigious, and their schedules are more controllable. Today
rabbis are looking for things they never sought in the past like a
strong Jewish community, a place with Jewish day schools for the
children. That never crossed my mind when I was raising my four
children.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the shortage of rabbis, leaders of major Reform
Jewish organizations have formed a task force to produce new
approaches to attracting rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to devise creative new ways to communicate what a
wonderful life is out there for people in the rabbinate,'' said
Panken of Hebrew Union College. Among the things being studied are
ways to reduce the time demands on rabbis and increase the
responsibilities of the members of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Though some experts think the decline in clergy is cyclical,
others think that failure to stem the tide would have serious
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we somehow increase the number of those choosing
religious professional life, ultimately this will be a disaster for
organized religious life,'' Zimmerman said. ``The pivotal people
who touch and embrace human beings at the most significant and
challenging moments of life will be lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
