<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-KORS14-COX     02-13 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-KORS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kors' line evokes images of speakeasys,
 &HT;    art deco scenes and `Casablanca'
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Michael Kors likes a Gershwin tune _ how
about you?
</P>
<P>
   To the strains of ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' a melody evocative of
Manhattan glamour _ thanks primarily to Woody Allen _ a
well-groomed cast of male and female models at Kors' fall 2000
collection show strolled down the runway sporting the snazziest,
jazziest and dressiest clothes of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the mall as inspiration. Fall looks from Kors are more
evocative of a moll.
</P>
<P>
   This designer's rap isn't ``gangsta'' or ``Penthouse'' pet.
Kors' looks summoned up pinstripe-suited, fedora-wearing gangsters
from the 1930s, Ingrid Bergman in ``Casablanca,'' Ivy Leaguers on a
crisp Saturday afternoon at the game, and lithe and sexy beauties
sipping gin at a speakeasy or in an art deco apartment on the 90th
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Themes aside, Kors' collection was a ``Blass from the past.''
Like the now-retired Bill Blass, who was always a pal to his gals,
this at-his-peak designer is offering women the elements to create
a put-together look that has an unabashed upper-class demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Classic and fancy tailored tweed or pin-striped flannel suits,
trimmed with feathers or fur, offered something fresh and new
consideringKors is best known for working in a luxuriously rendered
dressed-down context. Though simple in form, pieces clad in
geometric beading patterned after the facade and other
architectural details of the 1929 Chrysler Building lent some
fabulous flash to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   His evening wear, which hasn't been a strong part of his
collections in the past, was slinkily successful for the upcoming
fall. The silhouettes are still lean, but distinctly softer.
</P>
<P>
   With his men's collection, Kors has definitely moved forward and
back at the same time. Instead of offering simple luxed-up-casual
jeans and sweaters, the designer has moved into amore bespoke and
dandified mode, with gentlemanly garb that served as the perfect
escort to his ladylike styles for women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
