<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-MAIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods erases big deficit, but Mickelson ends his streak
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ The Streak is over. Tiger Woods lost a golf
tournament. Byron Nelson's 11 in a row remain the standard.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Woods' six straight, having been assembled since
August 1999, become just slightly better than, well, a half-Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' streak ended Sunday at Torrey Pines Golf Course in the
Buick Invitational when San Diego native Phil Mickelson righted
himself after an early period of self-destruction that bordered on
the unfathomable. After squandering a seven-shot lead with 12 holes
to play, Mickelson rallied on the back nine for a 2-under-par 70
and finished at 18-under 270 to win by four shots.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Woods was right there until the last hour of the
tournament _ amazing because his swing had pretty much deserted him
and he was struggling just to hit fairways. Relying almost totally
on his short game for survival, Woods still shot a 68 and tied for
second at 274, along with Japan's Shigeki Maruyama.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III eagled the 72nd hole for a 70 to
finish fourth, five shots behind Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, to even be under par as (bad) as I was
hitting it, was kind of a miracle,'' Woods said. ``I just wasn't
hitting it good enough to give myself a viable chance down the
stretch, and it finally caught up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mickelson double-bogeyed the 7th and 11th and Woods
birdied the par-5 13th, the two were tied at 15-under. But
Mickelson, who had not won since the rain-delayed Pebble Beach
tournament in August 1998 and has been battling the Sunday swoons,
finally got his act together with birdies at 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   The ``big turnaround'' for Mickelson was a laid-off 9-iron from
116 yards at the 13th to two feet, which he eased in for a birdie,
returning to 16-under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly was not going to just hand it to him,'' said
Mickelson, ``even though it looked like I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods carried a sheepish look through his media center
interview, knowing he had been faking it at crunch time with his
swing out of sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to kind of hang in there and hang in there, chip and putt
and just grind away at it and just give myself a chance _ I was
very proud of myself for that,'' said Woods, who still managed to
go 45 straight holes without a bogey until one Sunday at the 14th.
``But to win a tournament hitting it like that is not an easy thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What did the end of the streak mean to Woods?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means I came in second,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What did winning six in a row mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Second all-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Woods said it was not the case, he seemed almost
relieved that the streak had ended, guaranteeing that his
appearance this week at the Nissan Open in Los Angeles will become
less of a media circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very draining,'' he said. ``Having to do a lot of press
conferences every day, and then the fans, the constant bombardment.
It takes its toll on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods deemed it possible that someone else could manage a
similar streak. Heck, for all the golf world knows, Woods himself
could win this week at Riviera and start another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just all depends if someone gets hot like I did,'' Tiger
said. ``If someone plays well and gives themselves enough
opportunities. Either you're going to win them outright yourself or
you might need a little help, but I think it can be done again.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, the frustrations with his swing, which had not been
sharp all week, were typified during conversations toward the end
of the round with caddie and former high school teammate, Bryon
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was more funny than anything else,'' Woods said.
``He said, `Would you just hit a fairway?'. . I said, `I'm
trying.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
