<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRADLEY CAMPAIGN, CONTEST IS THREE-WAY RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ In a speech to California Democrats on
Saturday, former Sen. Bill Bradley had just reached the part where
he usually contrasts himself with Vice President Al Gore, when he
swerved into new territory and began drawing distinctions between
himself and a Republican, Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain, he's moving in the polls, even getting some
Democratic support,'' Bradley said. ``Why do you think that is?''
And then he proceeded to tick off the reasons good Democrats should
not like McCain, from his opposition to abortion and gun control to
his support for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's quick pivot from Gore to McCain showed that he is
suddenly fighting a two-front war: against Gore for core Democratic
voters and against McCain for the hearts and minds of independents
who are important in states like California and Washington that
vote on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, polls have shown that Bradley and
McCain perform well among independent voters, who seem attracted to
their insurgent messages. Both claim to be outsiders fighting the
establishment, both staunchly advocate getting big money out of
politics, and both cast themselves as plain-spoken alternatives to
slick, poll-driven front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the campaign, Bradley's aides argued that there were
enough independent voters for both candidates. No longer. Since
McCain scored a 19-point victory over Gov. George W. Bush in New
Hampshire, largely on the strength of independent voters, Bradley's
advisers have conceded that McCain's rising popularity could draw
crucial independent votes away from Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   That will particularly be a problem in Washington state, where
Bradley has established a grass-roots organization and won the
support of many local officials, including Mayor Paul Schell of
Seattle. The state is one of several that Bradley's aides say they
can, and perhaps need to, win on March 7, when 30 percent of the
party's presidential delegates will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has a unique voting system, known as a blanket
primary, where Democrats, Republicans and independents will be
allowed to vote for candidates from any party on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates will actually be selected in closed party caucuses on
March 7, where Gore will be favored because of his broad support
among unions and party activists. But Washington Democrats say
results from the blanket primary will strongly influence public
perception of the race, and therefore affect the caucus votes.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, some of Bradley's top supporters in Washington
have begun using their public appearances to urge independents to
stand by Bradley and not join the McCain bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Hampshire, a lot of people were saying they couldn't
decide between McCain and Bradley,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott,
D-Seattle, who has endorsed Bradley. ``But they are not the same,
and in fact on most issues you couldn't have two people who are
further apart.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott and other supporters of Bradley said they are also
concerned that their candidate is not doing enough to show the
differences between himself and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us have told him, `You've got to differentiate
yourself from him,''' McDermott said. ``John McCain is like a
vacuum cleaner. His surge shows there is a powerful desire under
the surface for change. Bradley's got to show himself as offering a
kind of change that is different from John McCain's kind of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's press secretary, argued that there is no
clear evidence that McCain will hurt Bradley among unaffiliated
voters or independent-minded Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that McCain could pose a problem in states
with open primaries and said the Bradley campaign would
increasingly try to show differences between the two insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters who care about reform need to understand that reform
with John McCain means a pro-gun, pro-life, anti-environmental
agenda,'' Hauser said. ``Reform with Bill Bradley means the
opposite.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In most states independent voters will not be a factor, because
only registered Democrats will be allowed to vote in the Democratic
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But California, like Washington, has an open primary where
Democrats, Republicans and unaffiliated voters can vote for any
candidate. And while delegates will be allocated based solely on
votes from registered Democrats, the overall popular vote will be
viewed as an important indicator of Bradley's strength among the
general electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of voters in New Hampshire, where independents were
allowed to vote in either the Republican or the Democratic primary,
showed that McCain won the most independent votes. But Bradley did
better among independents than Gore, whose base of support is among
core Democratic voters, including union members and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has also posed a public relations problem for Bradley.
With his sudden surge, McCain has drawn media attention away from
Bradley, who has been sinking in opinion polls as steadily as
McCain has been rising.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's advisers say that voters in California, Washington
and other states that vote on March 7 have not begun to focus on
the race yet, and that McCain's domination of the news will become
a problem only if he wins the South Carolina primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got three weeks, and that's an eternity in
politics,'' Hauser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
