<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT MONEY SETS OFF RIVALS' HARD WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (Originally skedded BUSH) 
 (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After a tense stretch of harsh attacks and
paradoxical resolutions to run their campaigns on positive tracks,
Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain used their appearances on
television news programs Sunday to take renewed aim at each other.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in an interview on CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' assailed
Bush for opposing his proposed legislation to ban the largely
unregulated donations to political parties known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it should remain legal, I guess, for a
Chinese-army-owned corporation to give unlimited amounts of money
to an American political campaign,'' McCain said, referring to one
of the scandals of the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign quickly issued a news release noting that such
contributions were already illegal and that Bush supported bans on
soft money from corporations and labor unions but deemed other
aspects of McCain's plan flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, also questioned how
McCain's salvo squared with his vow late last week to stop running
negative commercials and keep his campaign on a higher plane.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an interview on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' dismissed
McCain's vow as a transparent ploy that did not excuse the Arizona
senator for running two television commercials that likened Bush's
trustworthiness to President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about as low as you can get,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   And so the final week leading to South Carolina's Republican
primary on Feb. 19 began with echoes of the recriminations and
grievances that preceded it, a signal of how much is at stake for
each candidate and how tight the contest seems.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his renunciation of negative advertising covered the
rest of the primaries, not just the South Carolina race. His
comments about Bush and soft money came after he was asked why,
despite his stated opposition to public financing of campaigns, he
had voted for it ``four or five times in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted against it on 10 or 11 times,'' McCain responded, then
alluded to his campaign's contention that the conflicting examples
involved procedural votes that he cast to keep an otherwise
desirable piece of legislation alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to allow the perfect to be the enemy of the
good,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleischer, in the news release and in a telephone interview,
said the votes illustrated a pattern of McCain's actions falling
short of his words.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's recent visit to Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C.,
a conservative Christian institution that bans interracial dating,
came up in both interviews.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that he had no plans to make such an appearance, and
that if he did, ``I would condemn openly the policies of Bob
Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had expressed his disapproval of the dating policy at a
news conference at a nearby hotel after his appearance at the
university but had not addressed the topic in his remarks to about
6,000 students and faculty members there.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Bush said he had no second thoughts about going there,
even though Bob Jones III, who sat beside Bush at the university,
once branded Bush's father a ``devil'' for proposing that the
school lose its tax-exempt status because of its discriminatory
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not agree with this notion that somehow, if I go to try
to attract votes and to lead people toward a better tomorrow,
somehow I get subscribed to _ some doctrine gets subscribed to
me,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, a Bush supporter, also addressed the subject on
``Face the Nation,'' saying, ``I think George Bush wants to reach
out and touch every segment of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically needs these people to win,'' Robertson added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his support for the death penalty had not been shaken
by the fact that Gov. George Ryan of Illinois, a Republican ally,
had placed a moratorium on executions because more than a dozen
people sent to death row since 1977 had been exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the South Carolina primary, Bush expressed
concern that Democrats in the state, who are allowed to vote in the
contest, were mobilizing to support McCain, because they felt he
would be easier for the Democratic nominee to defeat in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush remained in Texas on Sunday, McCain campaigned in
South Carolina and Georgia. At a book store in Atlanta, more than
1,000 people waited in line so he could sign copies of his
autobiography, ``Faith of My Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of them also swarmed onto McCain's bus so they could take
pictures of the spot where he typically sat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 2214EST &QL; 
