<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ALL-STARS-NYT &LR;      02-13 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ALL-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FUN SHOW, STARRING O'NEAL AND DUNCAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ They trotted out a younger generation Sunday,
an athletically incomparable cast of skittering point guards from
Philadelphia and floating small forwards from Toronto. Midair
improvisation and savvy scorers were no longer at a premium, but
the norm. It made you wonder: Where have all the great big men
gone?
</P>
<P>
   West, definitely the West.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Tim Duncan proved that reports of the
center position's demise in the NBA are greatly exaggerated. They
did their own Twin Towers thing at the New Arena here, leading the
Western Conference to a 137-126 victory over the Eastern Conference
in the 49th All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was awesome, parlaying monster blocked shots and powerful
dunks into a 22-point, nine-rebound day. His front-line companion,
Duncan, ended with 24 points and 14 rebounds as the West simply
swatted away those pesky fleas from the East like Allen Iverson and
Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Always perceived as too young, too overhyped and too consumed
with his entertainment pursuits to realize his potential, O'Neal
proved his merits as the biggest player in the league's midseason
extravaganza. Duncan merely added to his growing list of
achievements, which included an NBA championship ring last season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who would take home the most valuable player trophy after
the two held the award up high at center court, O'Neal smiled and
said: ``He's got on one of those rings. I'm taking this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett was in the running, too, finishing with 24 points,
10 rebounds and five assists on a frontline the East could simply
not match. Iverson was up to the challenge, scoring 26 points on
10-of-18 shooting. Carter finished with 12 points and excited the
crowd with his acrobatic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the West finally took control of a close game in the fourth
quarter and put it away with about three minutes left, outscoring
the East by 39-28 in the final quarter. The combined 39 turnovers
did not make for great viewing. And neither the local flavor point
guard tandem of Gary Payton and Jason Kidd emerged enough to
capture the sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the big fellas, the 7-foot-1-inch O'Neal and 7-foot Duncan,
tried as best they could to make up for the lack of genuine drama.
O'Neal finished with three blocked shots, while Duncan changed the
trajectory of about 10. The dunks were expected. But using jump
hooks and medium-range jump shots to make most of their points
offensively, they were too much for Alonzo Mourning or even Dikembe
Mutombo to handle.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neal was not wowing the crowd with his power, he had fun
with the fans. Going coast-to-coast with the basketball at one
juncture in the first half, he softly put up a finger roll instead
of trying to take down the backboard support with a thunderous
slam.
</P>
<P>
   Honors for the most scintillating play went to Iverson and
Carter, who teamed up for a pretty sequence in the first quarter.
Carter was standing on the left baseline, double-teamed, when he
spotted Iverson on the right side. Carter whipped a no-look,
behind-the-back pass, and Duncan left him and went to stop Iverson,
a summit meeting of the game's most exciting diminutive player and
its most accomplished big man. Iverson hung in the air, drew the
foul and hit a sweet over-the-shoulder layup with his back to the
basket, bringing the crowd to its feet. Beating Duncan twice on the
same play was quite an accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson and Carter had combined on another play moments earlier,
when Iverson lofted an alley-oop pass along the right baseline that
Carter caught _ after he beat his defender back-door _ and
deposited for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the first half, Carter, the new slam-dunk
champion whom one league official said ``saved'' a monotonous
All-Star Saturday with his feats above the rim, took off from the
left baseline and slithered alongside the rim until releasing a
reverse layup on the right hand side.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about dynamic duos and NBC promos _ Kobe and
Shaq, Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell, Jason Williams and Chris
Webber _ nothing looked more potent this weekend than Iverson and
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Bryant was spectacular. He always is. With three minutes
left in the game, he literally caught an Iverson layup attempt in
midair. On the other end moments later, Jason Kidd, the homegrown
star from Oakland Hills, lofted a ridiculously high alley-oop pass
that no human had any business laying a finger on, much less
catching. At its apex, Bryant somehow caught that basketball with
his right arm cocked back as far as it would go. He then slammed
the ball hard, a continuous ``ooooohhhhh!'' ushering it through the
rim. Youth had been served again.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Weekend was about the future more than the past. The
game was telecast to more than 240 countries in 44 different
languages. For the first time, several players and both coaches
wore microphones, their comments edited for public consumption
during the telecast. For the first time, NBC used a separate set of
announcers for a high-definition television transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the 2000 class of All-Stars is 28.3. Standbys
like Karl Malone and John Stockton played only three minutes apiece
in the first half, and David Robinson played only seven. But there
was a poignant tribute to the past.
</P>
<P>
   With 6 minutes 50 seconds left in the game, the owner of the
Golden State Warriors, Chris Cohan, handed over the All-Star mantle
to next year's host, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A video montage of Michael Jordan's career played out on the
Jumbotron above the arena, as the applause grew louder and more
intense with each highlight from Jordan's career. Jordan, now the
Wizards' head of basketball operations, received a standing ovation
as he walked to center court.
</P>
<P>
   Except for his hiatus as a minor-league baseball player, it was
the first All-Star Game Jordan had not played since 1985, the year
a precocious youngster from North Carolina was frozen out by his
elders. In many ways, with all the errant alley-oop passes off the
backboard and the lack of genuine theater throughout, it was like
inserting a saucy scene in a lackluster movie.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for that one moment, the game was in Michael's hands again.
And neither poor TV ratings nor empty seats could take away the
feeling that somehow, some way, everything was going to be all
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
