<SLUG> BC-SC-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
 
BUSH AND McCAIN: MIRROR IMAGES OF EACH OTHER 
 (With REPUBS) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ For weeks, Gov. George W. Bush's aides mocked
Sen. John McCain's campaign bus, ``The Straight Talk Express,''
deriding it as ``The Double-Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, the Bush campaign has christened its own bus that roams
through this state ``The Victory Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the look-alike vehicles, it is increasingly tough to tell
the two Republican presidential candidates apart in this last,
frantic stretch before the South Carolina primary on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush and McCain find themselves in an unexpectedly
competitive duel to distinguish themselves, the more their battle
escalates and the more the two are looking and behaving alike on
everything from their campaign trappings to the heart of their
oratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next, he'll be standing in the desert next to a cactus wearing
a T-shirt saying, `I'm from Arizona!''' said Mike Murphy, a senior
strategist for McCain. ``People want the real McCain, not a guy
wearing a McCain costume that doesn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman, scoffed at the remark, saying,
``It's hard to copy someone who doesn't stay in one place long
enough to be copied.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, one senior Bush adviser said that after the governor's
defeat in New Hampshire, there were discussions about making Bush
``a pure carbon copy'' of McCain as a way to win over the
independent voters that have flooded to the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   While the campaign did not go that far, there has been something
of a role reversal in how the two candidates and their advisers
present themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It is reminiscent of Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley last year. After polls showed Bradley surging in New
Hampshire, Gore adopted the posture of the underdog. As his
campaign aides traded recriminations, the vice president shed his
tie and jacket and left no doubt that he would do whatever it took
to win.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Bradley behaved like the confident,
above-the-fray incumbent. And the Bradley camp was credited for its
political nimbleness. (That, of course, now seems like ancient
history.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is McCain strategists who are being called geniuses. And
the recriminations are among Bush loyalists who insist that they
had pressed long and hard to remedy the campaign's ills _ but no
one ever listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing now is the real George Bush coming out, the
man that was so popular and is so popular as a governor,'' said
Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J. ``I've been saying that for weeks to the
campaign: They weren't projecting the real George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps since he is still drowning in resources and
endorsements, Bush has not felt compelled to go as far as Gore and
declare himself the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   But at a town meeting on Friday at the College of Charleston
here, Bush sounded humbled. ``I'm here at this great institution to
ask for your vote,'' he said. ``I thank you for coming, and I'm
asking for your vote.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it was McCain, at a packed town meeting a few
nights earlier outside the Stratford High School in Goose Creek, on
the outskirts of Charleston, who sounded newly confident,
declaring, ``My dear friends, tonight, with this kind of reception,
this kind of turnout, I am for the first time convinced that I will
win this primary in South Carolina!''
</P>
<P>
   As happened with Bradley's advisers last year, McCain is
behaving a little more like a front-runner. He and his aides have
shown flashes of a fresh confidence, bordering on arrogance, that
was once the province of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Before New Hampshire, McCain liked to offer himself as ``the
overwhelming underdog'' who faced stiff odds getting the
nomination. McCain has scrapped that line from his standard speech.
</P>
<P>
   McCain displayed another sign of confidence during one of his
marathon chat sessions with reporters aboard his campaign bus this
week. He did not shy away from talking about possible members of a
McCain cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two candidates, the more obvious transformation has been
in Bush, who has refashioned himself in the McCain mold (albeit
without the cactus). He appropriated McCain's anti-establishment
mantle. He put himself forward as a ``reformer with results'' and
began emphasizing the need to save Social Security and to pay down
the debt. He loosened his stump style, began fielding more
questions from voters (his clipped, five-word answers have been
replaced by sometimes long monologues) and shed the battery of
elected officials that would flank him at public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   This evolution was on display at the two events here this week,
where the candidates seemed like they had graduated from the same
political finishing school.
</P>
<P>
   Each bounced about the stage with a microphone, eagerly fielding
questions from a jammed-to-the-rafters crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Each pronounced himself the genuine reformer in the race and an
early advocate of overhauling the campaign finance system. Each
stood for so many questions that some people grew impatient and
left. And each eagerly ventured into the audience, shaking hands
and scribbling autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's remake, he and his advisers still seem confident
that they will win the nomination. They are just less obvious.
</P>
<P>
   A day or two before the New Hampshire primary, Karl Rove, Bush's
chief strategist, happily told reporters that the governor had
turned things around and would emerge victorious.
</P>
<P>
   Rove has learned his lesson. Asked about prospects in South
Carolina, he said Saturday: ``My job is to remain scared. And we're
going to run hard, hard, hard through the balance of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, it is the McCain camp's turn to gloat. Asked
whether the Bush bus was a rip-off of the McCain concept, Dan
Schnur, McCain's communications director, said, `` `Straight Talk
Two' might have been a little too obvious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
