<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-PHONEBANK-POLITICS-1S     02-13 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONEBANK-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMPAIGN'S POLLING BECOMES ISSUE IN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Inserts new graf beginning ``A copy ...'' Inserts 2 new grafs
beginning ``Opinsky described ...'') 
(lb) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nearly 1,000 miles from South Carolina and the bitter
political war between George W. Bush and John McCain, one flank of
the war is being fought from a four-story office building in the
northern suburbs of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the top floor, inside the offices of a company called
Voter Consumer Research, a few dozen people, from college students
to grandmothers, spent two days last week calling prospective
voters in South Carolina to ask them carefully scripted questions.
They began innocuously enough: Will you participate in the
Republican primary? How much attention have you paid to the GOP
race? Are things better or worse in the country?
</P>
<P>
   But the questions quickly shifted to McCain, and the tone became
less innocuous: In the guise of introducing questions, the callers
stated that McCain's tax plan does not cut rates for most people,
that he had been reprimanded by the Senate Ethics Committee and
that his campaign finance proposals would give labor unions and the
media more influence in deciding elections.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of poll is this? One written by the Bush campaign. The
people conducting it were not starry-eyed campaign volunteers but
were paid by the hour, not much more than minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly nasty primary in which each candidate has
blamed the other for the nastiness, the usually obscure role of
telephone canvassing and polling has unexpectedly become a central
issue as hundreds of thousands of calls pour down on voters in
South Carolina. McCain has complained that Bush and his supporters
are conducting a thinly disguised telephone smear campaign, a
charge the Texas governor vehemently denies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has accused the Bush polling operation of spreading
negative information about McCain, rather than truly trying to
survey South Carolina voters. Such polling _ in which pollsters
give the impression that they are conducting a real poll, when they
are actually posing questions that spread doubts about the opponent
_ is known as ``push polling.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegation has put Bush on the defensive. ``It is just
ridiculous, it is unbelievable, this whole kind of thing about, you
know, Bush is push-polling, and we're not,'' Bush told host Tim
Russert on Sunday on `Meet the Press.' ``We're the one campaign,
Tim, that has said, `You're welcome to look at any phone script
that we pay for.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman, said McCain and others had
mistakenly confused the Bush campaign's use of ``advocacy calling''
_ designed to drum up support _ with its polling. Fleischer said
the campaign had made 200,000 advocacy calls into South Carolina,
in which callers read a script essentially blaming the negative
tenor of the race on McCain, and then ask if the respondent would
vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the McCain questioning in South Carolina, conducted
by a firm called Public Opinion Strategies, appears designed to
gauge support for the Republican contenders, and to determine which
issues resonate with voters, and whether they regard themselves as
conservative or liberal.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the questionnaire was provided by the McCain
organization and it does not include any questions or comments that
attack Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, several people at McCain rallies have told
stories of telephone calls that they said distorted McCain's record
and his personal history.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became public last week when a woman at a McCain rally
said her teen-age son answered the phone and heard McCain called a
liar, a cheat and a fraud. Then Marsha White, the wife of the mayor
of Greenville, a McCain supporter, said she had received a similar
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a couple of hundred calls in our office for
people who say they've gotten these calls,'' said McCain's
spokesman, Howard Opinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleischer said no such calls had been made by the Bush
campaign. To prove his point, on Sunday he released the script from
the poll conducted by Voter Consumer Research, the group that is
working from the Houston office building.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer emphasized that this script was different from the
massive advocacy calls. He conceded that the wording seemed loaded
in several questions, but he said the scope of the survey was
limited to 300 respondents.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said that unlike push polling, which targets thousands
of people, the Voter Consumer Research survey was specifically
designed to determine which issues were resonating with voters in
South Carolina. He said the campaign might use its findings to
create television commercials. These, presumably, would be aimed at
whatever those surveyed mentioned as McCain's weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surveys gather research,'' Fleischer said, noting that the
small size of the survey would preclude it from influencing many
voters. ``Surveys are meant to figure out what people are
thinking.'' He added, ``Push polls are taken with hundreds of
thousands of people, or tens of thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Frankovic, the director of surveys for CBS News,
reviewed the questions from the Bush campaign survey over the
telephone, and though she did not know if the assertions made about
McCain were true, she described the survey as ``fairly common'' and
``not unusual.'' She said political campaigns use partisan polling
to test attack lines much the same way that marketers poll people
to try out new slogans for products.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast to the long, detailed questions, she said push polls
are usually short and punchy in order to reach as many people as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky described the wording of several questions in the Bush
survey as inaccurate. He said McCain's tax plan provides cuts for
people in every income bracket, and he said the senator was never
reprimanded by the Senate Ethics Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said the questions are accurate. He also said some
Bush supporters have received push-poll phone calls about the Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Michael W. Traugott, president of the American Association for
Public Opinion Research, an organization of commercial, political
and academic pollsters, said that push polling is designed to
accomplish one of two things: to either convince people to change
from one candidate to another, or suppress an opponent's vote by
tarnishing his reputation in the eyes of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are deleterious and invidious effects to this,'' said
Traugott, who also teaches at the University of Michigan. ``This is
an unpleasant experience for most citizens, and we think it
increases their cynicism about politics and politicians.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for the type of calls made by the Bush campaign, Traugott
said, ``There's a very thin line between advocacy calling, where
you have people calling around to promote your candidacy, as
opposed to negative-persuasion telephoning, which is designed to
move you away from another candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   One unknown quantity in evaluating the use of polls is that a
number of calls are being made on behalf of candidates by
organizations other than the two campaigns. Published reports have
suggested that groups such as the National Right to Life, as well
as pro-tobacco organizations, are planning to make calls in South
Carolina on behalf of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he does not know what other organizations are
doing, and he has promised to fire anyone from his campaign if they
are involved in push polling.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston it is almost impossible to detect that the bland
brick building not far from a shopping center is actually a nerve
center in the presidential race. Bush first hired Voter Consumer
Research during his gubernatorial race, and the company now
operates phone banks north of the city. Some of its customers are
companies interested in testing opinions.
</P>
<P>
   But one employee said that political races are dominating
business now, particularly the South Carolina primary. Inside,
employees sit in front of computer screens, earning an hourly rate
to ask the same questions over and over again. One woman said the
average rate is $6 an hour. According to employees, every
conversation is monitored electronically to ensure that callers do
not stray from the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, according to one employee, supervisors warned the
staff against speaking to reporters. One woman said that McCain is
not the only object of polling. She said she had spent time asking
questions of voters around the nation about Vice President Al Gore.
One of the questions, she said, was about opinions on Gore's now
retracted claim that he invented the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The woman laughed and described the process as ``mudslinging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
