<DOCNO> NYT20000213.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-13 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GORE-780&AMP;ADD-NYT     02-13 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GORE-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TRIES TO SOOTHE CONCERNS OF SHARPTON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to solidify his support among black New
Yorkers, Vice President Al Gore met Sunday for the first time with
the Rev. Al Sharpton and received the endorsement of the Rev. Floyd
Flake, a former congressman and now the pastor of a prominent black
church in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The two sessions began a week-long drive by the vice president
to highlight his support among blacks, which is derived in large
part from his association with President Clinton. And they are
signs of an accelerated strategy from a campaign increasingly
confident that the Democratic presidential nomination is within
Gore's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sessions differed markedly in style, reflecting
caution on Gore's part after his buzz-saw encounter with New York's
ethnic politics in his failed 1988 presidential bid. He was open
and voluble with Flake, but met with Sharpton in private.
</P>
<P>
   A buoyant Gore, with microphone in hand and a choir behind him,
addressed hundreds of congregants at Flake's church, the Allen AME
church. He referred to the Scripture and raced up and down the
aisles asking congregants how many years they had been married and
how many grandchildren they had.
</P>
<P>
   Then he heard these surprising words from the pastor himself:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do endorsements from across the pulpit because I never
know who's out there watching the types of laws that govern
separation of church and state,'' Flake said, draped in a flowing,
gold-embroidered white robe and standing next to the blue-suited
Gore. ``But I will say to you this morning, and you read it well:
This should be the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a week before, Flake had been host to Gore's sole rival,
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, and given him a warm
welcome but no endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Flake's embrace of Gore was significant because of the influence
of Flake and his church within the black middle class. Flake joins
many of New York's other black leaders, including Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., and state comptroller Carl McCall, in backing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But not on that list of endorsees, at least so far, is Sharpton.
Some of Gore's top staff were not even aware of the meeting, while
others, including Donna Brazile, Gore's campaign manager, were
arranging it and then attended the session, which lasted about an
hour and took place at the East Side apartment of Karenna Gore
Schiff, Gore's oldest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The press corps that normally follows Gore were told by aides
that the meeting with Sharpton was not happening and that his visit
to his daughter's apartment was strictly personal.
</P>
<P>
   While Sharpton said in an interview afterward that he had not
yet decided whom he might endorse, he said the discussion with the
vice president had been ``extremely positive'' and that the meeting
``included a frank and honest discussion of the concerns of the
people in the areas that we come from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we don't agree on everything, he showed a willingness
to talk and a willingness to listen,'' Sharpton said. ``I was
impressed with a lot of what he had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton has been urged by supporters of both candidates to make
an endorsement. He initially considered supporting Bradley, but
came under pressure from political leaders like the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, who urged him to endorse the vice president (although
Jackson has yet to make an endorsement).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's meeting followed some tension between Sharpton and the
Gore campaign. A week ago, Sharpton complained that he had
perceived indifference from the vice president's campaign on racial
issues. And he said Gore needed to make amends with blacks in New
York over his 1988 presidential campaign. That year, Gore was
competing against Jackson, among others, and during the New York
primary Gore's ally, Mayor Ed Koch, was engaged in an ugly public
feud with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said that the campaign wanted to acknowledge
Sharpton's influence as a political leader but hesitated to fully
legitimize him. Gore fears getting entangled in New York's local
political cross-currents, and did not ask Sharpton for his
endorsement. Nor did Sharpton offer it.
</P>
<P>
   But the two discussed several matters concerning economic
development in heavily black areas, including access to media
ownership, according to Gore aides.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton did ask Gore to hold a debate with Bradley on minority
issues, Sharpton and Gore aides said. A week earlier, Sharpton had
hinted that he would encourage black voters to support Bradley
unless such a debate took place. Gore noted that the campaigns had
already agreed to a debate at the Apollo Theater in Harlem on Feb.
21.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore's events in New York on Sunday marked the beginning of a
week aimed squarely at black voters, who make up one of the party's
most reliable core constituencies. Gore's campaign has always
perceived the black vote as its insurance policy or ``fire wall''
if Gore stumbled in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Gore campaign is making a major pitch to black
voters now, before the collection of primaries on March 7, is a
clear sign of the Gore camp's growing confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule tells much of the story. The vice president is
planning a string of events in heavily black areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   He is to speak about education at Medgar Evars College in
Brooklyn on Monday. On Tuesday in Baltimore, he plans to address
the economic plight of blacks in the information age. That night he
begins a southern swing through North Carolina, Macon, Ga., New
Orleans, Jackson, Miss., St. Louis, Cleveland and Springfield,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., is to travel with Gore in the
state on Monday and endorse him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
