<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE PARIAH OF EUROPE, AUSTRIA SEEMS UNBOWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: INSERTS new graf that begins ``Smaller demonstrations ...''
DELETES 1st sentence of graf that follows.) 
(lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ As a political entity turned pack of would-be
toughs, Europe is proving unimpressive; it is slapping Austria
around a bit, but is unable to bring it to its diplomatic knees.
</P>
<P>
   France, Belgium and tiny Andorra boycotted a speech here last
Thursday by the new Austrian foreign minister. But they stayed to
take part in the meeting of the Organization for Cooperation and
Security in Europe that she was presiding over.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Austria's new social affairs minister was allowed
to attend a meeting in Lisbon on unemployment. But only the host
would shake her hand, and the others refused to pose for the usual
ministerial family photo.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the German minister seemed to regret his rudeness; the
Belgian and French ministers, who also walked out during her
speech, reveled in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative caucus in the European Parliament heard a
motion to kick out Austria's People's Party for inviting Joerg
Haider's Freedom Party into government with it. But members said
the motion would not be voted on until April and had no chance of
passing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles postponed a planned summer visit, and the actress
Claudia Cardinale said she would not attend the Opera Ball, the
height of the Vienna social season. But Queen Beatrix of the
Netherlands took her annual Austrian skiing vacation as she has for
the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium theatrically canceled an order for seven Austrian
armored cars. But Sweden said it still hoped to sell Austria a
squadron of fighter-bombers.
</P>
<P>
   And the French finance minister, a socialist, may have split the
diplomatic hair of the week when he discovered that his Austrian
counterpart is from Haider's party. ``I'm not sure I'll be talking
much with him,'' the minister told journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is in a quandary. Fourteen of the Continent's foreign
ministers threatened to isolate Austria if it let Haider's
xenophobic party into government. Austria promptly called its
bluff. Now Europe is divided and confused and falling back largely
on bad manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unprecedented situation, and there is no uniform
front,'' said Hans Rauscher, a columnist for Der Standard here.
``It's not a massive, concerted action, but it's pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe is not alone in having divided reactions. Israel's
ambassador, the first to leave, is still gone. The U.S. ambassador
returned this past weekend after the State Department tentatively
accepted assurances that Austria would hew to the democratic path.
</P>
<P>
   But the Argentine ambassador was just recalled to Buenos Aires
for consultations after a letter he wrote last October describing
Haider as neither ``an extremist nor a neo-Nazi'' but rather ``a
democrat'' was leaked to an Argentine paper.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has predicted that any censure effort would quickly
crumble. He may be proved right. It isn't just smaller European
countries like Greece and Denmark that are already skeptical. Even
the big powers are subdividing: in Germany, Bavaria broke with
Berlin over isolating its Alpine neighbor, and Italy's provinces
around Trieste, abutting Austria, criticized Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the union has discovered that it needs stability more than
it needs to punish. After the euro slipped last week on rumors that
Austria might be forced out of the monetary union, the European
Union issued a hasty denial that it would impose such a harsh
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   And the fight has strengthened anti-Europe forces. Isolationist
groups in Switzerland and Denmark have gained ground in opinion
polls, citing anger at the drubbing of Austria. Britain's anti-euro
conservatives are crowing their we-told-you-sos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to see how the EU can now get out of the hole that
its leaders have dug,'' Peter Ludlow, the director of the Center
for European Policy Studies in Brussels, Belgium, wrote in a
scathing essay in Britain's Financial Times last week.
</P>
<P>
   By aggressive posturing, the other European countries ``exposed
themselves to the risk of a series of humiliating and very public
compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the predicament is systemic: The union is bound by
treaties, not a constitution, and its important decisions, like
those on a common currency or admitting new members, are made by
consensus. It is not a congress, and cannot freeze out or vote down
members. Ministers meet in order to talk.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem is haste. Austria called Europe's bluff so
fast that there was no time to plan a response. With careful
timing, European ministers might have embarrassed Haider over
weaknesses newly revealed: One of his new Cabinet ministers is
accused of bankrolling a right-wing paper that denied the
Holocaust; another once supposedly said that any businesses that
hire more than 10 percent foreigners should not get government
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Europeans ended up snubbing Elisabeth Sickl, the
new social affairs minister, a friendly middle-aged former school
principal who says her values are ``humanist.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the foreign media, which for weeks whipped up images
of Nazism in Austria, are beginning to turn around and suggest that
someone was indulging in hyperbole. For example, the same BBC radio
anchorman who on Feb. 1 asked an Austrian theater director if he
planned to flee the country (the answer was a puzzled ``no'') by
Feb. 10 was asking a European Union spokesman if his organization
had been in the grip of anti-Nazi hysteria (the answer was a
defensive ``no'').
</P>
<P>
   Within Austria itself, protests against the new government,
which were buoyed by the European Union response, continue,
although with less vigor than in the first days. About 15,000
demonstrators shouting ``Resist racism and fascism!'' marched in
Vienna on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller demonstrations were held in cities throughout the
country. On Sunday a discussion at Vienna's main theater about
artistic freedom under the new government was packed an hour before
it even started.
</P>
<P>
   A march that may be swelled by the trade union allies of the
Social Democratic Party, which was forced into opposition by the
new ruling coalition, is planned for Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see what happens when Haider defies
the advice of his party and goes to Brussels on Feb. 17. As
governor of Carinthia province, he is on the European Union
committee on regional government.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers urged him to miss the meeting. But Haider answered
them last week with his characteristic mix of cheek and love of the
limelight: ``I'm not going to cancel my trip just because someone
wants to hit me with a tomato.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-00 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
