A5806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     02-13 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN NBA ROOKIE TRIES TO REMAKE HIS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Steve Francis stood in one of the busiest
corridors of the All-Star Game weekend on Saturday afternoon. This
was the lobby of The Arena in Oakland, a control center where all
the stars and entourages entered.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' day had begun at 6 a.m., when he left his hotel to
attend an event for the NBA's Team-Up, a community involvement
program. Francis, the Houston Rockets point guard who was not even
on an All-Star team, taped a cable-television program and talked to
children. Afterward he signed autographs and spoke with members of
the audience. Then he went over to the arena to get ready for
Saturday afternoon's rookie challenge featuring the top NBA rookies
against the best second-year players.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was exhausted by halftime of that game. He wound up
playing 28 minutes, scoring 13 points and handing out 11 assists in
a 92-83 overtime victory for the 2000 rookies.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. After a national-television interview, Francis
participated in the 2Ball competition, in which he and Cynthia
Cooper of the WNBA's Houston Comets lost in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he doing this? Marketing. ``I just want to set my own
type of trend,'' Francis said. ``I want to take the game and also
marketing to another level. That's my goal. That's one of my
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the plan? ``It's baby steps first,'' he said. ``You got
to crawl before you walk, so I'm doing all the rookie stuff I
possibly can do so next year I can get more consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a touch of atonement in Francis' method.
</P>
<P>
   Francis committed his first turnover before he played an NBA
game. On draft day last June, while everyone else was celebrating
the dream of the draft, Francis was visibly disappointed over being
selected by Vancouver with the No. 2 pick after his junior season
at Maryland. The Grizzlies had drafted Mike Bibby, another point
guard, a year earlier. Francis forced a trade to Houston and
quickly became cast as part of the spoiled player syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a clear explanation,'' Francis said. ``I had no way to
excel at point guard at Vancouver with Mike Bibby there. There's no
way. He's the same age as me; he's talented, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to Saturday night and the slam-dunk contest.
Francis flung off the fatigue. Like an exhausted fighter still
confident he could end the fight with one punch, the 6-foot-3-inch
Francis issued a promise. ``I'm going to win that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not this night. Vince Carter, last year's rookie phenomenon, won
the contest with a pair of riveting dunks that brought down the
house. Francis said that he thought he had won _ he finished second
_ but that the contest didn't tarnish his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year nobody would have ever thought
that I would average as many points and assists as I do,'' said
Francis, who is averaging 17.8 points and 7.0 assists. ``They
thought that I'd be a crybaby because of the Vancouver thing. But I
think I've done a great job of overcoming that and striving forward
and trying to be an All-Star next year.''
</P>
<P>
   This was billed as the first All-Star Game of the millennium,
and the theme has been the new replacing the old. But Nate
Thurmond, the former Warriors center and an assistant coach for
Francis' winning rookie team on Saturday, said the young players
were being misread and miscast. ``This new group is beautiful,'' he
said. ``You hear so much about, `This guy doesn't want to do that,
this guy does want to do that.' I didn't see that, I saw guys who
came in and wanted to have fun,'' and did what the coaches asked
and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very nice at practice, very grounded,'' Thurmond
said. ``All the media attention, all of the people trying to get to
them, you can understand that it's a big world for them.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered what pressure Thurmond faced when he was drafted in
1963. ``There was no pressure,'' he said. ``I was making $16,000;
my brother was a schoolteacher. He was making $8,000. I called him
up and I said, `Brother, I make twice as much as you.' So what? My
brother retired at $65,000 _ do you think I was making $130,000 a
year when I retired? I was making twice as much as a schoolteacher,
and I was the third guy drafted in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not making money. They're making money now. Today, my
brother would be making $65,000 and I'd be making $10 million. Has
it changed, or has it changed?''
</P>
<P>
   Francis said yes and no. For all the talk about technology this
All-Star Game weekend, all the talk about the race to become the
face of the NBA, Francis said the building blocks for success were
timeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to perform; everything starts on the court,'' he
said. ``The marketing will come from that. Maybe it'll come, maybe
it won't, but I have to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis will turn 23 next week. He has his career in front of
him. For now, he said all he wanted to do was get back home. And
rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
