<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 02/13/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- NEWYORKER-CARTOONS-3 -- Ed
Koren, right, with the writer Mark Singer and Singer's son at the
New Yorker exhibit at Davis &AMP; Langdale. The cartoonists who looked
back at the magazine's history were hardly misty-eyed. At the
reception and in private interviews, they smoldered and wondered at
the changes they had seen. (Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- NEWYORKER-CARTOONS-2 -- Roz
Chast, a New Yorker artist since in 1978, with her daughter Nina at
the New Yorker exhibit at Davis &AMP; Langdale. ``When people look
back, they say cartoons aren't as funny today,'' says Chast, who
specializes in drawing homely types with odd domestic obsessions.
(Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- NEWYORKER-CARTOONS-1 --
Jules Feiffer with his daughter Julie at the New Yorker exhibit at
Davis &AMP; Langdale. The exhibition was no insurrection, but protest
was in the air. At the reception and in private interviews, the
cartoonists smoldered and wondered at the changes they had seen.
(Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- DOG-WESTMINSTER -- Ch.
Tryst of Grandeur, a black Afghan hound who won best of breed at
the Westminster show in 1996, is returning after a two-year
absence. During her professional hiatus, Tryst, as the Afghan is
known, lived at the Mill Neck, N.Y., home of her owner, gave birth
to two litters and rested on her estimable reputation as the
winningest hound ever. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LATHAM, N.Y. -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- MILITARY-ANTITERROR-2
-- Sgt. Peter C. Nestor, left, and Spc. Brian A. Gordon preparing
to enter a a gymnasium in Latham during a simulated terrorism
attack which presumes the presence of nerve gas and anthrax. The
22-member anti-terrorism team is part of a newly formed cadre of
full-time specialists created to help local police departments and
firefighters after a chemical, biological or radioactive attack.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LATHAM, N.Y. -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- MILITARY-ANTITERROR-1
-- Members of a new counterterrorism unit wash Spc. Brian A.
Gordon, who plays the victim of nerve gas in a simulated attack on
a Latham gymnasium. The Pentagon is forming 27 of these groups,
called Weapons of Mass Destruction Civilian Support Teams, which
fall under the command of the state National Guards and are
assigned to zones established by the Federal Emergency Management
Agency. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- MILITARY-GAYS --
Maj. James Garrett explaining to his audience of 48 commissioned
and noncommissioned officers at Fort Campbell the practical
applications of the military's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
``Going to a gay bar, having a gay roommate off base, marching in a
gay parade, that's associational behavior,'' he says. ``That is not
against the policy.'' (Christopher Berkey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CHICAGO -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- MUSEUMS-AND-MONEY -- James
Cuno, director of the Harvard University Art Museums, at Saturday's
session in Chicago. Nearly 400 academics, arts administrators,
students and others convened here to examine the relationship
between the arts and society in the wake of the the exhibition of
cutting-edge British art owned by the collector Charles Saatchi,
``Sensation,'' which ended up pitting Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in
court against the Brooklyn Museum of Art. (Steve Kagan/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN -- Archie
van Bueuren, president of Godiva chocolates, sits among Valentines
Day boxes of his company's product in his Manhattan office last
week. Godiva has turned to online marketers of gift certificates to
bolster sales. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDON -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- VIRGIN-INTERNET -- Richard
Branson at home i a characteristic pose. Fingering the buttons, at
left, on one of his mobile phones, he acknowledges more optimism
and business confidence than technological savvy. ``I was one of
those anti-mobile phone guys before we did Virgin Mobile,'' he
explains, referring to the cellular phone service that he started
in November and that has already signed up 300,000 subscribers.
(Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- LEBANON-GUERRILLAS
-- Hussein al-Khalil, a key figure in Hezbollah, the Shiite Muslim
organization that has waged a three-week offensive against Israeli
forces in Lebanon, being interviewed by reporters Saturday evening.
``As long as there are Israeli forces in southern Lebanon, our
resistance will continue,'' vows al-Khalil. (Courtney Kealy/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 13, 2000 --
KOSOVO-UNREST-2 -- French troops taking up position in Northern
Mitrovice to enforce a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew Sunday. French
troops killed an Albanian gunman during fierce fighting in the
streets of this bitterly divided town Sunday in the most sustained
clashes involving peacekeeping troops since they arrived in Kosovo
eight months ago. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 13, 2000 --
KOSOVO-UNREST-1 -- British troops evacuating an Albanian family
from the northern area of Mitrovica after a grenade attack and
heavy fighting erupted there Sunday. French troops killed an
Albanian gunman during fierce fighting in the streets of this
bitterly divided town Sunday in the most sustained clashes
involving peacekeeping troops since they arrived in Kosovo eight
months ago. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- PHONE-AT&AMP;T-B&AMP;W -- Barely a
year after joining AT&AMP;T, H. Eugene Lockhart, president of the
company's core consumer unit, intends to step down, executives
close to the company said Sunday. An announcement of Lockhart's
departure is expected Monday, the executives said. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- MOSER-PROFILE -- Peter
Moser, Austria's ambassador to the United States, in his office in
Washington. ``This is a nightmare,'' he says of the flack a new
Austrian government that includes the far-right, anti-immigration
Freedom Party led by Joerg Haider - who has praised some of
Hitler's employment policies - has engendered. ``You think of the
job of a diplomat as a dream under usual circumstances. Well, what
is going on now is the reverse. It is surreal.'' (Paul Hosefros/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING --
Maureen Howard is her own ``first and most unforgiving audience.''
``Writing fiction is not about first love, that blush of self-love
when you discover your name in print,'' she explains. ``It's about
passion and endurance, a combination of desire and grunt work often
at odds with each other.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- PHILLY-VALENTINE-2 --
Christopher Duffner, 8, checking out the right ventricle of the
giant heart at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia. Though this
science exhibit was intended to teach schoolchildren about the
circulatory system, it has turned out to be one of the most
romantic places in Philadelphia. (Timothy M. Shaffer/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PHILADELPHIA -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- PHILLY-VALENTINE-1 --
Jim Seiple and Stephanie Cahill celebrating Valentine's Day early
with a Thursday visit to the giant heart at the Franklin Institute
in Philadelphia. ``What better thing to see than the big heart?''
asks Seiple, 21. Who needs expensive, candlelit restaurants? One of
the most romantic places in Philadelphia turns out to be a science
exhibit intended to teach schoolchildren about the circulatory
system. (Timothy M. Shaffer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) TROY, N.Y. -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- PATENTS -- Tahira Reid, a
senior at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, patented the
double-dutch jump-rope machine, which she first thought up when she
was in third grade. The machine consists of two drive systems that
sit 10 to 15 feet apart and about 30 inches off the ground. Each
drive system has its own motor, which, through the help of a set of
pulleys, turns two arms that grasp two different ropes. (David
Jennings/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- OBIT-LANDRY-4-B&AMP;W -- From
left: New York Giants Kyle Rote, Fred Benners and Tom Landry, in
1952. Landry, the taciturn Texan who coached the Dallas Cowboys for
their first 29 seasons and led them to five Super Bowls, died
Saturday night in Dallas at Baylor University Medical Center, where
since May he had periodically undergone treatment for acute
myelogenous leukemia. He was 75. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DALLAS -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- OBIT-LANDRY-3-B&AMP;W -- Dallas
Cowboys coach Tom Landry in a 1964 publicity photo. Landry, the
taciturn Texan who coached the Cowboys for their first 29 seasons
and led them to five Super Bowls, died Saturday night in Dallas at
Baylor University Medical Center, where since May he had
periodically undergone treatment for acute myelogenous leukemia. He
was 75. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MINNEAPOLIS -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- OBIT-LANDRY-2-B&AMP;W --
Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry and quarterback Roger Staubach on
the sideline during a 1978 game against the Minnesota Vikings.
Landry, the taciturn Texan who coached the Cowboys for their first
29 seasons and led them to five Super Bowls, died Saturday night in
Dallas at Baylor University Medical Center, where since May he had
periodically undergone treatment for acute myelogenous leukemia. He
was 75. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MINNEAPOLIS -- Feb. 13, 2000 -- OBIT-LANDRY-1-B&AMP;W --
Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry and quarterback Roger Staubach
(No.12) on the sideline during a 1978 game against the Minnesota
Vikings. Landry, the taciturn Texan who coached the Cowboys for
their first 29 seasons and led them to five Super Bowls, died
