<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BLOWS CHANCE FOR UPSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ They came all this way to come so close. In the
end, that's what hurt the most.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was fourth-ranked Syracuse. Yes, it was in the Carrier
Dome, in front of the largest on-campus crowd in the nation this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Playing their fourth game in nine days, the
Orangemen were there for the peeling. This was a game the UCLA
Bruins could have won, and that would have made their cross-country
trek much more fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was there for us to take and we didn't take it,''
Bruins guard Ryan Bailey said after a 71-67 loss Sunday afternoon
before a crowd of 29,731 in the Carrier Dome. ``That's the toughest
kind to deal with. Sometimes, you have an off night and you lose by
18. Those things happen. But the games you know you should win are
the toughest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played passive but effective defense. They were
organized on offense. Their shot selection was solid. They
outrebounded Syracuse 42-32. They moved the ball well (21 assists
on 28 baskets) and they quieted the massive crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 minutes, in fact, the Bruins played one of their best
games of the season. The problem was the last five minutes, when
the Bruins wasted several chances to steal a victory that would
have done wonders for their NCAA Tournament chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts so bad because they're the No. 4 team in the country
and we were better than them for 35 minutes,'' Bruins forward Rico
Hines said. ``They beat us in the last five minutes and we beat
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Shown to 75 percent of the nation, the game was more audition
than competition for UCLA (13-9). No doubt, NCAA tournament
selection committee members were watching on couches from coast to
coast. A win might have helped the Bruins snatch an at-large bid if
they finish with 17 victories or a sub-.500 conference record.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they lost the game and they lost their slack. The
remaining task is simple but difficult: Win five of eight games to
finish 18-12 and they're in. Anything less and it's probably NIT
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to perform well in the conference to make a
statement to the (selection committee),'' said Bruins coach Steve
Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's locker room was quiet but not demoralized. The players
refused to claim a moral victory _ ``It's W's and L's and no
in-between,''guard Earl Watson said _ but they couldn't ignore
several important developments.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's second consecutive start added rhythm and flow to the
offense. He finished with seven rebounds, seven assists and one
turnover. His precision passes against Syracuse's soft zone helped
the Bruins shoot 51.8 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Hines and Ray Young combined to make 7 of 8 shots, score 14
points and give UCLA its best bench play of the month. Hines was
his usual savvy self. Young, slowing emerging after a four-game
skid, showed betterjudgment than he has in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, slumping center Dan Gadzuric played his most
effective game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric overcame tender thumbs and knees to score 18 points,
grab 12 rebounds, avoid foul trouble and outplay Syracuse's All-Big
East center, Etan Thomas (nine points and seven rebounds). If
Gadzuric repeats his performance Thursday at Arizona State, the
Bruins just might get the road victory they need to return to an
18-win pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm posting up harder and playing harder,'' Gadzuric said.
``Every day, I'm getting a little more confident, since I'm still
raw.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Bruins needed was an average game from forward Jerome
Moiso and they'd have departed with smiles, not snarls. But Moiso
played as poorly as Gadzuric played well. He committed four
turnovers, made 3 of 9 shots and failed to attack the basket. He
made bad passes, lost the ball in traffic and settled for fadeaways
when he should have powered for dunks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some turnovers in the first half and I got down on
myself,'' Moiso said quietly in the far corner of the locker room.
``I felt like I was losing the ball every time I touched it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fault was not Moiso's alone. Far from it. The Bruins had two
chances to take the lead midway through the second half; each time,
reserve guard Billy Knight took (and missed) bad shots.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final 6:44 _ when the Bruins failed to score on seven
of 10 possessions _ there were breakdowns everywhere. Jason Kapono
missed a wild shot in the lane. Moiso committed a turnover.
Gadzuric missed two free throws. Yet Syracuse could not pull away.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins trailed 67-65 with two minutes left when Kapono
botched an alley-oop pass to Moiso. On UCLA's next possession,
Thomas blocked Moiso's weak jumper.
</P>
<P>
   More breakdowns followed. Syracuse led 70-67 with 9.7 seconds
left when Ryan Blackwell missed a free throw, but Thomas outhustled
Gadzuric and Young to the rebound. After another Syracuse free
throw, Watson lost the ball as he began a desperate dash downcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to us not getting rebounds, or turning the ball
over or forcing shots,'' Watson said. ``We were patient until we
had a chance to break through, then we rushed things. We had our
chances. We didn't capitalize on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
