<SLUG> BC-TELIGENT-MANNESMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELIGENT IS SAID TO FORGE LINK TO MANNESMANN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expanding its presence in the fast-changing European
communications market, the American company Teligent Inc., a leader
in providing high-capacity communications links using wireless
technology, intends to announce Monday that it has formed a
partnership with a unit of Mannesmann of Germany, executives close
to the deal said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For Mannesmann, the deal with Teligent follows the agreement
reached earlier this month in which Mannesmann would be acquired
for $183 billion by Vodafone AirTouch PLC of Britain, the world's
largest wireless telephone carrier. The executives said the
Teligent partnership would be inherited by Vodafone AirTouch if the
merger is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Teligent, which is led by Alex J. Mandl, a former president of
AT&AMP;T, is one of the leaders in the United States in delivering
telephone, video and high-speed Internet services using advanced
wireless technology between buildings and other fixed points. The
largest shareholder in Teligent is the Liberty Media Group, the
television programming operation controlled by John C. Malone, the
cable television executive. Teligent's stock is up some 30 percent
so far this year, though it dipped during the technology-stock
sell-off late last week, closing at $80.50 on Friday, down $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   In competition with Winstar Communications Inc., Teligent is
trying to deploy its wireless systems on thousands of office
buildings in the United States. Now, European nations are
auctioning big swaths of wireless spectrum, opening a similar new
market.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Teligent won 36 spectrum licenses in Germany. In the
deal to be announced Monday, Teligent will combine those licenses
with those of Mannesmann Arcor, a Mannesmann subsidiary. The
companies intend to form a joint venture to exploit their combined
licenses and also to bid for additional spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Among Teligent's competitors in Europe is a start-up company
based in New York City called Firstmark Communications
International. Firstmark recently announced the formation of a
joint venture in France with Suez-Lyonnaise des Eaux, Groupe
Arnault, Rallye Casino, BNP Paribas and the Francarep unit of the
Rothschild Group.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Teligent declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
