<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAGAT-EXPANSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAGAT SURVEY GETS INVESTMENT FOR EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Tim and Nina Zagat began publishing their eponymous
restaurant guides in 1979, the couple's company, Zagat Survey, has
refused all outside investors.
</P>
<P>
   That is set to change Monday. Tapping additional capital in a
bid to expand into cyberspace and the wireless ether, Zagat intends
to announce that it has sold a $31 million equity stake to a group
that includes some of the digital economy's most prominent
individuals and institutional investors, Zagat said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Zagat now sells millions of restaurant and hotel guides covering
about 45 cities. The guides' trademark is a reliance on the
opinions of everyday people who volunteer contributions, rather
than on professional reviewers. The company now is moving onto the
Web and into the wireless arena not only to canvass contributors
but also to distribute its information.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a wireless system now in place in Japan that he hopes
will move to the United States, Zagat said Sunday: ``You push a
button on the phone and it shows the five restaurants closest to
you, with our ratings. Then you push the button and you see our
review. You push again and its tells you how to get there with our
map. Then you click on the phone number and it connects you on the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial details were unclear Sunday, but people close to the
deal said the agreement valued Zagat at more than $100 million,
meaning that at least two-thirds of the company would remain in the
couple's control.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group is led by General Atlantic Partners, a
private investment firm based in Greenwich, Conn. William Ford, a
General Atlantic partner, will join Zagat's board.
</P>
<P>
   The other institutional investors are Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield
&AMP; Byers, one of Silicon Valley's best-known venture capital
operations, and Allen &AMP; Co., the media investor and adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Myhrvold, a founder of Microsoft and enthusiastic
gastronome, will also invest, as will Nicholas Negroponte, director
of the media laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and Nancy Peretsman, an investment banker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
