<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGAPAD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOCH'S WAIT IS FOR NAUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY _ While her colleagues were trying to avoid sinking
in the still-flooded fairways, Carin Koch was drying off in the
Wood Ranch Golf Club clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Victory was still a realistic possibility for Koch, winless in
five previous years on the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about (winning) because anything can happen,''
Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   Anything didn't happen to Laura Davies, who survived another day
of miserable weather to win the Los Angeles Women's Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, who started her round almost an hour ahead of Davies'
group, shot a 2-under 70 and stood at 2-under for the tournament.
About that same time, Davies was barely maintaining her lead by a
stroke over, among others, Koch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got finished, I saw that Laura had made bogey (on 14)
and gone down to 3 (under), so I didn't know what was going to
happen,'' said Koch, whose effort bettered the final rounds of
Davies (73), Michele Redman (72) and Janice Moodie (72). The latter
two shared second place with Koch.
</P>
<P>
   An already drenched course that caused severe trauma to much of
the field gave Koch hope she was low enough to get into a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always think someone will come through,'' Davies said.
``The most worrisome thing was Carin coming in at 2-under. Once
someone posts, you begin to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies eliminated any drama with birdies on 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wet under the collar: Davies braved the steady drizzle
throughout the day without using an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old native of Coventry, England, doesn't believe in
protecting herself from the elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be a wet rat than a cold-handed rat who stays
dry,'' Davies said. ``I'd rather my hands be warm.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ace in the hole: For all of the problems the leaders
encountered Sunday, Sherri Turner conquered the par-3 seventh hole.
The 43-year-old hit her 7-iron 143 yards for a hole-in-one.
</P>
<P>
   Turner shot a 73 and finshed at 223 for the tournament, 13 shots
behind Davies.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth ace of her career came on the wrong hole, however. Had
she accomplished the feat on 13, she would have won a new car.
</P>
<P>
   __ Local results: Studio City's Emilee Klein shot a 1-over 73
and finished in a four-way tie for 20th at 219.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who finished eighth at her previous tounament in Naples,
Fla., is 20th on the LPGA money list, earning $29,608 for three
tournaments. The Notre Dame High of Sherman Oaks graduate finished
1999 in the 23rd spot.
</P>
<P>
   Kristal Parker (UCLA) was tied for 14th at 218; Jenny Rosales
(USC) shared 43rd with a 223; Debbi Koyama (UCLA) was 58th at 223.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
